\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 Of my family?  It\rquote s very patchy.  Very patchy indeed.  Talking to my father \endash  my father\rquote s side \endash 
 my father said that he was from one of the neighbouring Parishes called Manchester, it was named after Lord Manchester.  And he - as you know, a lot of Caribbean families, Jamaican families in particular, are very c
olour distributive, and most of the Goulbournes were sort of brown to white, white to brown.  But my father\rquote s father\rquote s father, so it\rquote s going three back, was on the dark side, and he felt he was very discriminated against \endash 
 this is my father\rquote s story.  He, therefore, left Manchester, and into the hills, into the mountains of Clarendon, and bought himself some land when some of the big plantations were being split up and sold off to small settlers.  And so there
\rquote s still the case today that, in Jamaica, I sometimes come across folks who are named the same as myself \endash  which is an unusual name \endash 
 and obviously are related, and the myth goes back to Manchester, and they are brown to white.  Whereas us, in the Clarendon hills, [the Goulbournes] are black.  There is a
lso a line, which we have come across in Kingston, who are more South Asian, who look typically South Asian, and who are also related.  Then when my father was dying, and we had a lot of sessions of talking together, he mentioned a couple of other familie
s who are related to us, and some of those names don\rquote t mean a thing to me at all.  And I think this is part of the story of migration \endash  you get cut off as you go along the line, from relatives, etc..  So that\rquote s on my father\rquote 
s side.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 
