\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 Into Clarendon.  That would have been late 19}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\super\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 th}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796  century, I would have thought, because my father was born in 1911, and my mother in 1914.  So he\rquote s talking very much of the well, not turbulent, adventurous, I 
suppose, looking back now, years of the post-slavery period.  So if you imagine slavery was abolished in 1840, in Jamaica, in particular, with a lot of Crown lands in the hills, slaves are moving from the low-lying areas to buy land, or to squat on land i
n the hills, where the plantation economy had not taken force, because it\rquote 
s not so adaptable to plantations, and it was still owned by the Crown.  The Missionary forces, like the Baptists and so on, are assisting a lot of free people to buy land or, in some cases, squatting land.  I suppose it\rquote 
s part of that large movement.  Obviously my father wasn\rquote t able to explain it to me in those terms, but what he knew, very much, was the urge to own land, and that his grandfather had moved up into the hills, acquired 
some land, and was one of the first set of people to have done that.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 
