\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 And once he got that land, that would be treated as family land, or as just land that he owned, do you think?
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri113\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin113\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11870632 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid6571465\charrsid6571465 Harry:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 Well, it would have been, once he established his family there
, it would become family land, in the sense that the law of primogeniture would not apply.  So, obviously, it gets more and more fragmented.  More and more fragmented, like in Ireland, or other places.  I was in Goa recently, and talking to some people th
ere about the fragmentation of land, because there\rquote s no law of primogeniture, similarly to that situation in Jamaica.  And so what we would now, in Jamaica, consider to be family land, is really where my grandparents \endash 
 my paternal grandparents \endash  are buried,
 and some of their children who died very young, some uncles, some aunts.  My last paternal uncle lives on, with his children, and some relatives from another uncle who lives nearby.  But the land has got smaller and smaller and smaller, you know!  (LAUGH
S)  Eventually it will end up just as a graveyard!  (LAUGHS)  Because it has just contracted and contracted.  So when I\rquote m visiting there, or any of my siblings, they\rquote ll go there to see grounds, as they call \'93grounds\'94
, the burial grounds, because it is family land.  Technically, I suppose, in terms of custom, any of us could go there and claim, \'93Look, I\rquote ve nowhere to sleep.  I\rquote m sleeping here tonight\'94
.  And that will be the case!  No one would question that.  But obviously, if you were to stay, it would lead to conflict and all the rest of it, would it not, because there\rquote s a limited space.  But in that sense, it is family land, and that\rquote 
s important in a lot of ways.  But then family land, in terms of customary culture, would mean also where I was born, where m
y father bought his own land, and where most of us were born, on that spot, that spot of land would also have been regarded as family land.  \tab But the tradition was broken when \endash 
 through migration.  When my parents came here, then [later] they returned to J
amaica, most of us scattered around the place, but my eldest sister, and one of my brothers, went back with them and stayed with them.  They felt it was their duty to be there, etc..  They exploited my parents too, and all the rest of it.  But they stayed
 
there.  So in writing up their Wills, my father had quite a number of pieces of different lands and houses in Kingston and so on.  What he decided to do was to give [the land] where nearly all of us were born, all but one, to give that piece of land to hi
s first child \endash  my eldest sister.  That was, I think, an acreage of 3+ acres, which is, in terms of plantation and land-holding in Britain, is neither here nor there, but in the mountains, a lot of land!  (LAUGHS)  It\rquote 
s very cultivatable, it is very rich, you know, it grows coffee \endash  you name the products, it would take it.  But she then sold it off.  But on that plot of land, most of us would have had what we call \endash  in that part of the country \endash  
\'93navel trees\'94.  I don\rquote t know if you\rquote ve ever come across the navel tree?
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 
