\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 So they actually do that once you\rquote ve got old enough to remember.  What sort of age, then?
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri113\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin113\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11870632 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid6571465\charrsid6571465 Harry:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 I can\rquote 
t remember, I must have been three, four, five.  And so, you know, all of us had our own trees in our plot, and that was your link to the place, as your family, etc., etc., your responsibility.  I sometimes use that to illustrate the notion of patrioti
sm in writings of nationalism, because it relates to a friend of mine, if I might say this, in Franche Comt\'e9 in France, where we were talking about such matters.  He\rquote 
s a diehard French Nationalist character, and he was saying, in part of France, on the borders with Switzerland, that until Louis XIV took it over in the 17}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\super\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 th}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 
 century, that people in that part of France saw themselves very much as part of what we would, today, regard as Switzerland.  And it is still the practice there that when a male dies, the
 idea is that that person is buried with their face down in the grave, because the story is, no person from that region wants a Frenchman to walk on their face!  (LAUGHS)  So I think, \'93
Well, this sounds very much like this notion of having your own plot, you\rquote re buried into the soil\'94.  And it\rquote s this notion of patriotism isn\rquote t it?  We might look at Franche Comt\'e9
 as just being another part of France, but as far as the people around there are concerned, they are not French. Similarly in Jamaica, it\rquote s not throughout the country, it seems to have been \endash  I\rquote ve never studied it properly \endash 
 but it seemed to be one of what Herman Herskovits called \'93retentions\'94 - retentions from the African past.  In 1970, as an undergraduate, I hitchhiked in West Africa, partly because 
I wanted to feel West Africa, to know what it was like, and found that a number of these practices were actually from there, and that\rquote s certainly one of them.  Whether it\rquote s continued or not, I have no idea.  Whether it\rquote 
s still alive in the Clarendon Mountains, I have no idea.  I\rquote ve spoken to other people from other parts of the Caribbean, and they have mentioned a similar practice, so it\rquote 
s obviously much wider, and obviously got distributed through the experience of slavery.  So, going back to the notion of family land, that is part of that.  So it\rquote 
s not that there would be one piece of land and it would run throughout time as being that, because being no law of primogeniture, it would become distributed.  So my father, then, would have started, so to speak,
 his own family land.  And his great dream was that we\rquote 
d all live there at some point or the other!  Which is, of course, impractical!  (LAUGHS)  And he, himself, when he returned to Jamaica, went to live not in Clarendon, but in Kingston.  Of course, in Kingston, there is no such tradition.  It\rquote 
