\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 Oh yes.  Oh yes.  In my family, the person who ran the money entirely, was my mother!  (LAUGHS)  You know, I\rquote ve often said that the two most intelligent, sharpest minds that I\rquote 
ve ever come across, in my whole life, were two people \endash  my mother, and my eldes
t brother, George.  They are, you might say semi-literate, they left school very early.  But if want to have a really thorough discussion about international relations, and I\rquote 
m in Kingston, I can have this with my brother George, as well as a number of pro
fessors at UWI, and his perception will be sharper than theirs!  (LAUGHS)  My mother, in terms of just human intelligence, was a superb person.  In terms of arithmetic, in particular, you could throw any amount of numbers at her and ask her for the conclu
s
ion, and within a matter of minutes or seconds, you would have them.  In buying and selling she used to say - she took her scales with her, because each of these sellers would have their scales, but that she could put them in her hands, throw them up, and
 
tell the buyer what the weights are, and if they want to test it, they could test on the scale, and it would be exact!  (LAUGHS)  And that is quite incredible!  (LAUGHS)  She was a very very sharp leader of people.  When my mother died, in this country, y
e
ars later, and we took her body back to Kingston, I was overwhelmed by the amount of people who turned up from Britain, the United States, and throughout Jamaica, to her funeral, people whom I knew only peripherally.  And she had a profound impact on thos
e.  Now, she ran the family, in terms of investments.  In this country, my parents bought a number of houses, rented them, and in Kingston as well, and a number of lands.  So by the end of their day, they were quite substantially rich, but there\rquote 
s so many of us didn\rquote 
t get anywhere!  (LAUGHS)  But it was always my mother, my father was very cautious, but he always left it to my mother to deal with, and she was always the person who took those decisions.  The only area, in terms of finances, where my father to
ok the decision, was - you might have heard of the system of \'93Jamaican partnerships\'94?  That\rquote 
s nothing to do with sex or companies, you know!  (LAUGHS)  It goes back to the idea of buying of land for the ex-slaves, freed people.  But banks and insurance com
panies, etc., would not invest in people, and particularly in the migration story of coming to Britain, they couldn\rquote 
t go to a Building Society, or to a bank, etc., so they had to depend on their own resources.  And what they did was to re-institute the par
tnership system, whereby - it could be small or large, and it was all a matter of trust.  So there are 20, 15, 50 of us, we contribute, say, \'a35 or \'a310 \endash  and you do it according to your ability \endash 
 to a common fund, and each week, one person would draw a \'93hand\'94, as it\rquote 
s called, and one person would draw all the money. But they continued to contribute throughout, continuously, until each person has had a hand.  You withdraw what you have put in.  So there is no interest, and it\rquote s all done through trust.  Now, f
or that system, for that network, you need one person whom everyone will trust. And, of course, that was my father.  He was the person.  There were several of these going on, and there are several of them where you might interlink across as well.  But it
\rquote s a financial arrangement.  And my father was the centre of a number of these, because people trusted him.  The trust was within himself and my mother, but he was the person who led that and organised that.  And, and that\rquote 
s how they were able to help people who were migrating into the country from Jamaica, help them to buy their first properties, and, of course, their own.
