\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 Well, the advantage is that, you know, say you wanted to b
uy a piece of furniture, or you want to take some money to the bank, to build up towards a mortgage, is that after every couple of months or weeks, you \endash  depending on the size of the partnership \endash 
 you had a good lump of money.  Or sometimes, send for your 
spouse.  I recall a number of young men wanting to send for their spouses, or girl.  Although arranged marriages, in our lifetime, has not been part of Caribbean society as such, but in the migration story, I heard a bit of this, where young men, or young
 women, would come to my parents and sort of say, \'93Look \'85\'94 they remember a girl, or a young man, back home, and could they help to bring that person across?  Sometimes these people came and didn\rquote 
t want to know the person who had paid for them to come!  (LAUGHS)  And so there was always a degree of difficulties involved!  (LAUGHS)  So not only were my parents involved with this financial thing, but also with marriages.  That\rquote 
s why I hate weddings, because, as a child, I was always going to weddings!  (LAUGHS)  You know, it\rquote s not like today, where you\rquote d rent a hall and you\rquote 
d go there.  So the local church down the road, the Baptist Church at the end of Coldharbour Lane, at the Camberwell end, where the formal thing would take place \endash  the ceremony \endash  and then the
y would retreat back to our house for the reception and a party.  And it was, it always struck me as being a very frightful experience.  So when we got married, we didn\rquote 
t get married that way at all!  (LAUGHS)  But again, they were the centre of that.  Because you have to look at it this way, that this was a situation where there was nothing to build on.   There weren\rquote 
t the institutions as they are now, where people could just fit into a situation, so families/individuals had to simply utilise what we would
, today, call their network, and those networks were fairly loose.  So any people whom they saw - my parents were in their mid to late thirties when they came here, so they would have been seen as older folks, and they were highly respected in that sense,
 in terms of the local community, if you can call it a community, that was spread across London.  It\rquote s a savings system, in a trustworthy way.  That\rquote s what it is.  That\rquote s all it is.  That\rquote s all it is.  That\rquote 
s all it is.  But it did mean, also \endash  because there\rquote s no interest \endash 
 it did mean, also, that when needs arose - and we have to get ourselves away from the present situation today.  If you and I have a need today, we just go to the bank and say, \'93Give us some money\'94, and that\rquote s fine.  In those days, it was 
not on, and particularly for migrants without any records of who they are, etc., and the financial system was not what it is now.  So if people had a need, a death somewhere, or a wedding coming up, or something of the kind, they have to pay their rents, 
etc., then that was their succour, that was where they could go to, and say, \'93Look, I have a problem now.  I know my hand is way down the road, but can I have it now?\'94
