s a system of tremendous trust.  But that trust focuses, very much, as I was saying, on the person who is the centre of that.  When I started earning, I seem to remember my brothers and a couple of people said, \'93Should we start one of these?\'94
  And I said, \'93Well, what for?  I don\rquote t need one\'94.  (LAUGHS)  But years and years later, in Jamaica, a very good colleague of ours, who is now a very prominent barrister in Kingston, and obviously didn\rquote 
t need that at all, what he did, he became part of one, and a leader of one \endash  not so much for himself, but for the workers at the University.  He was a lecturer, he was one of these brilliant chaps who had a Double First \endash  a F
irst in History.  He did for two degrees, one in History, had a First.  Did law, had a First.  Went to Oxford, as a Rhodes Scholar, didn\rquote t finish is his doctorate, and, as I say, is a very prominent lawyer today.  Now, it\rquote 
s part of his collective family history, that, way back, his family used to practice that as well, and he was one of these characters very close to working people, they trusted him.  And he started one of these systems \endash 
 for them, largely.  He participated as the head of it, and also contributed.  But, obviously, he could depend on the formal financial system, but he also continued to do that.  And I sometimes felt that perhaps I should have done that, you know.  But it
\rquote s basically, in a situation of poverty and need, a situation where people can fall back on something, purely on the basis of trust.
