\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 My father\rquote s side.  I lived with him
 for a while, and he, at his household, he had two horses, two or three donkeys, a number of cows, and a bull, which served the region, and he planted all the crops that I mentioned, in different patches, and he simply oversaw all of these.  And he had a 
n
umber of people who lived on different patches of his land, and who made a living for themselves.  But like feudalism, later on as I learned in school here, for me coming to England as a child and learning about feudalism, I could see it, because on my un
cle\rquote s land, he\rquote d have these people who were not related by blood, but they were seen as family.  There was always a distance which, as a child, I couldn\rquote t quite understand.  They wouldn\rquote 
t come into the inner part of the household, they were always \'93out there\'94
 somewhere.  But my uncle could call on them to do anything, anything at all, and they would do these things.  They would also use part of his land for themselves, would build small huts for themselves, but basically they were working there for him.  And
 then, of course, when it came to reaping season, where you need to reap crops very quickly - otherwise they rot and you lost them \endash  then he would bring in other people and pay them accordingly.  Then there\rquote s another system, which he didn
\rquote t use so much, a couple of times, but other people would.  And it\rquote s a system called \'93morning sport\'94
, where all the men of the village, of an area, usually on a Saturday morning, get together to do a piece of work.  So that, for example, say we have these trees here to limb, there\rquote s usually things which need to be done quickly.  They\rquote 
ll bring them in, they\rquote ll provide a meal \endash  the women provide a meal \endash  and it\rquote s usually just a morning, say from 6 to about 12, and it would be a blitz, in terms of all the males in the area come
 together to do that piece of work.  There is no payment involved, because it meant that you would do the same, when it was necessary, for others.  And the young men would just come in to help to do that.  So in that sort of rural context, there are diffe
rentiations, but they\rquote re not harsh differentiations, and there\rquote s a very strong notion of community. We\rquote ve just come back from India [Goa], and it\rquote s the village that Selina\rquote s parents are from, it\rquote 
s a very similar situation, and if we have time, I could descr
ibe that, to show the tremendous similarity, in terms of the system that the Portuguese partially established there, and which, up to now, has gone on, but is just about to change because of the impact of the commercialisation of land as a result of touri
sm.  That also, I\rquote m sure, has changed in Jamaica.  What I\rquote m describing here, I feel that if I were to go Jamaica now, there would be people able to relate to it, in terms of talking about this sort of experience in the past, but I\rquote 
m sure it doesn\rquote t exist in the same way any longer.
