Yes, I think that there was that.  As a child, living in that situation, because my parents were here, and because we had lots of uncles and aunts around, all of whom on their own plots of land and so forth, we were seen, alongside a number of other famil
ies who were similar, to be somewhat different from those who didn\rquote 
t own their houses and their land.  We were also different from a group of people who rode on horseback all the time, and owned a substantial amount of land.  I recall two families, for exam
ple.  One who was more white than black, and I never, as a child, I never saw the head of that household, off of horseback.  (LAUGHS)  So, as I child, you thought he and his horse was always wonderful!  And he was always formally upright, with a hat, hard
 
hat, and his bridle, the formal wear for horse-riding.  Whereas with us, as kids learning to ride, I learnt to ride bareback, without any accompaniment at all.  You get on to a horse, and it gallops with you, and you stay on or you fall and break your nec
k
!  I recall when in the sixth form, in London, our headmaster felt that, before you go off to university, you must become gentlemen, and we had to do ballroom dancing, or you could do horse-riding.  I was very shy about doing ballroom dancing with this wo
man who was teaching us, and so I went for horse-riding, and the people who were taking us were very pleased with me, because I took to it naturally, and they thought they had taught me!  I didn\rquote 
t tell them that I'd always known how to ride! (LAUGHS)  It\rquote s like walking, once you can walk, you can always walk.  And similar for riding.  The only difference was that they\rquote 
d given me all this equipment which made it so much easier!  (LAUGHS)  So there were differentiations and there were differences.
