\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 I think they related to them - not in an economic sense, but I think they looked up to them, and that they were their betters.  I\rquote m thinking, now, very much more in terms of my uncle\rquote s fa
mily, who were fairly well-heeled in terms of the wherewithal of things.  There were a couple of our cousins who were school teachers, postmistresses, constables, all of which were very important in that sort of setting.  You look back now, and you realis
e they\rquote re neither here nor there, but in that setting, they were considered important. When I went to school, one of the schools I went to \endash  because I can\rquote t remember a time when I didn\rquote t go to school.  It\rquote 
s like my younger son, Neil, he started going to school, kindergarten, at the age of 23 months, and he can\rquote t think of a time when he couldn\rquote t count, etc., you know, knew his alphabet.  Similarly, I can\rquote t think of a time when I didn
\rquote t, and I think it\rquote s partly because I remember being very distraught that my brothers were going off to school and I wasn\rquote 
t, and then I was sent along with them.  I would have to run behind them, running behind them, and they would run ahead of me and so on, and on one occasion, wetting my pants, because they were so far ahead of m
e!  But as a result of all that, I think that there was never a time I can remember that one couldn\rquote 
t do your alphabet, numbers and so on.  But part of that was because I think, looking back, might have been because some of those teachers in these kinderga
rtens were relatives, and they saw me as a child who wanted to be around other children, particularly my siblings, and why not?  Why not just come along? Like Neil, when he started at this kindergarten in Kingston, at the age of 19 months, we had just mov
ed from Tanzania to Jamaica, and we were looking for a school, a kindergarten, for Hugh, who was then two and a half, and we went to this school, and they only had 80 kids, up to the age of 11, so it\rquote 
s a wide range, from 4 to 11.  And the Headmistress said, \'93What\rquote s happening to Neil?  What do you want to do with him?\'94  And I said, \'93Well, we\rquote 
re looking for a playgroup for him, but all the places we have been too, we, at home, have more toys than in these places, so we\rquote re worried about that\'94.  She said, \'93Well, is he potty-trained?\'94  And we said, \'93Yes, he is potty-trained\'94
.  She said, \'93Well, look, let him just come with his brother, and we\rquote ll have him in the kindergarten class, and when he\rquote s tired \'85\'94  We said, \'93Look, he\rquote s still, you know, in the afternoon, he likes to sleep\'94
, because he was that young.  And she said, \'93Fine\'94, you know, \'93We\rquote ll have a bed here for him.\'94  But, in a sense, my memory of early schooldays is rather like that!  (LAUGHS)  But we digressed.
