\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 That\rquote s right.  And there was one family, in particular, who owned perhaps a lot more land than that, as well as some shops.  And again, they were quite a different group of folks.  I can\rquote 
t recall there being much contacts at all.  They lived and moved in the same world, but I can\rquote 
t recall that there was a great deal of contact between those sort of people and us.  What I can recall also, however, is that with migration, people who had migrated \endash  like my parents \endash 
 I had an uncle who had migrated, much earlier, to Cuba.  And the story I remember of him was a story that he\rquote s a rich man.  Whether he was rich or not, I don\rquote t know!  (LAUGHS)  I don\rquote t think he could have been, actually!  (LAUGHS
)  But he had been to Cuba, and apparently, when he was very angry, he would swear in Spanish!  (LAUGHS)  And that was a real mystery!  (LAUGHS)  He lived in a big house, a huge house, with quite a bit of land, and his house had an upstairs, which was qui
te something to have, on two floors.  But the person who, in our area \endash  Spalding, Ritches \endash 
 was considered to be really rich, was a man called Percy Junior, who was a big figure in Jamaican history.  My father used to tell me the story that Percy Junior was
 the first millionaire in that area, that he started life, however, with a crocus bag on his back, buying coffee from people like my father\rquote 
s father, and it was through his efforts and, you know, sheer hard work, that he eventually became this entrepreneur
.  Very rich.  In Spalding, today, one of the big private schools is named after him, the hospital in the area is named after him.  And later on, I learned, in Jamaican culture, he\rquote 
s seen as one of the great entrepreneurs in the twenties/thirties, into the forties.  And he was a black man.
