\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 Oh, family story.  Okay, yes.  Her family story was really that her surname is Mickell \endash  Michael as we pronounced it in Jamaica, but generally pronounced Micke
ll.  And her father, the story, I don\rquote t know whether it is true or false, was that he was from the Maroons.  But then he fell in love with a woman who had been married and was separated from her husband \endash 
 who was my grandmother, Emma.  And she then bore him a number of  [children].  They got married.  He was younger than she was.  And she was, she was white to look at, in every way.  I remember her vividly.  Because I didn\rquote t know my father\rquote 
s parents at all, they died way before I was born.  But my mother\rquote s 
father and mother I knew very well.  And so my grandmother, on that side, I always knew her as being blind, because by the time we were conscious, as kids, she was pretty elderly.  She was entirely grey, white hair \endash 
 hair like yours.  And white.  Now, they used to describe to us the differences of colouration, which didn\rquote 
t make any sense to me until, centuries later, reading Edward Long!  (LAUGHS)  So that, technically, in the Jamaican kaleidoscope of colours, she would have had a percentage of black and, therefore, she wasn\rquote 
t entirely white, but physically, and in every way, she was, everything about her.  So she was older, as I said, than my grandfather.  
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 
