\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 Do you know what the family she was from, then?
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri113\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin113\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11870632 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid6571465\charrsid6571465 Harry:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 Not entirely, but I knew that the story, the myth, is that she\rquote 
s from a very rich family.  I knew one of her brothers, who was much younger, and the story about him is that he had quite a bit of land, and he had a very wonderful house, and I spent time with him from time to time \endash  he was a ver
y quiet, dignified man \endash  but that he was conned out of his inheritance, and the family, other side, stole most of the property.  He didn\rquote 
t have much of an education, and they conned him out of it.  But they left him with everything else, because what we knew of him, he was fairly well-heeled.  But that side of the family, they then moved, also, approximate to where my father is from 
\endash  my father\rquote s family \endash  in the mountains.  But they also had come, originally, from Manchester.  Manchester, as you might perhaps know by now, in Jamaica, part of it is where there\rquote 
s still a strong brown-cum-white settlement, and we usually refer to them as the \'93red men\'94, or \'93red people\'94.  My mother\rquote s side is very much that.  My grandmother, maternal side.  My grandfather, the sto
ry was that he was from the Maroons, but he\rquote 
d fallen in love with this woman, who was not a Maroon, and there was a tradition that once you leave, once you marry outside of the Maroons, you cannot return.  So he was never able to go back.  So, in a sense, 
he had cut himself off from his family.  So he\rquote 
d moved even further away, into the borders, what is literally the borders of St. Elizabeth and Clarendon, and where my mother was born.  So where my mother was born, and where my father was born, is about thr
ee or four miles apart.  My mother used to love to tell us the story of how they met.  That she was passing through }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11678484\charrsid7427796 Belcarras}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 , where my father - and she saw this fellow, and he looked at her, and she decided to run, because she used to be a great sprinter,
 to run away, to get back to her house, and he sprinted after her.  But my father was not as tall as my mother, and she used to say, \'93He\rquote s just a short man!\'94
 and she took pity on him, and stopped running and went back to talk with him, and that\rquote s how the romance started.  And they were married very young.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 
