\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 But about the grandparents, can you describe their characters?
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri113\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin113\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11870632 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid6571465\charrsid6571465 Harry:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 On my maternal side?  Yes, certainly.  Yeah, my grandfather, even to this day, seemed to me to have been - when I came to this 
country and I was fascinated by the tales of King Arthur and the Knights of the Round Table, I remember seeing a picture, a pencil drawing, in one of the books, of Sir Lancelot, with hair coming out of his nose and out of his ears, and very hairy.  My gra
n
dfather was like that!  A very tough man.  Very tall.  The baldness in my present family, seems to come from him, because he was fairly bald as well!  But hair everywhere else!  (LAUGHS)  He lived into his eighties.  And, for a while, we lived with him.  
When he died, in fact, I was on the same bed with him.  It was an election year in Jamaica, and he had gone to the hustings, the local place, came back late, and we had gone to bed.  We were on \endash  my youngest brother and myself \endash 
 we were on the same bed.  And he came in, and early in the morning, there was a strange sound coming from him, but we didn\rquote t think anything of it.  And then, as the morning came \endash  and he was always a person to be up before anyone else 
\endash  he wasn\rquote t up, and there was a strange froth com
ing from his nostrils and from his mouth.  So we then called some adults, and asked them what it was, and they said he had had a stroke, so they took him to the hospital.  So I have a very strong vivid memory of him.  He was the sort of person who, if he 
h
ad a toothache, tie a string on the tooth, and just throw a stone, and it was out!  (LAUGHS)  If he had had a bite, he would use a knife and just slit it and let the blood out, and then just rub over it!  (LAUGHS)  He had this remarkable skill to detect p
oisonous and non-poisonous mushrooms.  And he had the ability to walk into a nest of bees, extract from them, you know, the honeycomb, and they wouldn\rquote t trouble him at all.  And then he\rquote 
d walk out.  And you were mystified by it.  So, for me, he was a great hero, a great figure.  You know the Wordsworth poem, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 Michael}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 ?  He\rquote s another figure in English literature - when I was reading Wordsworth, as a school kid, I used to think of the father of Michael\rquote s father, as being very much like my grandfather.  Though there
\rquote s no equivalent story in our family to relate to.  But very much, for me, that poem, which I\rquote 
ve read over and over and over, and always go back to, is always an image of my grandfather, in so many ways.  A person who could always stand up to anything, who would always be able to relate to anyone \endash 
 young, old, anyone at all.  And a person to whom could come and sit and talk.  The thing that he grew a lot of was tobacco, in two of his plots he grew quite a lot, and made quite a bit of money from tobacco, 
and he would always smoke his own tobacco.  And he and his daughter \endash  one of my aunties, by the same name of Selina \endash 
 were the only two people I can think of, in my whole family, who smoked.  But they smoked their own pipes, and their own tobacco!  (LAUGHS
)  So he was that sort of a figure, and a very powerful one.  My grandmother, as I said, I always recall her, remembered her, very much, as sitting in a chair \endash 
 not active.  Always having a story to tell, always bringing us to her, all of us, as grandkids,
 and knowing each of us without having seen us clearly, because she was partially blind, and by the end of her life, she was entirely blind.  She would say that she needed us to plait her hair for her, and to rub it.  And I was talking in India, recently,
 to some of Selina\rquote 
s relatives there, about aloe vera oil, and, of course, a lot of these plants were grown in our places.  And whenever she had a headache, she always instructed one of us to go and cut one of these, open it, and put it on her head, and jus
t rub it for a while, and then she\rquote d claim the headache had gone.  We thought these were a lot of mythologies that didn\rquote t work!  So it\rquote 
s interesting now to see that aloe vera is supposed to be this big thing in terms of healing and folk medicine and so on.
  So, again, my memory of her was a very vivid one.  When my grandfather died, because when my parents left Jamaica, we had this one house and then a second one, and as more people from the kinship group migrated, my parents suggested that one of my mothe
r\rquote 
s sisters, whose husband and older kids are also in this country, and my grandparents, that we should all move to one of those houses and live there.  Then we lived there for some time, and that auntie, whom I was living with, she decided to move to a pla
ce called Williamsfield \endash 
 you might have passed through there en route to Mandeville.  She bought a piece of land there, and built her own house there.  My grandmother went to stay, to live with her, my grandfather stayed with us in the house.  The story I
 related of his death in 1958/59, meant, then, that my parents had to take immediate action, so my father had to come to Jamaica, and decided that it\rquote s time for all of us to come to Britain, that we might, as kids, all come here.  Now, I didn
\rquote t want to at all, because I was very close to my grandmother, even though she was not in the same household.  And for a while then, for about the period of three months, since my grandfather had died, my father had arrived, we moved into my auntie
\rquote s house in Williamsfield.  And in that period of time, I spent a lot of time with my grandmother, talking and so forth.  I didn\rquote 
t want to leave, and I kept begging my parents that could I just stay?  (LAUGHS)  And they said, "No, it can't be done". Then we came to Britain and 
I was very unhappy.  Very very unhappy.  And I wanted to go back, partly because I missed my grandmother very much.  And my father made a promise.  He said, \'93Look, I know you want to be able to own a bridle and a stirrup, so that when you\rquote 
re back in Jamaica, you can ride a horse with your own equipment\'94.  I said, \'93Yes\'94.  And he said, \'93Well, listen, we\rquote re staying in Britain for three years, and after that, we\rquote 
re all going back to Jamaica, and if you settle down at school, when you go back to Jamaica, I\rquote ll buy you these, and I\rquote ll buy you another horse\'94
.  And that settled me.  But the last - I think my childhood was quite miserable in some respects, because of missing my parents, and the last great pain cane, I think, in my childhood, was when, one evening, com
ing home from school in Camberwell, I think I was still in primary school, my mother, knowing how close I was to her mother \endash  to my grandmother \endash  called me, and then sat me down and said I must relax for a while, and I was wondering what
\rquote s happening, and then she announced that my grandmother had died.  And, of course, I cried and cried.  And then I never cried again until \'85 until my parents died.  And that was decades later.  So my proximity to her was very profound.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri113\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin113\lin1871\itap0\pararsid6571465 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid6571465\charrsid6571465 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 So, in a way, you had become closer to her, would you think, than to your own parents, at that point?
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri113\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin113\lin1871\itap0\pararsid6571465 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid6571465\charrsid6571465 Harry:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 Oh yes, definitely.  Oh yeah.  And that is because, of course, in the migration story, lots of children, I think, get cut off from their parents.  I think we were lucky in the se
nse that there came a particular time, because of the death of my grandfather, that my parents decided, \'93Well, we\rquote d all better be here\'94
.  And, of course, in the scholarship, you realise, much later on, what was happening in Britain, which was the whole debate about the end of immigration from the Commonwealth.  And I\rquote 
ve never discussed with my parents, but I suppose it must have been part of their consciousness that what they really wanted was to stay on in Britain a bit longer, will they be able to bring t
heir children here?  And so when my father came to collect us, there were four of us who were still there \endash 
 two of my eldest brothers, and my eldest sister, were already here with them, but my father became a travel agent, if you like, because a number of 
