\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 Yes.  Well, as I said, well, one of the great things, I think, about my grandparents as well as my parents, was what we might call \'93joking relationships\'94
.  In the case of my grandparents, during the rainy season, when it was really wet and heavy, and you had to stay in, one of the gre
at things I recall was the storytellings of the Nancy stories.  And I was particularly good at this, because I could listen to things and repeat them almost exactly, and they used to ask me to tell stories, because all I would do was simply repeat what pe
ople had said!  (LAUGHS)  In that way, you get to know them, and the jokes, and the teasing that would go on.  With my parents, similarly.  I sometimes said to my kids that in our generation of bringing up kids, they become your friends.  I wouldn\rquote 
t quite say I was friends of my parents in that way, in that you could tell them everything that\rquote 
s on your mind, but certainly in terms of jokes, in terms of teasing, those were very much part of regular life.  For example, my father was responsible for discipline, naturally, in a typical household of that time, which meant that if you misbehaved, he
\rquote d give you a good spanking.  But his heart was never in it!  (LAUGHS)  His heart was never in it!  So sometimes, at home, you\rquote d do something wrong, and he was going to give you a good spanking.  But he would come home from work, he\rquote 
d go off into his bedroom, he would go off to bed after a while, after eating, and then he would say, \'93Harold, don\rquote t forget to bring me the strap\'94, because you\rquote re supposed to bring the strap that he\rquote 
s going to spank you with!  (LAUGHS)  So then we'd go and tease him, just when he\rquote s falling asleep, and say, \'93I\rquote ve brought the strap!\'94
  (LAUGHS)  Of course, he wants you to get away, because he wants to sleep!  I sometimes have a talk with Selina ab
out her father, her relationship with her father, and recently we were talking to her brother, in Goa, about relationships, and they would say that they can\rquote 
t remember having had discussions or talks at all with him, because it was very formal and very str
ict.  Whereas I can think of any amount of times of jokes, of teasing, of pointing fun at them about themselves, and similarly about me, about us generally.  That relationship wasn\rquote 
t always equitably so right across my sibling groups, for example, my youngest brother, he never had that, for some reason, and I think it\rquote s still an influence on how he perceives the family \endash 
