\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 Not that religious.  To a degree I was, partly through one of my aunts and my grandmother.  For example, in the relationship that I discove
red through my grandmother, one of the things she always wanted is to read to her The Bible, or sometimes to sing her a hymn from the Sankey Hymn Book.  In a sense, one\rquote 
s introduction to literature is really from them, in that way, first.  I would say that, in terms of one\rquote 
s appreciation of Shakespeare, I see those as all one, as one package, in a way.  So one was very very religious, in fact.  And at the age of 15, I decided that, yes, I would want to become that, leave school.  Our Deputy Headmaster was a
 devout Baptist, at school in Peckham, pleaded with me to say, please, I shouldn\rquote t leave.  Eventually I did.  And I went off to Ireland for a year.  At the end of that year, I decided, \'93
Well, actually, this is a terrible decision!  I ought to go back to school\'94.  So I went and saw the Deputy Headmaster, and he said, \'93I\rquote m pleased you\rquote ve seen the light!  Come back\'94
