\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 What happened there?  I think what happened, I fell in love with a girl.  I remember, it was my birthday, I was 
16 during the course of that, and I was walking along the North Antrim coast, in Northern Ireland, and I became very fascinated by this girl, who had also come, from Somerset, to the same College.  She was a descendant of the great hymn writer Wyatt.  Ver
y much from that Evangelical background.  And I remember, I recall at the end of the year, when I realised that, look, if I was going to have this interest in girls and women, I can\rquote 
t become a religious man!  (LAUGHS)  But, more importantly, she had done her \lquote O\rquote  Levels, and at the end of the year when I said, \'93Look, I\rquote m abandoning this\'94, she said, \'93
Well, what are you going to do?  You have no qualifications, you\rquote re now quite old\'94, and in those years, at the age of 16, you were old!  And I thought about it, and I thought, \'93God, yes!  You\rquote re here, and I\rquote 
ve done nothing with my life.  I should do something\'94. That\rquote s when I went back to school and saw the Deputy Headmaster, and said, \'93Look, am I too old to come back?\'94  And he said, \'93No, you can come back.  You\rquote re 
still 16, you can come back into the school\'94.  And became something of a hero for the school, in a sense, because I applied myself so hard to academic work.  But that\rquote 
s what I think happened in Ireland.  Also, I learnt a bit about the politics of religion,
 in the sense that the people who were heading this college I went to, I realised that they did not have leadership qualities, and that they were very hypocritical, that their interest was very economic, in terms of what they could get for themselves.  An
d
 I felt, well, here was a set of young people, like ourselves, who were interested in the spirituality of the thing, the intellectuality of the thing and so on, but they were much more interested in the economics, as I saw it.  And I thought this is very 
h
ypocritical, very bad.  Paisley was part of one those preachers in the background.  He was not part of that group, but some of the churches we would go to, to practice preaching and so forth, he was involved in that wider network.  And at the time, the di
scussion was really, he was going to go into politics, and we thought, \'93A man like that, into politics?\'94
  (LAUGHS)  So I became very disillusioned by that, in those kinds of ways.  And I suppose it was a period of youth, of developing, whereas, I suppose, a
 lot of other young people might have been interested in Communism or Socialism, or other isms.  For me, my background there was religion.  And that was how one approached it.  And it wasn\rquote 
t until I got to university that the political dimension of youthful consciousness came into the picture.
