eligion\'94, that all this thing about discussing things and querying things was wrong, and that\rquote s not Godly, that\rquote s Satanism, that\rquote 
s bad!  That having too much of a formal education was also not right.  And she opposed, very strongly, my idea of going to uni
versity to study these things, when, really, I should be in the Church. I used to be a very good public speaker, preacher, so she wanted me to continue in that vein.  She travelled a great deal within the Caribbean and North America, amongst these Evangel
ists, and she was quite a brilliant speaker, and she wanted me to be in that same vein.  And by not being that, I was questioning her authority which, for me, again, meant that this is something that I did not want to follow.  I\rquote 
ve always seen my liberation from my mother as a liberation from religion!  And for me, that\rquote 
s a very important victory.  The woman, in later life, looking at her from a distance, who always reminded me of my mother, is Margaret Thatcher.  My mother could convince almost anyone of wh
atever she wanted to.  The thing is not to listen to her if you don\rquote t want to be convinced!  She is a very powerful, persuasive, kind person, but with that kindness, I felt, also went a destructive quality, to control people\rquote 
s lives.  And that was what I came to dislike thoroughly.  So that when I went to university, I went without her blessings, and as a result, I never invited her to university.  When I graduated, I didn\rquote t go to my graduation myself, I\rquote 
ve never been to my own graduation at all.  But part of it was that I would never ask her to attend.  Years later, when I went to Jamaica, to live there, and I was teaching at the University, and she was close by, just living down the road, I\rquote 
d invite her to the home, but in terms of what other people would have told her about my achievement, in terms of, you know, I\rquote m a doctor, and I\rquote 
m writing books and so forth, I kept that entirely out of her purview, because I felt, since she was so ashamed of me, I would keep that away from her!  And after she died, I wa
s ringing to one of my cousins in New York, who is very much of that ilk, and very much a religious man.  He\rquote 
s a very rich man, he must be a millionaire several times over, but he spends most of his time buried in this narrowness of religion, and he was te
lling me of what my mother said to him, in terms of how I treated her badly, in a way, but that she understood why.  So I don\rquote 
t feel too bad.  I mean, I still feel badly about it, but it is one of those things.  We never did fully reconcile ourselves in th
at regard.  Whereas I never had that sort of relation with my father, he was a much more liberal, open-minded person.  With my mother, ideal for us, the Christian principle, ideal for us, or you were against it.  There is no midway point!  (LAUGHS)  With 
my father, he was much more open, much more liberal.
