\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 No, not really, no.  My father, in this country, his instinc
t was Labour, but is the paradox of it.  And I think this is something which has been shared with people of that generation, that in terms of public issues, he would have been very much part of support Labour, in voting.  But in terms of his economic inte
r
ests and instincts, he was Conservative.  And there are two things there.  One, as I said, my parents made a living, and, given their background [believed] that you must never depend on the State, never depend on public facilities, you depend on yourself 
and your network.  It meant that, for example, when it came to retirement, drawing his pension, I had to force him to draw it.  He didn\rquote t want to, because that\rquote s something from \'93out there\'94
.  That he had contributed to it is neither here nor there.  Hence the investment in land and in housing.  And impressed on us, and I think that\rquote 
s in terms of social capital, one thing which has come through all my siblings and all of us, is that you must always own where you live, so to speak, which may be a primitive idea, but as my father used to say, \'93
Look, when you see a Jamaican in London, who owns a car, parked outside a home in which he lived, but that home is owned by someone else, he\rquote s not one of us.  He\rquote s a Kingstonian.  Urbanite\'94.  Those of us from the countrysid
e, first, you may not be able to own a car, or good clothing, etc., but you own where you live.  And I think all of us have been thus.  Now, I\rquote ve wandered away from the point you asked me there.  But the point I\rquote 
m trying to stress, I suppose, is basically the sense that dependence on self, and they sensed that the Conservative Party was more for \endash  to express in a Jamaican way \endash 
 for the little person, the little man, who can make an effort to keep themselves going, and not depend on public largess or the State.  So there\rquote s a contradiction, and there\rquote s a tension in that.  So they would vote the way my father voted 
\endash  vote Labour \endash  but he would always feel that the Conservatives were more correct.  Similarly in Jamaican politics, they always felt that what Mr. Manley did, and what the PNP \endash  the People\rquote s National Party, the Socialist Party 
\endash  what they were doing was good for people, but that the Jamaica Labour Party, which is equivalent \endash  more Conservative than the British Conservative Party \endash  was that, really, they\rquote 
re the right Party.  (LAUGHS)  So there is a tension, there is that contradiction which flows naturally, particularly in that generation.  But in terms of being active politicians, no.  In my family in Jamaica, the only person - one of my father\rquote 
s nephews \endash  a cousin \endash 
 not far from Spalding, in a place called Frankfield, one of his brothers, who is settled and has his family there, one of those boys was an active - well, not an active politician, he was the party manager for the area, for the Constituency
.  And the MP who dominated there, for generations, was a Jamaica Labour Party man, but bear in mind, the Jamaica Labour Party is more equivalent to the Conservative Party in this country.  It is the PNP there, which is, indeed, a member of the Socialist 
International, same as the Fabians, and as the British Labour Party.  So he is the closest to it.  And, as I say, very much to the right of things.
