\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 Bush tea, that\rquote s right.  And then you go off, and you see to t
he animals, which might mean helping to milk the cows, taking out the pigs, etc., but sorting some things like that out.  Then you would come home, and you have breakfast, which is some solids.  And then you would get off to school.  You\rquote 
d go to school, you\rquote d come back home for lunch, and you go back to school.  And when you come home in the evening, again, you have to help with the animals and so on.  And so your day, as a child, is a very arduous and long one.  And if you didn
\rquote t do well at school, then they would know, and you would have to give an account of yourself!  (LAUGHS)  And don\rquote t forget, in those days, we didn\rquote 
t have things like exercise books, you had a slate, a piece of slate, and a piece of chalk, and you\rquote d move from one lesson to the next, and if you didn\rquote t remember, the following day, what you\rquote d been taught, you\rquote 
d be given a good caning.  And if your uncle knew that you\rquote d had a caning for not remembering, you\rquote d have another caning!  I sometimes related this to my kids, and said, \'93Look, you know, in terms of memory, that\rquote 
s where you really learn.  Because there\rquote s nothing written that you can go back to, each lesson you go to, is that\'94.  So I often say that my learning of grammar, of my times tables, goes back to those days \endash  not schooling in th
is country, because the schooling in this country is a joke!  This is a playtime thing!  (LAUGHS)  You have books, and you move from one thing to the other, leisurely, etc.  (LAUGHS)  No, no!  So that was one uncle.  Another uncle who has been very import
ant to me, was on my mother\rquote s side.  That was Uncle Theophilus, but we just call him \'93Uncle T\'94
.  And he migrated, first, to the United States for a while, and then he went back to Jamaica and came here, and lived here for some years before re-migrating back to Jamaica.  And, as a child, I didn\rquote 
t like him.  He struck me as being too frivolous.  He struck me as wanting to be like us, as kids.  He was always seen, listening to my parents, as being a bit on the wild side.  But as I grew older, and he grew older,
 we became very good friends.  And the last time I saw him in Jamaica, we went up to see him, and he said, \'93Look, this will be the last time we\rquote ll see each other.  Next time you come, I\rquote ll have died\'94.  And I said, \'93
