Well, for a while she worked at Hayes Laundry, towards Camberwell and Coldharbour Lane, but about a couple of months after we arrived here as kids, she gave that up, and she [was] a housewife, she just saw t
o us at home, basically.  And she became very involved with the Church.  Very involved, as I was saying earlier on, with I suppose we\rquote d call these things, today, \'93community matters\'94, of seeing to people\rquote s needs.  You know, I\rquote 
m fairly mean, I think.  I don\rquote t give things to beggars, and I don\rquote t let people come into my home, who are not friends, and whom I don\rquote t like.  And I think it springs from my mother\rquote 
s attitude to people.  I can remember several Sundays, because Sunday breakfast was a big thing in a Jamaican household in those days.  But sometimes, we\rquote 
d be sitting with tramps off the streets in Camberwell, because anyone who knocked at the door \endash  and remember, a number of Irish people would \endash  and she simply said, \'93Come in\'94.  And we always had a table wher
e there was an extra plate, and it springs from this religious thing that you must always have for the \'93unknown guest\'94
.  This is not just a myth, it was a reality.  And quite often, people would be brought in like that.  People would knock and say they haven\rquote 
t got anywhere to stay.  My parents rented rooms in the houses they had, could they stay somewhere?  My father would say, \'93Look, if they can\rquote t pay, no.\'94  But then he would back away, and my mother would say, \'93Well, there\rquote 
s this room here.  Just come, never mind if you can\rquote t pay\'94.  So that our household was always open to all and sundry \endash  poor whites, poor Irish, Africans, Afro-Caribbean people \endash 
 right across the board.  As a result, I think I grew up with this idea that \'93my home is }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 my}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 
 home, I don\rquote t want all and sundry to come in!\'94  (LAUGHS)  I think I find it difficult to live with a lot of people around me, because I was brought up in that way.  Our house, in Jamaica, when they returned, you\rquote 
d find all kinds of mad, crazy people at home.  Seriously, I\rquote d 
go there, and there will be any amount of people.  They lived, their house was in a garden of about half an acre, and all kinds of riff-raffs and people would be around!  All they had to claim was that they love Jesus (LAUGHS), or that they were in need, 
and then she would try to say, \'93Look, you can help.  I can help.  You can help.  You can help\'94
, etc..  But it did mean that, in Jamaica, my mother, people who came to her funeral, ranged from the lowest of the low, in social order, right up to Justices, fai
rly senior people, even some people at the University.  A couple of the Heads of Departments were very religious people, and I had no idea they knew my mother, but they came to tell me afterwards, and that they\rquote 
ve always observed me and thought I was similar to her.  And I said, \'93I\rquote m not like her at all!\'94  (LAUGHS)  So she did a lot of work in those kinds of ways. But, going back to uncles, I\rquote ve pointed out the two there \endash 
 one on my father\rquote s, and one on my mother\rquote s.  My father\rquote s youngest brother, I\rquote ve always disliked, though again, in older years, I\rquote 
ve come to think of him as not such a bad figure.  But he always reflected to me, to us, the generation of my parents, where siblings had to refer, in order of age, to each other.  So I had to, when I was very sm
all, I had to refer to my eldest brother, as \'93Brother\'94, in addressing him.  His name is George, I had to say \'93Brother George\'94, because he\rquote s ten years older than me.  And I always noticed that my father\rquote 
s younger brother, whenever he came to the house to see him, would treat him in the same way as we treated our father.  He would refer to him as \'93Mas\'94, \'93Mr.\'94 or \'93Brother\'94
, and there was always that deference, much of which has now completely gone, of course!  And I wasn\rquote t terribly fond of him, but because he\rquote 
s now the only one of that generation living, I find I do pay him some respect.  It was really my aunties, I think, whom I found \'85
