\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri113\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin113\lin1871\itap0\pararsid6571465 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid6571465\charrsid6571465 Harry:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 The aunts, yes.  I suppose the single auntie, whom I\rquote ve been most closest to, was Auntie Selina.  She was the only other woman I knew by the same name as Selina.  But she didn\rquote 
t have any children at all.  She was the eldest of my mother\rquote s sisters.  Of the three of them, and one brother, she was the eldest.  She migrated, she came here as well, and when we came to this country, she didn\rquote 
t stay long, she stayed about two years and returned.  And she didn\rquote t have any children, so she treated us as her children, in a way.  And I spent a lot of time - well, it seemed a lot, it couldn\rquote t have been that long, but I sometimes st
ayed with her, when my parents were in this country, and she was there, I would sometimes go to her house and stay for a week or so, a couple of nights and what have you.  And her husband, \'93Mas Bob\'94 as he was known, it\rquote s only in later years I
\rquote ve realised he was \'93half-Coolie\'94 as they say in Jamaica, he was partly Indian. 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 
