\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri113\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin113\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11870632 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid6571465\charrsid6571465 Harry:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 I felt she treated us, myself and a cousin of mine, who is living in Canada, the son of my Uncle T \endash  Uncle Theophilis \endash 
 very much as brothers almost, and would have us around from time to time, would dance with us.  My mother would dance with us from time to time, and similarly, Aunt Selina would, she would say, \'93Let\rquote s have a dance\'94
!  (LAUGHS)  And so she was very much like another mother to me, in a way.  She died after my parents, and I never saw her after the funeral of my mother, which was always very sad.  So whenever I\rquote 
m in Jamaica, again, I go to her grave, to see where she\rquote s buried and so on.  But she was very close.  My other maternal auntie \endash  Aunt Emily \endash 
 for me, she was always the great beauty. When I came to this country, and I remember seeing Sophia Loren in films, I used to look at her, because she was - my Auntie Emily.  But it\rquote s curious when you see a person 
and you think her behaviour, her beauty, everything, is the same.  And even now, if I see Sophia Loren, I still think of Aunt Emily.  She was outstandingly beautiful, and resembled her in every way.  And she took after her mother, much more white than bla
ck.  I\rquote m sure if she would have been in Italy, she\rquote d have been seen just as an Italian.  In a way, she\rquote s so important in our lives, because her children and my mother\rquote 
s children, we go one after the other.  In terms of cousin relationships, her children and us are the closest, in terms of all the other cousins and so forth, and I think it\rquote s because they\rquote 
re staggered.  So my eldest sister, followed by my auntie\rquote s eldest child, just by a year, and so we stagger like that, all the way down, and so my cousin, who is my equivalent from her family \endash 
 who is this cousin I was telling you about in New York \endash  who is a very rich man, but a mad hatter for religion, he and I are as close, or closer than some of our own siblings.  We were brought up in that way in Jamaica, and so we\rquote 
re very close indeed.  She also used to - we had a lot of fun in terms of jokes and what have you.  Sadly, one of the great guilts that I have is that when she died \endash  she died some time after my parents \endash  I wasn\rquote 
t able to go to her funeral.  And I always felt very bad about that.  On my father\rquote s side, my aunties, Aunt Bertha \endash  someone, again, I remember vaguely in my childhood, very fondly.  Then when we went to live in Jamaica, an auntie whom I
\rquote d only met twice \endash  my father\rquote s sister \endash  she died, and so we went to her funeral.  I took both kids along, because when I was a child, the idea of shielding children from death was not on.  It\rquote s part of life.  And I
\rquote ve always felt the same in that.  Do you remember the scene from }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 Dr. Zhivago}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 
, the film, where the child goes to his mother\rquote s funeral?  When I first saw that, I thought, \'93My God, this is just like childhood!\'94
  Not as dramatic as that, but the idea of hymns over the the grave, of moving the grave from the home to the place of burial, and everybody, of all generations, participated in that.  And so, both boys still remember going to that funeral.  And I said, 
\'93Well, I won\rquote t apologise for that.  It was intended that you should see that this is part of life\'94.  I\rquote d only met her a couple of times, but I was very very fond of her. 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri113\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin113\lin1871\itap0\pararsid6571465 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid6571465\charrsid6571465 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 On funerals, did they have that sort of night watch?
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri113\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin113\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11870632 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid6571465\charrsid6571465 Harry:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 Yes, yes.  Oh yes.  Oh yes.  Nine nights.  Nine nights.  So, so when my grandfather, for example, the one who I remember most vividly, when he died, the body wa
s kept in his own room, in his bedroom, for that period of time, and then every evening, people from the neighbourhood would come in to sing hymns and to tell stories.  It wasn\rquote t all sad.  And there\rquote 
s talk about his life and so forth.  Then, at the funeral, there\rquote s part of the ritual \endash 
 because he was buried on his own land, where a son of his had died in childhood, where he was buried, and that was about two miles away from where we were living \endash  and what usually happens then is that the men of the family w
ould take the coffin, on their backs, and to carry it all the way.  And part of the ritual, which was frightening, as a child, is that the body should resist this.  So every so often, the coffin, the coffin, would fall off their shoulders, but it wouldn
\rquote t be damaged.  What it is is the spirit of the dead resisting.  And that, itself, is expected.  I used to be mystified, how does it do this?  (LAUGHS)  And this would happen over the stretch of two or three miles, every so often \endash 
 particularly around bends and around corners!  (LAUGHS)  I remember it so well, it was so dramatic!  Then there\rquote 
s hymns all the way, and crying and weeping and so forth.  And then you get there, and similarly, over the grave, there would be this long ceremony.  It's an all day affair.   It\rquote 
s also an occasion when relatives from other parts, come along. I mentioned that when I was hitch-hiking in Ghana, staying with a family in Kumasi, in the heart of Ashanti land, and one of the evenings they were having a similar thing, after the fu
neral and so on.  They were relating to me how important that is, socially, for members of the wider kinship group to get together, who may not know each other very well.  And they were saying, well, the experience of that in Jamaica was very much that so
rt of thing.  Now, obviously, with migration and so forth, I\rquote m sure that doesn\rquote t happen any more.  This is really much from a rural peasant community, that these sort of things would happen.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri113\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin113\lin1871\itap0\pararsid6571465 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid6571465\charrsid6571465 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 I noticed, too, when I was there, that people seemed to dig the grave together.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri113\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin113\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11870632 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid6571465\charrsid6571465 Harry:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 Oh yes, yes.  It\rquote s not a professional - well, for example, when my mother was buried, and she didn\rquote t want to be buried back out in the countryside, she wanted to be buried in \'93
neutral ground\'94, so to speak, so she wasn\rquote 
t buried with her parents, as would have been the practice, because where her parents are buried, the graves are still kept, and the family go from time to time to tidy up and so forth.  She wanted to be buried with her husband \endash  with my father 
\endash  in a professional cemetery, that\rquote s fairly neutral.  We bought a spot for my father next to hers, so we didn\rquote t have that sort of thing, it was just much more as you would see in this country.  But, yes, it\rquote 
s usually that, the men of the family, or of the ne
ighbourhood, would dig the grave together, whereas in the urban setting, it would be professional groups, people who work there, who would do so.  I think partly they wanted to be buried there because we are scattered all over the place, because they real
ised that it\rquote s a driving distance from Kingston, so when people are visiting, we\rquote d always be able to go to the grave, whereas way out in the country, 70 miles from Kingston, it\rquote s less likely.  And I think that\rquote 
s what has actually happened.  And it was a good thing, there was the wisdom to have bought two plots together. I don\rquote t know if I\rquote ve ever told you this, but my mother was visiting us in this country in \rquote 
86, and said this is the last time she\rquote s coming to visit people in England \endash  friends, family and so on, church groups \endash 
 and she was doing the rounds.  She had gone up to Ipswich to stay with my brother there, then came to London to visit another brother, and then she was to come to stay with us, in Coventry, last.  And she rung up, on the phone, to say that she wasn
\rquote t well.  And I said, \'93Don\rquote t worry.  I\rquote ll come down to see you soon\'94
.  She was staying with my sister in Norwood, and one day we had this call to say she had a heart attack, and by the time I got to London, the ambulance had been, collected her, took her to King\rquote s College \endash 
 just behind where we were brought up, King\rquote s College Hospital, just behind Coldharbour Lane, where we were brought up - and she died.  At the same point in time, my father lost his marbles.  Completely his mind went.  And by 
the evening, when I came down and saw him, he said he can\rquote t understand what was happening.  Lucy (my mother) had left and gone off somewhere.  And he just refused to recognise.  And after a while, he said, \'93Look, up to there\'94, so he said he
\rquote d just like to go home now, back to Kingston.  So two of us \endash  my eldest brother and another \endash  took him back to Kingston, and he never really recovered, in a sense.  When I went out \endash  with my mother\rquote s body \endash 
 a couple of occasions, he came together and we talked about his childhood, and I said, \'93Look, would you like to revise your Will?\'94
  And I brought in a friend, a lawyer, who went through it with him and so on, and that was about the only sort of sanity, or conscious part of it.  And he just refused to eat, he refused to
 drink.  They eventually took him to a small hospital down the road, and put him on a drip, and they were very very good with him, and they said there\rquote s nothing they can do, because he\rquote 
s refusing to live.  So within five weeks, he died.  And they said, \'93Physically, there is nothing wrong with him\'94.  But then they said, \'93Well, look, they\rquote ve been married for 53 years, and they\rquote ve always been very close, so then it
\rquote s understandable, and that this does sometimes happen\'94 \endash  particularly to the male, not to the female!  (LAUGHS)  So it\rquote s a very sad tale, really.  But which point were we on?
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri113\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin113\lin1871\itap0\pararsid6571465 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid6571465\charrsid6571465 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 The funerals.  Well, it\rquote s aunts, really, you were talking about.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri113\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin113\lin1871\itap0\pararsid6571465 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid6571465\charrsid6571465 Harry:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 Aunts, yes. 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri113\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin113\lin1871\itap0\pararsid6571465 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid6571465\charrsid6571465 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 I mean, most of these are the ones that stayed in Jamaica? 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri113\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin113\lin1871\itap0\pararsid6571465 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid6571465\charrsid6571465 Harry:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 Yes, in the countryside.  Yes, always in the countryside.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri113\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin113\lin1871\itap0\pararsid6571465 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid6571465\charrsid6571465 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 None of these aunts and uncles, for instance, went to the town and had professional jobs? 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri113\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin113\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11870632 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid6571465\charrsid6571465 Harry:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 No, not at all.  No, no.  No.  I mean, like my auntie, Aunt Emily, she had her own land, and she grew
 enough coffee and citrus and sold those, but I think she only went to Kingston to visit, like when my mother returned.  She always refused to migrate, or to travel to see her children either in this country or in the United States or in Canada.  It
\rquote s only
 towards the end of her life that she made one visit to New York, and then people from Canada and other places went to see her.  She refused to go anywhere else!  (LAUGHS)  No, no, she never travelled at all.  No, there are none of them professionals.  Th
ere\rquote s none of them highly educated folks at all, although [there are] relatives who are school teaching element and so forth, some of whom I\rquote ve met.  They\rquote re not not the inner core of our group as such.  It\rquote 
s like when I was in Goa, one of the people at Selina\rquote s family home, pointed out that, in one of the international magazines, that the woman who\rquote d jumped the longest \endash  the record for this year \endash 
 is a Goulbourne from Kingston, and did I know her?  (LAUGHS)  I said, \'93No, I don\rquote t\'94.  The fact that her name is spelt exactly the same way, I\rquote m obviously related to her.  So she will, obviously, if she\rquote 
s gone to the Olympics, will be something [significant, but] I don\rquote t know her at all.  In this country there is a chap, he\rquote s a vicar in the Church of England, in one of the London parishes, again same name, and obviously we\rquote 
re related, but I don\rquote t know him from Adam.  But there\rquote s nobody famous, there\rquote s nobody important, in terms of the ways of the world, in either side of our families, as such.  Though our generation 
have gone on, because of the migration story, and have done something else. We\rquote 
ve kept in touch tangentially, but not significantly.  For example, I have a cousin in Kingston who runs a private company as a consultant.  He was an agriculturalist, and he\rquote s 
done a lot of work with the UN and so on, and occasionally we run into each other.  But we don\rquote t know each other terribly well.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri113\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin113\lin1871\itap0\pararsid6571465 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid6571465\charrsid6571465 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 Could we run through your brothers and sisters, see what\rquote s happened to them?  Can you start with the eldest?
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri113\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin113\lin1871\itap0\pararsid6571465 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid6571465\charrsid6571465 Harry:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 The 
eldest?  And this will take you into the patterns of Jamaican families, in particular.  My eldest sibling, my sister Ann, she died at the age of 58, some years back, a couple of years back, in this country.  She was, in a sense, almost a mother as well, b
ecause when my parents came here, she was then in her teenage years, and she had to take on a heavy responsibility, so that my youngest brother sees her more of a mother than he sees our mother \endash 
 because he was much closer in his early years.  And she\rquote s the one who kept close to my parents, and returned, etc..  The next in line is - well, there are two next in line.
