\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 Well, he was brought up by my uncle.  Then when he migrated later on, and came to this count
ry, he joined my family in this country, so by this time he was in his late teens/early manhood, and my mother simply accepted him, he\rquote s one of our brothers.  Now, in terms of my parents\rquote  Will, when they drew up their Will, they didn\rquote 
t treat him as an equal to us, the rest of us.  But we decided that we would simply change it slightly, and treat everyone as the same.  So he\rquote s, in every way, one of us.  And he goes by our name as well \endash 
 surname.  And so I sometimes say that, obviously, I\rquote m not a good Jamaican father, because I ought to have had at least some kids - (LAUGHS)  Because my father was typical of Jamaican fathers, he\rquote s married to my mother for 53 years, they
\rquote ve always been close, etc., he left matters largely in her hands and what have you.  Whereas quite often you find people marry several times or have lots of kids outside etc..  In his case, it was just this one instance.  
