\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 Yes, yes.  Yes, yes.  Everybody.  Everyone di
d.  Irrespective of what they did [beforehand].  This is what sometimes I think about as being the loss of the agricultural skills, because that was what, in terms of skills, they had, but they came into an industrial setting, and there was no marriage wh
atsoever, with the English countryside.  My brother, George, in the late sixties, he wanted to very much go into the English countryside, and that\rquote 
s why he moved to Ipswich, and I used to go with him to various parts of the counties around London, looking a
t properties, with some agricultural land, because he very much wanted to go into agriculture.  He never quite made it.  He made it into living out in a village outside of Ipswich, but he never really made it into that.  So when, long years later, in 
\rquote 89, when we bought our homestead place, they felt - well, he visited from Jamaica, and he felt, he wished he hadn\rquote t gone back, he would have come and joined me and bought somewhere nearby.  Because it\rquote 
s still very much lodged in his head what he should do.  But no, I think so, there\rquote s been a great deal of loss in that respect.  And since they never had\'85  Their education went up to the age of [12/14], my father\rquote 
s education up to the age of 12, and my mother\rquote s, my brothers up to the age of 14 \endash  George and Alfonso \endash 
 in Jamaica.  Those who came here, who came up as children, their education went a bit further, but not a great deal more, in the sense that the culture in which they lived, they always wanted to get off and work and get some money.  And I recall, for ex
ample, the brother whom I follow in line, when he finished school, they\rquote d set up an apprenticeship for him.  But he didn\rquote 
t want to go into an apprenticeship, he wanted to just go like other people around him, and earn immediately.  And that has been the story of his life, in a sense.
