\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 Well, that\rquote s true.  And I think, you know, as much as you might say that migration for Caribbeans has been a great disappointment to Britain, it\rquote 
s not entirely true.  I was saying to Rex Nettleford, a couple of months back \endash  Rex Nettleford, the former Vice-Chancellor of the University of the West Indies, and he\rquote s a good friend, and we were travelling, and I was saying, \'93
Well, Rex, if my parents had not migrated to Britain, I would have just been a country bumpkin.  Because, Jamaican leaders have not done much for people there, and it\rquote s a good thing we did migrate!\'94  (LAUGHS)  And he said, \'93No, no, it\rquote 
s not true.  Given that you have a brain, something would have happened\'94
.  But I doubt it very much.  I think that, as I was saying earlier on, some of the brightest people I know, in terms of native intelligence, are people without any education at all, and I think what migration did was to 
provide us with opportunities, and some people were willing to take these up, and others, for whatever accident of life, were not.  In my own case, I enjoyed school.  And the normal story, in this country, of black kids not doing well in school, and schoo
l is a terrible time, I have to go against that and say, in my own individual case \endash  I\rquote m not saying that, sociologically, it\rquote s not the case \endash 
 but in my own individual case, school, for me, was a wonderful time.  I happened at primary school, to enjoy it, and at secondary school. 
