\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 That\rquote s right.  Well, what was then called \'93primary education\'94.  Primary school, that\rquote 
s right.  And primary school there was - I came here, about 10 going 11, but basically, when I came here and I went to Crawford Primary School in Camberwell, I forgot what they were doing, I\rquote 
d done already, and so I had a good year of doing nothing really!  And I don\rquote t even remember taking the 11+ at all.  I might have done, or perhaps they didn\rquote 
t even bother to put me into it.  But I recall that during the last week or so, they said they have to write a report, and I hadn\rquote t done any work.  So my parents was brought to school to see what work I hadn\rquote 
t done, and they piled up all these books, and I said, \'93It\rquote s fine, I\rquote ll do them\'94.  And then I sat down and just did them all!  (LAUGHS)  The
n the school I wanted to go to was Peckham Manor School, where I had a friend.  And in those days, you have to imagine, there were very few black children around at all.  At primary school there was my younger brother, my younger sister, myself, and two o
t
her black kids.  At Peckham, when I went to Peckham, a school of 1600, there were ten of us.  And the reason I wanted to go to that school is (1) the street we lived in at the time, just off Coldharbour Lane, Southall Road, in Camberwell, there was an old
er black boy there, who was a friend of our family \endash  it was the only other black family in the street \endash  and he went to Peckham, and I wanted to go to Peckham!  That\rquote 
s the only reason I went there!  (LAUGHS) I think that was a Godsend, because the Headmaster at that school, Matthews, had this notion that - it was part of the comprehensive innovation \-
- that kids, any part of London, can do as well as kids in any other place, provided they\rquote re given the opportunity.  So a number of the kids who went to the scho
ol had passed their 11+, but instead of going to Bishop Tennyson School in The Oval, or to Wilson Grammar School in Camberwell, they went to that school.  But they were still streamed.  In each year, up to the third year, they had eight different classes 
or streams.  And I was in what they called the \'93technical stream\'94
, technical stream where, basically, you do things like woodwork, metalwork, technical drawing and so on, and the idea was that you would leave school, and if you were lucky, you would go into things like an architect\rquote s office, or you\rquote 
d go off to a factory.  There was another stream below us who would go off to the factories.  Then there was a stream of three classes above, whom they taught foreign languages to, etc., etc., and they would go of
f to university.  And each year, depending upon your performance, you could move up or down.  My outstanding subjects used to be religious studies, history, geography and so on.  But, typically \endash  and I still have my reports from those days \endash 
 typically, in term time, I would be bottom, but in the exams I would be at the top.  And they were very angry with me!  (LAUGHS)  Naturally!  \'93If you can do the exam, why can\rquote t you do it in the term?\'94  (LAUGHS)  And it wasn\rquote 
t until the fourth year, when we were now streamed for \lquote O\rquote 
 Levels, that we were given a test, which was given both to the fifth and the fourth year, after one term of teaching in Modern History.  The essay was on Lenin, and one day they announced in the assembly, that the top essay for the piece on Le
nin was written by me \endash  and I was a fourth year, better than the fifth year.  And the chap who was teaching us was just completely taken aback.  So he took me aside and said, \'93Well, if you can do this, why are you in this class?\'94
 you know!  (LAUGHS)  And I said, \'93I don\rquote t know.\'94   But the point is, I knew I could do whatever I wanted to do.  An understanding of the system was not there.  Anyway, this particular teacher, and we\rquote re still good friends \endash 
 Fred Murphy \endash  he is an Etonian.  He went to Eton, he had a
 Double First in Classics at Cambridge, and then as part of this whole innovation in comprehensive education, he came to Peckham to teach.  Obviously, a person like that, seeing someone whom he thinks has a mind, had a positive interest.  And he\rquote 
s had a lasting influence on me, in all kinds of ways.  I think more than any of my university lecturers, again, whom a number of them have had quite an impact on me.
