\'94 Level history, and introduced me to Friedrich Hegel, and to - I\rquote m just re-reading at the moment - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 The Decline and Fall}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 , Gibbon.  And to Tolstoy, and to Isaiah Berlin, and in terms of literature also, to a number of ancient writings, to Thucidides, and the fathers of the founding of history.  So that\rquote 
s how I went to university, particularly through this training for the \'93S\'94 Level.  You\rquote re taken through a whole range of stuff.  And the skill of writing - he said, \'93Look, you know, if you can\rquote t write an essay, you\rquote re not
 going to get anywhere\'94.  And so he drilled me through this.  He, himself, sometimes in history classes, he would sometimes set an essay, for which he would also write one.  The same question.  And then we\rquote 
d go through each together. Nowadays, teaching at university, I find that you can\rquote t do that with your students, and I think, \'93How on earth do they learn?\'94
  The patience that someone like Fred Murphy had with me, to learn, without that sort of nurturing and culturing, it\rquote s very difficult.  And so it\rquote s in those ways.  He introduced me to the theatre, we\rquote 
d go off to the [theatre], he would ensure that I\rquote d go and see certain plays, concerts, etc..  And in that way, broadened an horizon which was not part of one\rquote s background.  I think, however, it built on the 
idea that singing and music was always part of one\rquote s church background, and literature. I knew the Bible inside out, read through it several times, and almost any of the hymnals that you can think of, I knew the songs and the music.  Fox\rquote s }
