ve become and who you are.  So the teaching experience, the experience of schooling, for me, was certainly one where I had a number of teachers who were very very good.  And at university, similarly.  One of my history teachers - once 
I shifted to history as an undergraduate \endash  Michael Heale a very profound influence on me.  Michael Heale.  He mainly writes on American History, he\rquote s an American Historian.  A couple of years ago he retired finally, and he\rquote 
s a big name in American History.  They had a Celebratory Conference in his honour, at Lancaster, and he invited two of us back, of his past students.  The other chap who went, he\rquote 
s a Professor of American History at Nottingham, and he went into that area of American History, but I didn\rquote t
.  But Michael asked that both of us should come.  So I felt very honoured, actually, that he should have done.  So he had quite an impact on me.  Because, as an undergraduate was when one began to discover oneself, in the sense that I was familiar partic
ularly from Chaucer - in those days, I could still read Chaucer in the original, the Olde English, I don\rquote 
t think I could read a sentence now!  (LAUGHS) - to contemporary literature.  And for a while, I did think literature would be my subject.  Indeed, when I was doing my doctorate, I drafted quite a number of stuff which my supervisor, then, Bob Benewick 
\endash  who has been a great friend and inspiration \endash  thought that I should abandon this business of academic work, and write instead.  In fact, my very first publication was short stories.  I\rquote 
