\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 Well, I always felt that I could do what one wanted to do.  And from Jamaica, I felt that, really.  Oh yes, because there were three of us \endash  two cousins and myself \endash 
 and we used to compete against each other in two things.  This cousin of mine, I mentioned, who is in New York, and one in Canada, we always competed in two things \endash  mathematics and English.  And we\rquote 
re all three, always the top in our class there.  And I never felt that there was anything, in terms of matters of education, that if you wanted to do, you couldn\rquote t do.  \tab 
And when I came here, as I said, I found the school system demanded nothing of me.  Incidentally, I would say, in parenthesis, also, that when we came back here from Jamaica, with our kids, in 1984/85, that\rquote s what they found in scho
ol, that it was a playtime, and that\rquote s why we took them out of the State sector into a private school, where they would work them.  And although it was against my politics, I\rquote ve never regretted it, because at least, now, they\rquote 
re educated.  And I still feel
 strongly about that, that in the State sector, in this country, is they just waste the natural instinct to learn, of children.  I think children are like sponges, they just absorb.  And I certainly did, as a child, I just absorbed everything around me, a
nd it\rquote s not an effort at all.  But there\rquote s something about the British State system which says that children are there to have a good time, they shouldn\rquote 
t bother with this and so forth.  So a number of my years were wasted, I think, in that way.  When I rea
lly learnt, I think it came through the religious instinct.  If you take religion in that context seriously, you have to be able to read, you have to be able to have discussions, you have to understand what others are saying, and I think, also, once one i
