[To go to the school] which we call secondary school, that was already a great achievement, bearing in mind that, in the Caribbean, secondary school meant what, in this country, was a grammar school education \endash 
 at that time.  So they felt that, naturally, you would do well, because you\rquote re attending something which was very elitist, in the Caribbean, to go to a grammar school \endash  secondary school. Secondly, the tradition of entire trust
 in teachers, so they felt that the fact that they clothe you, feed you, send you to school, you\rquote re fine, because the pastoral care that they were used to in the Caribbean, of teachers acting totally in loco parentis to the child, they\rquote 
re not to know that, in this country, that had gone a long time ago! (LAUGHS)  So they just assume, if you\rquote re going to go to school, you will do well.  And so all they wanted to know is that on your Report, it says that you\rquote 
re doing fairly well.  And, of course, that misled a
 whole generation of parents and their children, and that is the beginning, if you like, of the understanding of that story of how badly West Indian kids did in the school system, in that generation.  It was an accident, and I realise that very much, that
 
I happen to have fallen at a school where there were, indeed, some very good genuine teachers.  I was giving a Public Lecture at Oxford, in honour of a chap called David Nicholls, a couple of years ago, and in talking in similar terms, afterwards an elder
ly man came to see me, and he said, \'93
Well, the story for Lindon Quasi Johnson is similar, because Lindon went to Tulse Hill School", and this fellow was one of his teachers, and he had taken Lindon under his guidance in that way.  I was in another Public Le
cture recently, at Goldsmiths, and it\rquote s only then that I realised the person who was chairing it was Lord }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid8141884\charrsid7427796 Ouseley}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 , Herman }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid8141884\charrsid7427796 Ouseley}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 
, and it was only then, in that discussion that came out, he said that when I was at Peckham, he was at Tulse Hill, and obviously, again, it\rquote s a similar story of someone paying attention and taking him under their wings.  So it\rquote 
s true that this idea of access to higher education is not part of my family\rquote s history as, indeed, it wasn\rquote t for nearly any of the migrants of that generat
ion.  But they did value education, because they saw education not only as an upward mobile factor, but crucially, that it\rquote 
s a moral good.  That is a moral good, that the educated man, the educated person, is a morally superior person.  (LAUGHS)  And so in that sense, they would say, \'93If you know what you\rquote re doing, we will support you\'94.  But they don\rquote 
t understand the process.  I think, to a large extent, when I speak to a lot of young students now, I realise that they\rquote re getting the same kind of support from their parents, but the parents don\rquote 
t understand the system fully.  Some of the problems of the Caribbeans, in this country, is partly that, I think, that they don\rquote t realise they have to negotiate the system in a very very different way.
