\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 Not really.  I don\rquote t know how, but I\rquote ve always felt that the language that we speak, in terms of Jamaican Creole, that we now call it, that\rquote s a separate language from English.  It
\rquote s different.  And recently, we had a one-day Conference at South Bank last year, the people from Jamaica and here, who wants to promote Jamaican as a separate language, and they asked me if we could host it, and we did, and I was saying to them, 
\'93Look, for me, it\rquote s never been a problem.  If I\rquote m speaking Jamaican, I speak Jamaican.  If I\rquote m speaking English, I speak English\'94.  And if it\rquote s seen in that way, that\rquote s what linguists are now coming to see, they
\rquote re saying that they\rquote re different.  At that seminar, the main speaker was a Professor of Linguistics at Mona, and he was making the point that Jamaican is as far from English as English is from German.  Now, you know, I\rquote 
m not a linguist, I can\rquote t say yes or no, but he was saying, in linguistics, there\rquote s that sort of distance.  And he\rquote 
s very much waging a war, in Jamaica, now, for that to be seen and recognised.  Parliament there has recognised that they need to make an effort in that regard.  I think that, certainly with my kids, that\rquote s how I\rquote 
ve stressed that, there are times when we speak Jamaican.  If you\rquote re in Jamaica, all the Jamaicans will speak Jamaican, but that English is another language and you\rquote ll speak it as such.  And, obviously, there\rquote s a close relation betwee
n the two, because, as you know, in Jamaica, there are a lot of retentions from Olde English, very much so, and I think that\rquote 
s quite fascinating, that the amount of words in Jamaican which I suppose a person in the Elizabethan age would understand better than a contemporary speaker in England today!  (LAUGHS)  But some 19}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\super\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 th}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796  centuryisms as well.  But no, I don\rquote t think I\rquote ve ever had that.  I think, in terms of writing, it\rquote 
s been up and down, and sometimes my grammar, I find that I have to pay strict attention to.  And I find, also, in terms of writing, to have disciplined myself that my written language is not my spoken language, and I think that\rquote 
s general.  I think that is a general situation, that the two are not the same at all.  And again, if you\rquote re doing creative writing, again, it\rquote s it\rquote s another language, in a sense.  But I\rquote 
ve just done a piece of research for Lilian Bayliss School \endash  I don\rquote t know if you know that school?  It\rquote s a school that\rquote s become famous in the media with the Tory spokesman [Oliver] Letwin, saying that he\rquote 
d rather beg than send his kids to the local school.  The local school is Lilian Bayliss.  And one of the problems there, one of the recommendations we\rquote ve made, and I\rquote ve stressed, is really that they should take on board, seriously, to t
reat these new kids who are now coming from Jamaica, to say to them that they should continue speaking Jamaican, but they must realise that English is another language and they should really address that, and some attention, formally, should be paid to th
a
t.  Because, in our time, attention was not paid to anything along those lines, then you sorted yourself for yourself.  So those of us kids in the playground, who are of Jamaican background, would speak in Jamaican.  Those who were from the French-speakin
g Caribbean, particularly from St. Lucia, a number of the kids at our school, two or three of them, in particular \'85 I don\rquote t know if you\rquote ve ever seen this thing called the \'85 }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 The Fresh Prince of Bel Air}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796  on television?  It\rquote s one of these regular television com
edies, with Will Smith and these actors.  Well, in it, there\rquote s an English butler, but the English butler is a black man.  Now, that fellow went to school with us, he\rquote 
s of St. Lucian background.  He was amongst the very first black actors taken on by the Royal Shakespeare Company, and he was a year ahead of me at school.  Now, those kids, we didn\rquote t understand their French-based Creole, but that\rquote 
s what they would practice in the playground, and I think that it was important to do that, because it was part of our identities.  At the same time, you knew that, in the classroom, or talking with the teachers, it\rquote s a different, it\rquote 
s another language that you would speak.  So for kids of Asian backgrounds, that\rquote s a much more straightforward thing, because the distanc
e between the languages is well, vastly different.  But I think those of us, I suspect, of my generation, anyway, I\rquote 
m thinking, of say, for example, the Philips brothers, though, to an extent, they were partly educated in the Caribbean, consciously or unconsciously made that kind of decision, and operated with it.  You want to have a break?
