\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 No.  Accident.  I think, at the very beginning, the idea, I suppose the pattern they had in mind, or subconsciously, would have been two.  One, 
the earlier migration to Cuba, for cane cutting, and where people went briefly, as men, and returned.  We had one relative who had done that, and he was supposed to have come back very rich.  It was a myth!  (LAUGHS)  And the other is of the seasonal work
ers in Florida, who again, only went, what, for three months, and came back.  Now, going to this vast faraway place, the Mother Country, but far away \endash  England \endash 
 which, in those days, in the days of my parents, would have taken two weeks by ship, or even by
 plane, three days.  When we came to this country, as kids, towards the end of the fifties, it took three days.  You get used to it now, you just get up and you fly and you\rquote 
re there.  But it was a three-day trip, flying.  So the sheer distance was, in itself, phenomenal.  And the idea was that you\rquote 
re going for a short period.  Both in terms of the myths about migration, as well as research conducted with people of that migrant generation, is that - it comes up proverbially all the time \endash  three years was the limit.  They\rquote 
ll go for three years, and they\rquote ll go back.  And most of those people, in my family/kinship group, whom I\rquote ve mentioned, who travelled, most of them fit that pattern \endash  two or three years and they\rquote 
re back.  Then it was to get just a bit more cash to help them in terms of their own resources back there, and also the experience of travel.  The idea of settlement and staying any longer was not on at all, they said that wasn\rquote 
t planned.  The planned part of it was come for that limited period.  If you can bring your spouse as well, that\rquote 
s fine, and probably one or two of the older children, but not as children, but as workers.  And again, the notion of preparing to take anything that comes your way, because it\rquote s not your life, it\rquote s a brief adventure, it\rquote 
s a brief period.
