\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 Maybe not, actually, because I remember, vaguely, in my earliest memories, that when she was to come, I was also to come with her.  And up to the last moment, the idea was that I wou
ld, even though I wasn\rquote t the youngest, nor the eldest, but because I was very close to her, that I would also be going with her.  And it was something of a shock that I wasn\rquote 
t, at the last moment.  And for years, I was told that England was over those moun
tains, over those hills, and I literally believed it!  Because the planes, as they were passing over, would disappear behind those mountains, and England was beyond those mountains!  It wasn\rquote t that far away, in a child\rquote 
s imagination (LAUGHS), but it was far away, because you couldn\rquote t get there yourself, you know!  (LAUGHS)  So I\rquote 
m not sure how that was.  I suspect it was nothing more than that he must have thought the three years was not really on, because I think he was here about two years or something be
fore she came, and then when she came, then George came, then Ann came, and that was supposed to have been the end of it.  But then, because of the death of my grandfather, who was then in charge, and they\rquote 
ve never said it, but the debate in this country, in the late fifties, that there should be a stop to immigration from the Commonwealth, a lot of families decided that their spouses, their children, they\rquote 
d better bring them into this country.  The figures zoom up, for those two years up to \rquote 62, precisely because of that factor.  So it had the opposite effect of what politicians hoped it would have had, because people then think, \'93
Well, we have the opportunity now, next year we might not.  So let\rquote s do it.  We can always reverse our decision\'94.  Even when we came, my father was quite convinced that we\rquote 
ll be here for a very short while.  It was in that period, in particular, that he started buying properties in Kingston, and in Spanish Town, and increased his holdings in the countryside as well, because the ide
a was that we were going home.  So we lived, in a sense, pretty miserable lives here as children, because the idea was that all your savings are put towards there, going back there.  So we used to say, \'93Look, what\rquote 
s the point of having these houses in Kingston, rented out, these pieces of land in the countryside, which you\rquote ve paid expensively for, building plots in Spanish Town, and who\rquote s benefiting from these?\'94  And the story was always, \'93
You will, because we\rquote ll be going back there\'94.  And, of course, it didn\rquote t happen.  But the motive of what led to them specifically travelling, is something I\rquote 
ve never really fathomed with, never thought of even, or discussed with them.  Certainly not.  It\rquote s something perhaps I should take up with my older brother, George, because he\rquote ll have been much closer to them at that time.
