\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 Yes.  Oh yes.  I remember there was a cake made,
 with a very sweet top, and this was to be taken for my father.  And there was something about one of my Godparents, because in that period I was very close to my Godparents \endash  who are not relatives.  I think they were church people, I don\rquote 
t even remember their names, now.  I can\rquote 
t remember whether one of them was also travelling, or the cake was to have been shared with my father.  But the cake and me were supposed to be really close, so it was wrapped up together!  And then when they brought the story to me that I wasn\rquote 
t going to come, they decided to cut the cake, and give me a piece of it.  So there\rquote s still a type of ingredients to cakes, when I taste it now, reminds me of that incident, because it was such a vivid one that I wasn\rquote t going.  Not that I wa
nted to go anywhere, but that I would be with my mother, because I was at that age, very close to my mother.  I recall when my younger brother was born \endash  because I used to sleep with my mother and my father, and very close \endash 
 that they explained to me that }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 I}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 
 was going to have a baby.  (LAUGHS)  Yes!  And for years I believed that my younger brother was my baby!  (LAUGHS)  I suppose, psychologically, it might have made sense, to ensure that I welcomed the child, that he was my responsibility, he was my child 
a
nd so on.  And for a long time, as a small child, I thought he was mine!  (LAUGHS)  So I became very protective of my younger brother.  But, anyhow, they decided, because I think they must have thought, then, that, even though she could leave [him], becau
se the baby was much younger, my younger brother is about two and a half/three years younger than me, that they wouldn\rquote 
t [take me from him], that I should be left [to be with him].  I suppose they must have thought it would have had quite a traumatic impact.  And I think it did have, in some ways.  I suppose that\rquote s why to a large extent, now, I don\rquote 
t like to be away from my kids, for any length of time at all.  And being in India, I was reflecting on this with my relatives there, just think that, you know, t
hese are folks who send their kids to Britain, to the United States, to be educated, or Selina\rquote s relatives in Kenya, they come to school and universities here and the parents are back there, and it\rquote s something which I don\rquote 
t think I could do.  I just couldn\rquote t do that at all, in terms of them being at that kind of a distance.  A few years ago \endash  I don\rquote t know if I mentioned this to you \endash 
 I was approached by UCLA with the idea of being appointed there, and I felt very flattered and honoured, and particularly the salary would have been immense, they would be paying me, but I thought, \'93
Do I really want to go to that distance away from my kids here?\'94  I think it must spring from that experience of the tremendous loneliness, which is not spoken much of in the literat
ure, either creative literature or official academic literature, of the pain there is in the experience of migration.  People are cut off, and people have a great sense of loss, a tremendous sense of loss.  So that when we came here and I saw my mother, t
he memory was there, but she wasn\rquote t the same person.  So it took time. 
