\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri113\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin113\lin1871\itap0\pararsid16140354 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid6571465\charrsid6571465 Harry:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 Oh yes, very much so.  Very much so.  My father, when he came to Jamaica, I knew he was my father, because that\rquote s what they said, and we\rquote 
re expecting this man and he came, but he was alien to me.  But what, what broke the barrier with him, was that he was so overjoyed to 
see us, he hugged us, kissed us and made much of us, took us out, etc., etc., during that period. Because in those days, you had to sort out Birth Certificates, photographs, passports, all of which took time.  I mean, in today\rquote 
s world, you can do those in a day probably, but in those days, it took time.  You had to go to Spanish Town from where we were, 60 miles away, proper photographs had to be taken.  He had to have suits made for us (LAUGHS), we didn\rquote 
t travel as we do now, you had to travel in style, so you\rquote d have your first hat, you\rquote 
d have your short trousers, a proper jacket, and a tie (LAUGHS) and so on!  It was an adventure.  It was an event, travelling.  We had to have all kinds of injections and all sorts of stuff, which was entirely alien to us.  For the first time, we\rquote 
re going into towns, into cities.  Up to then, I\rquote d certainly never been beyond Spalding, that was the largest grouping where I\rquote d been to.  I still remember going to Kingston for the first time, and being completely bewildered.  I rem
ember, we were staying at a hotel overnight, and it was night, all of us crowded at the window to look outside at people moving, at electric lights, cars, noise, and wondered whether this was safe!  Now, it\rquote s like an 18}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\super\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 th}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796  century boy from some village comi
ng into town, yeah?  And when you drive from Kingston to the airport, as you come off the mainland to a peninsula, the Pallisades, that long thing, I knew nothing about this, and there was this car, it was a big American limousine which took about 12 peop
le, as a taxi, and it was driving straight into the sea.  And up to then, of course, we\rquote 
d not seen the sea, and it was frightening!  Years later, whenever I drove along there, that memory came back, of driving straight off into the sea.  And this stretch, a
 thin stretch of land just going on and on and on, it was quite something.  And then, of course, getting on to an aeroplane and so forth, all those experiences were entirely new.  So coming to England, then, seeing your mother, seeing others, it wasn
\rquote t frightening, but it was strange and different.  I\rquote ve spoken with other people who have said, when they met their parents, they didn\rquote t know them and they didn\rquote t like them.  It wasn\rquote 
t quite so with us.  (LAUGHS) But the thing which surprised me most, in the morning, we had been told that my father has this huge house in London.  So we got into this house, and it\rquote 
s, of course, all terraced, stretched out along the street, and so for a couple of days I was puzzled.  Why is it that when you get into this huge house, you know, it just is limited in this way, so that you can\rquote 
t go along the full length of it?  Because I assumed \endash  because we\rquote d not seen streets before, apart from passing through Kingston \endash  just assumed that the whole row is the same house.  Now, that sort of perception, I suppose, if you
\rquote re brought up in an urban context, is not part of your puzzlement at all, is it?  But for us, coming through here, you assume that, all along the road is the same house, because in the countryside you live in isolated dwe
llings, separate dwellings. 
