\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 And how else did England strike you when you arrived?
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri113\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin113\lin1871\itap0\pararsid16140354 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid6571465\charrsid6571465 Harry:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 I liked it, because in those days, it was very clean.  You know, that really did strike me that the street was quiet and very clean, and people were, it seeme
d to me, remarkably kind, but they would stop and look at you carefully, they would inspect you \endash  including the children.  But basically that it was a good place to be at, that it was actually likeable.  \tab 
And for the first week, my mother said, \'93Look, the kids shouldn't" - I overheard this conversation \endash  \'93they shouldn\rquote t go to school, they should just relax\'94.  So for about two weeks, and this was in September, we didn\rquote 
t go to school, until one day, a chap saw us on the road \endash  a very elegant chap, dressed up in a suit \endash  and ask us which school do we go to?  We said, \'93Don\rquote t go to any\'94.  And he said, \'93Where do you live?\'94
  And we took him, we must take him to our house.  We did.  And the Truant Officer, of course, he then had a talk with my mother and my father. 
 And by the following day, we had an appointment to the school, then started there!  (LAUGHS)  School was quite a puzzlement.  I remember going in to see the Headmaster, Mr. Porter, because my older brothers they would go to secondary school, but my young
e
r brother and I had to go to a primary school, and we went in and Mr. Porter was one of these very reddish, black suit, typical Headmaster, I suppose, at the time, but very gentle, very very gentle, and he sat us down, and then afterwards he sent us out o
f the room, and it\rquote 
s all formalised and very different from what you would have been used to in terms of a teacher who might be a bit irritated and self-important!  (LAUGHS)  So in terms of that initial thing, those were some of the impressions.  Another th
ing, by the end of a week, my father said, \'93We must go down to Brixton, Brixton Market\'94
, so we were mystified as to what this place would be.  And in the course of the conversation [we gathered] that we would see other black people there, but most exciting
ly, you know what we would see?  We would see Africans.  And I think perhaps that was the first time we were hearing about Africans.  And, lo and behold, we went, and we saw these Africans in these incredible costumes, which we\rquote 
ve never seen anything like that before.  And I think we felt a certain degree of fear and anticipation about it all.  And then we noticed that they had these marks on their faces, and we wondered why they were so cruel to themselves \endash 
 which were tribal marks.  In those days, they were mainly students from Ghana and Nigeria, and it was obviously also the period of African Nationalism, the height of African Nationalism, and since King\rquote 
s College was not far from us, behind, might have been students there.  But there weren\rquote t many of them, but it was a mystery to go and see them, like it\rquote 
s an item of interest.  And, obviously, that denoted that the first Caribbean people, of our kind of backgrounds, were seeing Africans, or even hearing about them, and being told that, in some mysterious ways, you\rquote 
re linked with them.  (LAUGHS)  That was a very important thing.  Then as people turned up from Jamaica, in particular, Brixton became more and more interesting and important.  [You could be] sometimes, literally, overhearing older people saying t
hey must go down to Brixton on a Saturday \endash  not to shop, not to do anything in particular, just to be in Brixton.  And in retrospect, you could see what\rquote s happening, it\rquote 
s just the idea of seeing other people of similar backgrounds, colour, etc., and to talk about the news from home.  There were no newspapers and there\rquote s nothing about that, you know, in terms of communication.  A letter would take several weeks.  
\tab People did write letters, at least!  (LAUGHS)  And the sending of photographs was vitally important.  And so, again, a lot of one\rquote 
s childhood was sitting around looking proper, and having photographs taken!  Mike Philips and I were speaking at a launch of a photographic exhibition in Brixton, a couple of years ago, and I got involved partly because 
the people who were organising it, they\rquote re in Leicester Square, the Photographer\rquote 
s Gallery, is it?  They were putting on the exhibition of this particular photographer, Harry Jacobs, in Brixton.  Now, Harry Jacobs is a person who goes back to my childhood,
 because he was always at home, at weddings, etc., Christenings, what have you, and we still have - well, I don\rquote 
t, but my sister and brothers, they have lots of pictures by Harry.  And he had something over 60,000 shots, mainly of Caribbean families who had moved into the area over the last 40 years or so.  They\rquote 
d read one of the pieces about Caribbean families, so they had made a connection, but when they brought up Harry, I said, \'93I know Harry well, and I\rquote ve even been in touch since childhood days with him\'94
.  But Mike and I were then giving this talk, and one of the reminiscences that I brought up was how people always had their grips under their beds, because the notion of migration was so alive that they would be returning.  Mike\rquote 
s recollection was that, \'93No, sir\'94
, in his family and network, people always had their case, their trunk, their grip, on top of the wardrobe!  Again, the same thing, always ready to depart!  (LAUGHS)  And he felt that when he grew up, he was never going to have a suitcase on top 
of a wardrobe!  (LAUGHS)  But I think I still have a suitcase under a desk somewhere, if not under a bed!  
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri113\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin113\lin1871\itap0\pararsid6571465 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid6571465\charrsid6571465 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 One thing that\rquote s interesting me is that your family chose not to live in, say, Brixton, but in an area where there were very few black people.  Now, do you understand why this was?
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri113\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin113\lin1871\itap0\pararsid6571465 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid6571465\charrsid6571465 Harry:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 Yes.  I think I do.  I think my parents, certainly the sense I had from them, was that Brixton was not \endash  even though that\rquote s where they\rquote d settled \endash 
 my youngest sister was born in Somerleighton Road, Somerleighton Road is the central part of the black settlement in Brixton - but they had this thing that people coming into the country, from Jamaica in particular, settling in there, w
ere not the right type for them to be living amongst, and that really, they should move away.  But, obviously, they didn\rquote t want to go too far either.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri113\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin113\lin1871\itap0\pararsid6571465 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid6571465\charrsid6571465 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 They thought they were poorer people?
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri113\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin113\lin1871\itap0\pararsid16140354 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid6571465\charrsid6571465 Harry:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 Well, not so much  poorer, yes, but it\rquote s also in terms of their behaviour.  They would have parties, for example.  They would make noise.  They wouldn\rquote 
t go to church.  Those sort of values.  And so one of the things whenever my parents would interview anyone for renting a room to, they would always ask them, \'93Where was your last address?\'94  And if it was in Brixton, they were very cautious.  It
\rquote s because of that notion that Brixton was beginning to emerge that all these Kingstonians, in particular, who came - and they\rquote re used to an urban Kingston life, after all, we know that in Kingston, there are a lot of crooks anyway \endash 
 and it\rquote s that country/town division that is still very strong in Jamaica, of the country bumpkins and the town element.  But for people from the countryside, Kingstonians are morally undesira
ble!  (LAUGHS)  So they would tend - and so the idea of living in Camberwell where, as I said, the streets, Southwell Road, which we lived at first, on that road there were this other family who was black, and ourselves, and just on the corner, on Northla
nd Street, there was a Cypriot family, that was the sort of colouration in that vast area in those years.  They just weren\rquote 
t around.  Certainly the Camberwell end, the same road, Coldharbour Lane, linking Brixton and Camberwell, was seen as different.  But 
in terms of shopping, my mother would always go to Brixton, established very strong relations with the grocers there, who it\rquote 
s only later on I realised that (1) they were Jews, and secondly, they themselves were migrants of not so long ago, from the East End!  And developed a relationship with them where she could either sometimes send us and say, \'93
Say to Natty, just give you the same items that I took last week, and next week I\rquote ll come and pay him\'94.  Or to say she had been shopping, and \'93It\rquote s all there, go and collect them\'94
 - as boys, after we got home from school.  So it was a good relationship of trust.  Until recently, until these families retired from their stores in Brixton, but certainly up to, I would say 15 years ago, whenever I passed through Brixt
on, I would pass by to say hello to the fishmongers, to the grocers.  One of them, in particular, Natty, would always stop everything, and say, \'93\rquote Ere, it\rquote s, it\rquote s, it\rquote s\'85
 " - he never always remember who I am, my name, specific name, call out one of the names and he said, \'93It\rquote s Lucy\rquote s son \endash  the professor!\'94
  (LAUGHS)  And he covered himself.  But, you realise that, from very early, they had become part of your existence, in a way.  Of course, the other aspect of that story, which is very important, and some wo
rk should be done to document that, going back to the idea that people couldn\rquote 
t borrow from banks or building societies and so forth, the partnership was useful, but they still needed bigger amount of monies for buying properties, was that they, like my father, would borrow money from moneylenders.  It\rquote 
s only later on I realised they were Jews who were willing to trust them, and obviously they were getting a good deal from it, but they were also estate agents, and they were willing to sell to them, whereas,
 if you went to the ordinary estate agents, they would show you some properties but not others.  Today, looking back after 40-odd years or so, it seems absurd, but that was was the situation.  And again, in those days, no Caribbean person lived in Council
 housing, because they were not eligible, so housing was a crucial, crucial area of social struggle and social existence.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 
