\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 And when did your parents buy their first house?
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri113\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin113\lin1871\itap0\pararsid16140354 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid6571465\charrsid6571465 Harry:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 They used to rent, and my mother said that once they had my youngest sister, Mavis, once she was born, they said, \'93Never again\'94
, partly because it was very difficult, if you had a child, to get rented accommodation.  No one wanted a couple with a child.  Indeed, even my parents who had experienced that, I remember them rentin
g once to an Irish family.  The fellow, himself, was a drunkard, and he had two children, and my mother pleaded and said, \'93Look, you can\rquote t let the children stay on the streets\'94
, so they rented a room to them.  And once to a young Caribbean woman, also with two children.  But apart from that, they would always be careful themselves.  And that was the story of the times that forced them to say, \'93
Look, whether we are staying on or not, we are now thinking that we must get a house\'94.  So they went and bought the
ir house.  And I suppose that simply took them back to their own background, that is that you own where you live.  And then as their children and others came, and family \endash  other relations \endash 
 they would help them to buy somewhere, and so it went on.  I was in France, recently, talking to a French sociologist, who had invited me to this Conference, and the matter of housing came up in the discussion, and I just said, \'93
Well, apart from as an undergraduate, I\rquote ve never lived in rented accommodation, because it\rquote s just such a strong thing in my family that you own," and she was shocked and surprised.  She said, \'93
But I thought all black people in England live in Council accommodation\'94.  So I said, \'93You must be a poor sociologist to think that, even though it may be so generally today, that it has always been so.\'94 (LAUGHS)  It\rquote 
s a curious perception!  (LAUGHS)  But I think it came out of that real need, that you must have somewhere, it doesn\rquote t matter what you have, if you don\rquote t have [a house] \'85 My father always stressed, \'93
Look, you can have as much money as you like in the bank, if that bank breaks down \'85\'94 and he used to talk about the \'93Great Crash\'94 - it was only years later I knew what he was talking about, the 1929 Crash \endash  \'93
You lose it all.  Whereas if you own housing, or you own land, even if the economy comes to the worst, you have somewhere to sleep, and you have somewhere to grow your own food\'94
.  And I found, when I was at work, and one of the reasons for moving on to the land, when I felt I was really threatened at work, I thought, \'93Well, if the worst comes to the worst, and we can\rquote 
t survive, if we have a piece of land around us, we can grow our own food\'94.  (LAUGHS)
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 
