\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri113\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin113\lin1871\itap0\pararsid16140354 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid6571465\charrsid6571465 Harry:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 Yeah, mm.  The popular music is sinful.  But you could graduate, so my oldest brother, George, he could have a radiogram.  I don\rquote 
t know if you remember those little things?  And he could buy his own records.  But if he was to play them, he\rquote d have to close the door!  (LAUGHS)  This is Satan\rquote 
s music!  But in terms of deference, respect, etc., entirely still a Jamaican household.  You go to school and you live in the one world there, and you go back into the door and it\rquote s another world.  Which I think that, to
day, probably that is so for a lot of kids of Asian backgrounds. Whereas I sense that most Caribbean households have become very Anglicised, in terms of working-class culture.  We\rquote re great adopters, great integrators \endash 
 not into the right sector, no ways, but we integrate into something that\rquote 
s there!  And I think we have picked up a lot of the less desirable aspects of popular base and common English culture.  Some of those are strong, and some of those are wonderful and good, and I think that\rquote s part of the 
bonding between communities that, in fact, that exists between people of Caribbean backgrounds in Britain, because if you observe, for example, people of Asian background, you might find family linkages in the middle-classes, but at the working-class leve
l, there isn\rquote t that.  Whereas with Caribbean people, perhaps it\rquote s the reverse, there\rquote s strong bonding and neighbourhood linkages and household linkages.  I think any part of London you walk, you\rquote 
ll see that.  You see people of all generations round there, elderly white men pushing black kids around, black babies with elderly white women, and they\rquote 
re obviously their grandkids, and so on.  That kind of social change, I think, is part of that great strength of both communities, of people to integrate and to mix in with each other.  \tab But as a result of that, there\rquote 
s also a price.  Your cultural baggage changes.  And that\rquote s no great loss.  That\rquote s inevitable in human relations.  And I think that has meant, certainly, that in terms of this principle, for example, of
 almost everyone I knew, as a child, of Jamaican background, in particular, striving to own their own [house], but that probably has gone.  It\rquote s not such a strong thing any more, for better or for worse. 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 
