\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 Well, then a delegation, my elder sister, who was in the house, and others came down for me to come up and have a talk with Daddy \endash 
 my father and Mummy.  So I went up, and, of course, you sit there, and the assumption is that you know what you have done wrong.  And, of course, you sense it, but you\rquote re not going to say anything.  And of course, it was, \'93
Who is this girl that you have brought into the house?\'94  (LAUGHS)  \'93Who are her parents?  Where does she live?\'94  (LAUGHS)  And, of course, I then had to explain and so on.  \'93
The next time you bring [a girl], you explain, you tell us beforehand.  As long as you do that, that\rquote s okay."  That sort of concern.  But in terms of mixing, the sort of white folks would have come home
, invited to eat, and for dinners, were nearly always estate agents, and they were also people who would lend money.  As I said, I didn\rquote 
t realise at the time, but that they were of Jewish background.  Later on you realise that they were.  I think there is a story there to be written, in terms of the assistance and the opportunities, also, for themselves.  It\rquote 
s vitally important.  And the photographers, Harry Jacobs in particular, and a couple of salespeople who also came in, and who would come and eat as well there.  But I think this relates not just to my family, but to Caribbean families generally.  I
\rquote ve often contended that you can\rquote t find Caribbeans, at least, not people of African backgrounds predominantly, who are racist, because deeply and profoundly e
mbedded in Caribbean culture is the notion of equality, respect of who or what you are.  You might hate a person, despise a person, but it\rquote s because of that particular person, it\rquote 
s not because the person belongs to a particular group, etc., and that\rquote s refl
ected in so many ways in aspects of Caribbean cultures.  So that, for example, when Selina and I started going out, or before that, as an undergraduate, the girls whom I went out with, of Polish background, a number of girls of English background, and the
y all came home and got to know my parents and family fairly well.  And when I went to see my father and mother and announced that we think that Selina and I would get married, they then asked what happened to these other girls?  (LAUGHS)  And I said, 
\'93Well, it\rquote s not them\'94.  And they were all white girls.  That didn\rquote 
t matter one way or the other.  The only concern they had, with regard to Selina, was that she is Catholic.  So her Catholic background was something which, given the Pentecostal Evangelicism for
 my mother, was important.  But in terms of culture, racial background, those things are not of any significance at all.  There was another occasion, when I remember there was a debate around this issue, a similar issue, and that was where a cousin of min
e \endash  the daughter of Aunt Emily, Kitty - she was doing something unusual, she was going to marry a man from the West Indies, but not Jamaican, from a \'93small island\'94 as they\rquote re called.  I can\rquote 
t remember which island, now, he was from, but he was not Jamaican.  Now, that was seen as strange.  But then they debated, and as kids, you simply sit in the background listening, that she must be careful, we don\rquote 
t know anything about their family, about this fellow\rquote s family, \'93We don\rquote t know anything about that country\'94, and so that was unusual.  But again, it\rquote s not on a racial basis too, because he\rquote 
s the same race, same colour, everything, but very much in terms of the difference in that sense.  My eldest brother, George, before he got married to a Jamaican woman, L}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid8141884\charrsid7427796 u}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 nette
, I think the main girlfriend he used to bring home was an Irish girl.  And again, she came, she ate, we used to tease her because of the way she pronounced certain Jamaican words!  (LAUGHS)  But there was never any animosity or sense of difference with p
eople whatsoever.  Yes, I think that is a very important part of Caribbean culture, if anything, some people would think we\rquote re too prone to mix, and my own view is that human beings \endash  taking a broad perspective of history \endash 
 the people we\rquote re now seeing are not the people who will be around in a thousand years time!  (LAUGHS)  We will have changed.  It\rquote 
s a constantly changing gallery of folks, and the only pure breed, in terms of physical existence in the cosmos, perhaps is when we talk about pure bred dogs, and it\rquote s only because we force them to be so!  We\rquote re all mongrels!
