\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 So, you did get interested a bit in politics?
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri113\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin113\lin1871\itap0\pararsid16140354 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid6571465\charrsid6571465 Harry:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 Well, only marginally, in the sense that when we were in the sixth form, two things happened, which was interesting for our Headmaster.  One was that one morning, we were assembled \endash 
 we used to have a Tuesday morning session, coffee session, with him, the sixth formers, not all the sixth formers, prefects and so forth \endash  and one morning he was very agitated and he said, \'93Did you boys watch television last night?\'94
  And I didn\rquote t, and most people didn\rquote t.  One fellow, Toogood, who was a typical sort of no-nonsense English kid from Herne Hill area, said, \'93Yes, sir, I did\'94.  And he said, \'93Did you hear what was said?\'94  And so Toogood said, \'93
Yes, Kenneth Tynan said \lquote Fuck\rquote \'94.  And the Headmaster leapt out of his seat!  (LAUGHS)  I don\rquote 
t know if you remember that incident?  But that was such an electrifying moment, (LAUGHS)  (1) to have seen it and heard it, secondly to repeat it in front of the Headmaster!  (LAUGHS)  That was the first time I was hearing of Kenneth Tynan!  One didn
\rquote t watch television in the sixth form, you\rquote re busy working!  (LAUGHS)  But the other one was a similar meeting where he asked, he wanted to know from us black k
ids, and there was only a couple of us, did we go to a meeting which was called somewhere in London, which turned out to be, later on I learnt, Stokeley Carmichael, visiting from the US and giving a talk about Black Power, because it was the height of Bla
c
k Power in America.  He wanted to know whether any of us had gone.  None of us had heard about it, but we became intrigued (LAUGHS) to know more about it!  (LAUGHS)  And so a very good friend of mine, Philip Murphy, he began to investigate, and so we bega
n to hear more.  The other thing which struck me, because I told you, earlier, I was in the technical stream, which meant that they didn\rquote t teach us foreign languages, once I realised that I was university material, whenever, in school, I didn
\rquote t have a class
, and whenever any French teacher was free, they had to teach me French, so every day I had French, and I must have had all the members of the French Department teaching me French!  (LAUGHS)  And so I had this intensive course by about four different peop
l
e.  Every day, two or three hours, at least, of French, about three years.  And the thing about that then was that one of these French women was quite struck to meet someone like me, who seemed to know something about literature and history and so forth, 
but absolutely nothing about black literature, about Black America, the Caribbean, Africa and so on.  And she had just done her thesis a year or so before, Master\rquote s thesis, at an American university, and did it on the poetry of L}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid8141884\charrsid7427796 a}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 ngston Hughes, so she gave me a copy to read, and this was an eye-opener.  \tab 
So from that, one began to realise there was a wider world still.  And it wasn\rquote t, however, until I got to university, and we began to learn about more of this, and this is why I think I did badly, as well, a
s an undergraduate.  I did badly in terms of my subjects.  Because all my teachers, both at university and at school, assumed that I would get a brilliant First, which I didn\rquote 
t, because most of the reading I did as an undergraduate was to do with Africa, which I wasn\rquote 
t studying formally, and Black America, and some stuff of the Caribbean.  Michael Heale was particularly good in that he enabled me and helped me to relate some of what I was reading to some of my courses, but much of it was not at all related.
  So I did an incredible amount of reading and so on, but they were not part of the formal courses that I was doing. That was a period of self-discovery, in terms of politics and so on.  So myself and a couple of others who had gone to school together, an
d who got to know each other, and were at different universities, we decided that what we would do was to start a new group called \'93Contemporary Blacks\'94
.  And then soon after we did that, we got in touch with other people in London, like John La Rose and ot
hers, who realised, here was a group of educated black people who knew all about this stuff.  So slowly we got pulled into the whole Black Power Movement, and it was from then that one\rquote 
s activism started.  And within that, of course, the reading of Marxism.
