\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri113\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin113\lin1871\itap0\pararsid16140354 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid6571465\charrsid6571465 Harry:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 I went \rquote 68, because, remember, I\rquote d missed a year out 
in school. You see, when I went to Lancaster, I thought, at that time, I began to have an interest in politics in a formal sense, that it would be good to get to Parliament, but it was a very formal, rigid way, and I thought, \'93
Well, student politics would be a good way to start\'94.  So within three weeks of being at Lancaster, I got elected as President of the JCR for my College \endash 
 a collegiate system.  And clearly, I was going to be the Head of the Student Union the following year, in the second year, and I was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\ul\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 the}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796  student politician of that year.  But by the end of the first year, I\rquote 
d really got into Black Power, and Marxism, and the discussion between the IMG - if you remember those groups - and various Trotskyist groups, and black politics: their view being that colour and race is neither here nor there, it\rquote 
s a class situation, and a number of us arguing, \'93Well, actually, class is important, but so is race, because of the base on which some people have been oppressed\'94. So I got very much involved in those ki
nds of debates, and shifted away from student politics somewhat.  By the time I left Lancaster, as a past Student President, they wrote to me to say I ought to be nominated to be a member of Council.  And I wrote back to them and said, \'93
Wherever the revolution is is where I am!\'94  (LAUGHS)  Michael sometimes still reminds me of this!  (LAUGHS)  Indeed, when I left Lancaster at the end of that period of three years, I was determined to go and join one of two groups \endash 
 the Black Panthers in Oakland, California, or the MPLA in Southern Africa, against the Portuguese.  I was determined to do so.  And this is where I was saying that I didn\rquote 
t go to see any Careers Planning Officers, I thought they were a lot of idiots, I just didn\rquote t do it.  And it was, literally, pa
ssing through Peckham and stopping at my old school, and going through this with the then Senior Master, who, only then I learnt, had been a member of the Communist Party, he said to me, \'93Look \'85\'94
