\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 
No, he was the Deputy Headmaster, the other one.  This one was the Senior Master, who when we were at school, he was fairly rough towards us, but now I was a graduate, and he had moved up in the system, he\rquote s now Senior Master, and we were talk
ing and he pointed out that when he was young, he was a member of the Communist Party and so forth, and what I was involved in, it would pass!  And he said, to plea to me eventually, he said, \'93
Look, instead of taking these decisions now, of going off to these places which you know nothing about, why don\rquote 
t you come and teach with us?  We have this job here.  Come here, teach history for the year, and at the end of it, decide what you want to do\'94.  This was purely accidental that I didn\rquote t go and ruin my life 
round me!  And during the course of that year, I realised that I was like a fish out of water.  I really missed university, because I didn\rquote t attend lectures and things like that very much.  I didn\rquote t even drink very much.  I didn\rquote 
t smoke.  But I lived in the bars and in the Students Union, and at meeting, and I felt I really missed that environment.  So I then got in touch with Michael, who had always been encouraging me to do a doctorate and said, \'93
Look, you know, I really should do something\'94.  He said, \'93Look, you didn\rquote t get your First, you have a good 2:1, which I can understand why you didn\rquote t, because you just didn\rquote 
t do the work.  But you did a lot of other work.  And if you really want to, you should do it\'94.  And then another chap, called Holmes, who tau
ght British History, mainly in the reign of Queen Anne, he had taken, under his umbrella, so to speak, about three or four of us in our second year, and said, after looking at a number of our essays, \'93Look, you chaps, you\rquote 
re good.  You may not get First, but look, I didn\rquote t get a First, I got a 2:1, and us 2:1 historians are better than the others\'94
.  Again, I drifted away from that, but I went back and I had a talk with them at the end of that year, and they said, \'93Yes, now that you\rquote re ready, we\rquote ll support you to wherever you want to go\'94
.  So they set up interviews at Edinburgh, Stirling - where there African History - at Cambridge and at Sussex.  And I went through to each of these, and as I said, the first choice was to go to Cambridge, but when I met the p
eople at Sussex, I thought this was the place to go to.  It was a sense, not necessarily to become an academic, but just to go and do a piece of work and think about what one will do with one\rquote 
s life.  And, of course, even with that finished, I still hadn\rquote t thought, really, what I wanted to do.  But I did feel very old.  I felt I\rquote d lost two years of my life \endash  one as a schoolteacher, and one when I went off to Ireland 
\endash  and I felt very old, compared to my contemporaries.  I was all of two years older than them!  (LAUGHS)  So at the grand age of 26, having finished my doctorate, and going off to East Africa, I felt, \'93Gosh\'94, you know, \'93I\rquote 
ve lived all these years, and what have I done with my life?\'94 I went to East Africa with a great sense of mission, that when I was going to go there, it\rquote 
s a great opportunity to, finally, to live on the continent, learn something about Africa, but with a lot of arrogance and stupidity.  
