\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 That was my rebellious phase!  That\rquote s right.  My rebellious phase was as an undergraduate, I think.  I think, very soon thereafter, one\rquote 
s going back to university, that changed.  Yeah, the rebellious phase for me, is very much my second and third years at Lancaster, and it was very much in terms of the issues around Marxism, liberation politics in Africa,
 Black America, how it applied in the British context, to a degree.  And during those two years, also, the big issue in Britain was, we were learning, for the first time, that the schools were pumping out a lot of black kids from ESN schools, and I got in
volved with John la Rose }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid8141884\charrsid7427796 and Bernard Ca}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 rd}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\insrsid8141884\charrsid7427796 ,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796  who had published, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 
How the British education system has made the West Indian child educationally subnormal}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 .  And so we took on that task of starting what is now quite popular, what was called the 
\'93Alternative School System\'94 of organising Summer Schools.  So I think one of the very first Summer Schools organised in London, was one I was involved with in \rquote 71 and \rquote 
72, where we took these kids who were being sent to ESN schools, and we said, \'93We\rquote re going to teach them the three R\rquote s, and some black history\'94
, which we did.  And recently I was tidying up some stuff in my study at the University, and came across some of the notes that some of these kids did, and I was jokingly saying, \'93They look more literate and better than some of our undergraduates today
\'94! (LAUGHS)  But we started that off, and one my Ph.D. students who has just got a doctorate, looking at some of those issues, and I was trying to impress on her, and giving her some of the documents that I still had from t
hose years.  The second big issue I became involved with, and Selina as well, and a couple of other colleagues, at that time, was the question of black prisoners.  Prisoners, black people in British prisons, because that started off, at the time, with you
ng people, for youth, but in \rquote 72 the police brutality against middle-aged black men also started.  So we founded, in Brixton, what was called the \'93Joshua Francis Defence Committee\'94
, I was the Secretary for that, and one of the main organisers.  And there\rquote s 
a number of black groups in London generally, who got together to organise around that.  So those were two crucial areas which, in terms of activism, one became very involved in.  When I decided to go to Sussex, I thought I would still continue to.  But, 
remember, in those days, you had to live proximate to the university, at least for your first year, which I did.  And I lived in Brighton for a year.  And Selina, during that year \endash 
 we had been living together for the previous year - but her parents wanted 
her to come home, and what was this business of her getting involved with a black man, and a revolutionary and all the rest of this?  So she had to go back, to Kenya.  And then they returned to India that year, and she went with them.  So I was very much 
o
n my own, and I found this golden period of loneliness, but one in which I buried myself into reading, since I was shifting from history to political science, and it took me back, so to speak, to my non-rebellious days of my sixth form days, of just soaki
ng up stuff.  I then became determined to say, \'93Look, I have a three-year SSRC Major Award, and I\rquote m going to get out of this place within three years\'94
, which, at Sussex, they treated as a joke, because in those days, no one did their doctorate in three years, you know!  Or very few!  And I said, \'93No, I\rquote m getting out.  I\rquote m going to do that, and then think about what I will do\'94
.  By the end of that period, of course, I\rquote d got married, and, of course, beginning to have a sense of responsibility, so my years of r
ebellion, in that regard, was basically those years.  By the time I got to Dar-es-Salaam, one was deeply into a more rigorous intellectual Marxism, and there it was very useful, because you had Marxists from East Europe, from China, from all over the worl
d
, from Cuba, Central America, and within Africa, with different intellectual traditions, wars of liberation going on around you, and a lot of the political leaders you rubbed shoulders with.  And no television.  Radio for one hour in the morning, half an 
hour in the evening.  One English newspaper!  So you have all the time in the world to read!  Our house became one of the centres of Reading Groups around Marx, around }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 Kapital
}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796  and so forth, and I shifted my interest from Caribbean, writing on the Caribbean, to writing on \endash  you know, in terms of research \endash 
 to where I was.  And I always feel that where you are, there are things to look at.  Looking at African politics, and so then got much more involved in that way.
