\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 Yes, there was.  I think what was positive was I felt I didn\rquote t want to be a schoolteacher, that\rquote s one thing!  Positive for me, perhaps negative in 
other ways!  But, profoundly, I think, it was getting involved in the local communities of Brixton, Camberwell and so on.  Indeed, in my book, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 
Caribbean Transnational Experience}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 , two of the chapters there \endash  because I, later on, gathered the publications around some of those activities \endash 
 and if you have a look at that, you\rquote ll see how I\rquote ve drawn on some of those, because I still have the documents from those days.  I suppose the historian in me was always never to get rid of documents!  Always keep them!  The
y always come in handy somewhere along the line!  And these are documents that very few of the players in those activities have kept, or have at all.  I\rquote m seeing a student next week, she\rquote s doing a doctorate at Sheffield, she\rquote 
s read that chapter and wants to come and discuss it, because she said she\rquote s heard vaguely about this, but she\rquote 
s never seen documentation, documentary evidence about those activities.  So the positive things about that was that, certainly. I am probably of a conservative (small c) bent,
 and I think partly out of my background and so on, and that ever since returning to university after that year, I think, \'93Well, I\rquote 
m never going to be the great revolutionary, but I do want to understand what is it that makes people tick?  And what is it that brings about social action on the part of others?"  And hence one\rquote 
s interest in Marxism, and, of course, that was the intellectual dominant sway at the time as well.  But part of the thing, too, of my reaction partly against Marxism, before the death o
f this centralised State Socialism in the nineties, was that by the end of my Dar-es-Salaam phase I felt I was coming into a situation which may not have been that dissimilar from when I was under the sway of my mother, and of the Church, namely that peop
le looked at events, at social action, and predetermined causes before understanding those events.  And, therefore, that was not intellectually honest.  I like Marx, I might have to say that I\rquote 
m not a Marxist, because whilst at the same time respecting Marx
ism, and so for me, a sort of a Leninist distinction from Marxism began to emerge, and certainly also what I saw from Tanzanian Socialism began to point to me that this is not really what I would want to be closely akin to, and reverting into perhaps a mo
r
e intellectual posture of Marxism, rather than the more practical Leninist-cum-Stalinist development of it.  And so now, I find myself, to a degree, perhaps being far more conservative (small c), and conservatism is not the right word probably, on some is
s
ues, people would see me as being very much that.  So when I returned to this country, and for the first time really started to work in the area of race, some of the views I expressed amongst people who were working in that, they thought I was up the wall
!
