\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 By this time, ce
rtainly.  It had only been three years since I was a pupil there myself, but by this time, in the early seventies - as I mentioned when I went there in 1960/61 or so, there were 1600, and only about a dozen of us were from outside of Britain, including So
uthern Europe/Cyprus \endash 
 there were a couple of Sri Lankans and ourselves from the Caribbean, and there was one kid from Africa.  Apart from that, it was all whites.  Then, go ten years on, and that had changed dramatically.  There's still a majority of white
 kids, but quite a number of young black kids who were desperate to know who and what they were.  And in the school a lot of discussions were held, particularly with the Senior Master, who was quite open, being a member of the Communist Party, about teach
ing some of these black kids about Caribbean history.  And we said, \'93Well, actually, I don\rquote t know much myself!  And I don\rquote t think that having people around you who knows anything at all about it, but I\rquote m willing to learn\'94
.  One of the profound impacts that Fred Murphy, whom I\rquote ve mentioned earlier, had on me, was this, that if there\rquote 
s anything you want to learn about, adopt this mental posture that you can learn about it, so that, for example, when we started doing \lquote A\rquote  Level history with him, and there were, in those days, three papers for \lquote A\rquote 
 Levels, and he took out the syllabus and said, \'93What are you interested in?  I\rquote ll teach whatever area\'94.  And we were quite amazed.  So we chose three areas, one of which was American history.  And he said, \'93I know nothing about it, but we
\rquote ll learn it together\'94.  I\rquote ve always adopted that as well since, that you don\rquote t know about a thing, but you know how to learn about it.  And so I said we\rquote 
ll be willing to. But then, the more I thought of going back to university to do a doctorate, I thought, \'93Well, why should I want to do African history when I don\rquote 
t know any of the languages?  I should be looking at something in terms of understanding the Caribbean\'94.  So in those ways, certainly that year had quite an influence on subsequent behaviour, subsequent thinking, in a way.
