\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 Well, I met Selina in \rquote 68, because a good friend of
 mine who was  - when we were applying to universities, none of us in London wanted to apply to London University colleges, because if you did, you had to stay at home, because residence was given to kids coming from outside, and a number of the kids at o
u
r school, who were great mathematicians and went to Imperial, they came back to use our Common Room at the school because there were very little facilities, in those days, in the London system.  Of course, for me, going to university was going to be a lib
eration, I sensed that, and I didn\rquote t want to be at home.  Indeed, I applied to all the universities at least 200 miles away from London \endash  York, Lancaster, Aberystwyth \endash 
 all the outlandish places!  (LAUGHS)  And as soon as Lancaster came in, I withdrew from the others, so that\rquote 
s one to go to.  Part of that was that.  But, nonetheless, and this particular friend, Philip Murphy, he went to Southampton, and he had gone for an interview and he said he had met this person, a beautiful Indian girl who showed him ar
ound, and that was that conversation.  Then he went off.  And then at the first Christmas we met in London, and he said, \'93A friend is coming to visit.  I\rquote d like you to meet her\'94
.  And I met her.  And then they went out for a while, and then they stopped, a
nd then I came to London.  Selina graduated, and she came to London to do the Bar, because she did law, so she was doing the Bar at Grays Inn, and then after that she decided to do a Masters in Law as well, and she was very much involved with all these po
litical events that were going on at the same time.  And I came to London, you know, in \rquote 71 or so, leaving Lancaster, and I think it\rquote 
s in that period that we started then going out together.  And then we decided, I suppose we decided within a matter of mont
hs, that we would get married. And as I was saying, her parents became very very concerned and had her taken back to Kenya, with the idea that they would marry her off there.  Then they decided, in \rquote 
72, to go back to India, and she had to accompany them.  
The basic story there was that a line of young men were introduced with the intention that she had better choose between one, because they were never going to let her out of their sight again.  And so she had to, through devious ways, find her way to Bomb
ay, 400 miles away, and then got a brother-in-law \endash  her sister\rquote s husband there, who worked with Air India \endash 
 to get her a visa to come to London.  And she did.  And a couple of weeks after, because we felt we would go to Jamaica and get married the way my pa
rents had gone back to, though I was dreading it, because I hate this wedding business!  But I knew they would expect it of us.  So I had a call from Selina\rquote 
s, one of her sisters, whose husband was working up in Glasgow, at Glasgow University, as an economist, Vince Cable, he\rquote 
s the main economic spokesman, now, in Parliament, for the SDP, and he was teaching economics at Glasgow.  Olympia rang and just said, \'93Look, if you intend to marry your girlfriend, you\rquote d better go and do it now, because our father has
 decided that he\rquote s going to try and get the British government to deport her\'94
.  So it became really high politics, you know!  (LAUGHS)  So we, literally, the following the day, just went down to the Registry Office in Brighton, took out the relevant documents, and a couple of days later got married.  (LAUGHS)  That was in \rquote 
73.  By this time it was \rquote 73.
