Yes.  My methodologies were multiple, which I always attempt to.  One, the historical records themselves, so I did a lot of work at the PRO and the equivalent in Kingston.  All the Parliamentary debates and documents.  All the reports from the Government 
Departments \endash  Education Department there and here.  Colindale, the newspaper coverages, both at Colindale and in Jamaica.  And so that\rquote 
s sort of the solid documentary aspects.  Then, for more contemporary, also, the publications of the Union, which were sca
ttered, and I had to bring them together, because they were in different places.  And then thirdly, of course, interviews of leaders and the schoolteachers, many of whom had retired, some of them in Old People\rquote 
s Homes, some of them retired, some who were from this country, retired across Britain.  So I did an immense amount of interviews of them.  [Fourthly] attending their meetings, and they allowed me to \endash 
 their Executive Meetings, Regional Conferences etc..  So, and I\rquote ve always felt that, in that regard, it\rquote s important - I\rquote 
ve become a little uneasy where pieces are written around one methodology only, rather than backing it up with what they now call \'93triangulation\'94, to have it from a number of sources.  I think that\rquote s true, and it comes much more from my
 history than from social science as such.  And one of my dissatisfactions, at the moment, with much social science, particularly at the doctoral level, is that people are being encouraged to say, \'93
Go and do a set of interviews with, say, 10, 15, 20 actors, and write up a thesis\'94.  Okay, that\rquote s fine.  But so what?  (LAUGHS)  I think it\rquote s important, to use a Jamaican word, to have \'93backative\'94
, to support that with other documentations to make it a much more rounded thing, and that\rquote s what I did with that.  I 
was tempted, also, to try to use a kind of a survey for when I was doing my thesis, but I was persuaded that, given what I was doing, it wasn\rquote t at all necessary.  And I think they were right.  I don\rquote 
t think it would have marred the work, and it wouldn\rquote t have enriched it in any way.  
