ve, since those days, taken the advice of the late M.G. Smith whom I remember having a talk with some years ago, where he said, \'93Look, if you keep dwelling with the same text, becaus
e of whatever problems you have with publishers and so forth, and you don\rquote t get on to your next book, you get into a morass\'94.  At the time, I didn\rquote 
t quite understand what he was saying.  But since his death, Yale University has taken on publishing his total work, and there\rquote s an immense amount of books which have never seen the light of day, that they\rquote 
re now publishing, of his work.  But his view was, \'93Look\'94, you know, \'93as soon as you finish one book, don\rquote t spend too much time on it, move on to your next\'94.  (LAUGHS)  And in a sense, that\rquote s what I\rquote 
ve done with that, and I don\rquote t suppose, now, I shall ever go back to it.  I would have to re-learn }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid8141884\charrsid7427796 Kiswahili}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
