\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 Well, not - I learned it in two ways.  One, I used to do the shopping \endash  I still do, the household shopping \endash 
 and to go to the market I was fairly conversant with counting, bargaining and so on \endash  in that culture, you have to bargain.  The second, I could read the documents, and I could follow conversations, not for an extended period of time, but I couldn
\rquote t actually have an intelligent conversation in the language as such.  It\rquote s partly because we had to teach in English, because Tanzanian students, they only start learning English at secondary school level, by the time they
're half way through secondary school, so when they come to university, they\rquote re keen to use English only, and that\rquote 
s what you taught in.  But the people who learnt the language well were mainly people who worked in the villages and outside of the city.  So
 I spent a lot of time learning the grammar, so the paradox was that I knew the grammar, and Selina had the vocabulary \endash  from Kenya \endash  but she didn\rquote 
t have the grammar!  (LAUGHS)  So I learnt it enough to read some of the stuff, and some which I couldn\rquote t understand I had to have colleagues translate for me.
