\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 Can you tell me something more about interviewing politicians.  Because many people find that particularly difficult.  The typical interview technique is based on empathy, isn\rquote 
t it.  So how do you get politicians to talk?
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri113\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin113\lin1871\itap0\pararsid16140354 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid6571465\charrsid6571465 Harry:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 Now, that\rquote s a tough one!  That\rquote s a very tough one.  I\rquote ll illustrate how tough that can be.  When I was interviewing a number of leaders of the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\insrsid8141884\charrsid7427796 Kalistan}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796  Movement.  It\rquote 
s a group in the Punjab who wanted to break away from India, and it was very strong in the late eighties/early nineties, and in Britain I was interviewing some of them.  They had formed a government in exile \endash  the Kalistan 
Council.  And they used to allow me to come to their meetings, and sit in them, and for my purposes they would speak in English and so forth.  And I read their documents, and I was very much amongst them.  But there would be times when you\rquote 
re interviewing a person who had very clear ideas that you disagreed with.  But as you say, there is that aspect of empathy, to get things out, to understand what your respondent is saying and so on.  And I learnt, I developed a grunt, which meant, \'93
Yes, I can hear what you\rquote re saying, but don\rquote t think that I agree nor disagree with you\'94, and I find that I still do that now!  (LAUGHS)  It\rquote s become a habit almost, because in talking to another human being, you can\rquote 
t sit there dumb and totally silent, you must be seen to be en
gaging, and you must engage authentically and genuinely.  But at the same time, what happens, as in a case I was interviewing, not a Kalistani now, well, a person from East Africa, who was expressing some most racist ideas about Africans.  And taking for 
granted that I agreed.  Now, you don\rquote 
t want to get into a discussion about your own views about the matter, you want to hear what the person is saying, so either you jeopardise, then, the interview, and call it off, or you listen.  And in one instance where
, again, neither of those instances, a third instance where I was interviewing a professional person about political matters, about politics, and the person began to incorporate me into his racist views about Asians, and that sort of tension comes about, 
how do you let it be known that you\rquote re not sharing those views?  And so I waited until the end of the interview and then, you know, it wasn\rquote t being tape-recorded, I stopped, formally stopped, and I said, \'93Well, actually, I\rquote 
m not a racist and I can\rquote t share those views with you.  In fact, part of my family are Asians,\'94 and you could see him going under the table!  (LAUGHS)}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16140354  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 One time, I almost did interview Enoch Powell, and I felt I could handle it, felt I could have handled it, and I always regret that I didn\rquote 
t, because when I sent that particular book, it was sent to the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 Journal of Social and Economic Studies}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 , for review.  It\rquote s the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 Ethnicity and Nationalism}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 
 book.  And they sent it from the Caribbean to who?  To Enoch Powell, to review!  Which he did!  (LAUGHS)  So I kept feeling I should have followed my instinct and interviewed him!  But I think, it\rquote 
s always the case, with politicians' interviews, you\rquote re quite right, it is very difficult, because people expect that what they\rquote re talking about in political terms, what they would call your \'93demonic position\'94
 is the same as theirs, and because you have a sympathetic appearance and face, and you\rquote re listening carefully to what they\rquote re saying, they just assume that you\rquote re part of that process.  And there was one insta
nce I recall people wanting me to stand on a platform with them, and to be photographed, again, being incorporated into their mission, into their purposes, and that is, of course, something which I think the researcher has to avoid. The anthropologist wou
ld not, the anthropologist would say, \'93No, it\rquote s all part of that picture.  It\rquote s all part of that, that you are, indeed, within it\'94, there\rquote 
s not the rigidity of interviewer/interviewee.  But I think that there are instances, even for them, where there has to
 be a distinction, and you have to try to find a way, respectfully, ethically, morally, of making the difference and letting them know that, \'93Okay, I can hear what you\rquote re saying.  I\rquote 
ll even report you as close to your position as possible, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\ul\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 but}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796  that\rquote s not my position\'94
.  And that is, that is difficult.  If you\rquote re looking at a group with which you have a great deal of empathy and sympathy, obviously it\rquote s not so difficult, but if you\rquote 
re looking at, say, a right-wing political group, or right-wing politicians, or racists, you\rquote re talking to people and they have certain assumptions, sometimes you leave, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\ul\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 I}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796  leave, feeling terribly insulted and bruised and hurt, and keep thinking, it\rquote s one of Elliot\rquote 
s poems where the character says, Pruefrock, \'93I might have said something\'94.  You have that feeling that you could have said something, and you know you want to have said something, but you give the respondent \endash  the other person \endash 
 the benefit of the doubt, because, after all, the experience is more theirs that you\rquote re trying to capture, than your own, and that, I think, perhaps, of a bad situation, is the better position to take.
