\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri113\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin113\lin1871\itap0\pararsid6571465 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid6571465\charrsid6571465 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 But there\rquote s also the problem, with some politicians, you never get beyond the front. So they might be racist, but they wouldn\rquote t say so.  So did you have techniques for getting beyond \'85

\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri113\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin113\lin1871\itap0\pararsid16140354 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid6571465\charrsid6571465 Harry:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 Yes.  Let\rquote s see.  I think, since it\rquote s always a basis of treating that particular individual, I think I have been successful in getting the person sufficiently relaxed for them to fee
l that they can say to me what they want to say.  I realise, quite often, it\rquote 
s because they think that my physical empathy with them, so to speak, my immediate empathy, goes as far as to their views, though if they were to reflect on that, they would see that it\rquote s absurd.  But I\rquote 
ve not found that it is so difficult for them to say what they want to say to me, and that may have something to do with how they see - well, it definitely has something to do with how they see me as the interviewer, that they can d
o that.  And sometimes they will say, of course, \'93Well, of course, this is off the record", and I said, \'93Yes\'94.  Occasionally, people might have said things to me where I say, \'93Look, I\rquote m not going to take a note of that".  I\rquote 
ll listen to that, but I\rquote m not g
oing to [use it] in any way, because I think one of the things that the researcher has to do is to protect himself/herself, and their publishers, from potential dangers as well.  You know if you were to say it, they could sue you, and they would simply sa
y, \'93Look, we didn\rquote t say it\'94, so you don\rquote 
t!  (LAUGHS)  One of my students, recently, one of my doctoral students, I had to advise him closely on that, because what he was working on, his respondents were remarkably frank and open, and these were about politi
cal state matters, in terms of international agreements.  So I simply said, \'93Look, write it out as you have it.  Let me have a look before anyone else, and we\rquote ll go through it closely and edit it\'94.  And I think it worked.  \tab 
But it leads to the view where I remember, in the past, some Caribbean social scientist making the point that the social scientist has to be a novelist also, because you get so much material!  (LAUGHS)  And that it\rquote 
s only in the novel that you can say it.  And if you notice, some politicians now, when they retire, that\rquote s what they tend to do, they write a novel, because all they need to do is to have a disclaimer!  (LAUGHS)
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri113\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin113\lin1871\itap0\pararsid6571465 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid6571465\charrsid6571465 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 Yes.  Yes!  And, Harry, I know you wrote about Nyerere, did you interview him?
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri113\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin113\lin1871\itap0\pararsid16140354 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid6571465\charrsid6571465 Harry:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 I never interviewed him.  And when he died, recently, at St. Thomas\rquote s, I felt very bad really, because I had the opportunity to, in a way, because I knew people very close to him and said, \'93
Whenever you want to, you know, just do it\'94.  And I\rquote ve often felt that if I hadn\rquote t backed away from Tanzania so much, I\rquote 
d have loved to have done a critical political assessment of him.  Because he was such a major figure, and I think, a great contributor to understanding African politics.  His contribution there has been second to none, in s
o many ways.  I think Nelson Mandela, perhaps, is the only one who you could say \endash  and he has been lucky \endash  who\rquote s a bigger figure.  But Nyerere was outstanding in many ways\'85
 In African politics, in those days, the only person who could say anything about po
litics was the President.  Never mind this idea of political theorising and so forth.  And so Nyerere, of course, wrote a lot, and all his speeches were published, so you could write about what he said, and because he said so much, there\rquote 
s a lot of material to draw upon.  Then I wrote a piece on the Party, in Tanzania, and for it to be published, I had to talk to the Vice-Chancellor for permission.  So I went to see him, and we talked about it, and he looked at it and he said, \'93It
\rquote s okay.  You can publish it\'94.  So it was published.  And I said, \'93Well, actually, I\rquote d like to follow this through and investigate the Party, write on the Party as a whole\'94, and he said, \'93
Well, to have that, you have to speak to the President\'94 \endash  the President of the Party is also the President of the country \endash  \'93or to the Secretary General of the Party\'94, and I thought, \'93Well, I\rquote m new to this place, I can
\rquote t do that\'94.  About a year later, the Vice-Chancellor became the Secretary General of the Party.  So I then went to see him, and I said, \'93
You remember we were talking about this some time ago, and you said if I were to approach either the President or the Secretary General, I could have permission\'94.  He laughed, and he said, \'93Yes, I do remember!\'94  He said, \'93Okay.  Here it is.  I
\rquote ll give you a letter, and you can go to the Party Headquarters, and they will give you permission to see anything you want, and you can attend any meeting you want\'94
.  And it was on the basis of that that I was able to.  I had a Tanzanian colleague who would accom
pany me for some of the meetings.  And in some of those meetings, they would not speak with him present, others they would, and so on.  But I think what it was, being an African from outside of Africa \endash  so I have proximity but also have distance 
\endash  there\rquote s nothing I could say or do which could influence Tanzanian politics, and that goes without saying.   There were some radicals who felt they could, and that was a misunderstanding.  They couldn\rquote 
t really have, I mean, outsiders.  It\rquote s a very tight nationalist framework.  So that was part of the reason why I had that permission.  And so it\rquote s a great shame that it\rquote s never really seen greater light of day.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri113\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin113\lin1871\itap0\pararsid6571465 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid6571465\charrsid6571465 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 I\rquote m not sure whether I\rquote ve got this right, but I have the impression that you went to Tanzania, partly because you wanted to return to Africa, and also as a Socialist ideal.  Is that right?

\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri113\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin113\lin1871\itap0\pararsid16140354 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid6571465\charrsid6571465 Harry:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 Yes.  I think both, really.  When I finished my doctorate, I had three offers of jobs.  One was something in Manchester, which wasn\rquote 
t academic, it was working in a community based thing, which I didn\rquote t particularly want.  I was more or less offered a job at the London Business School, but I thought I couldn\rquote t face friends in those days, in \rquote 75, and say, \'93I
\rquote m working at the London Business School\'94!  (LAUGHS)  And, third, was an offer of both Selina and I to work in Guyana, same Department \endash  the Department of Law and Politics.  And the fourth was to Dar-es-Salaam.  Walter Rodney had just l
eft Dar-es-Salaam, and we met in London, and he said, \'93Look, no, man, you must come to Guyana\'94.  And I said, \'93Well, you know, I think I\rquote d like to go to Africa, to have an African experience\'94
.  Selina wanted to go to Guyana because she knew East Africa, she\rquote s from there, and I said, \'93No, no, come on, we\rquote ll go to East Africa\'94
.  I think it sprung from, I might not have mentioned earlier, but one of the great figures for me, when I had a political awakening as an undergraduate at Lancaster, was really the figur
e of Kwame Nkrumah, who used to be one of the few black figures we used to see on television when we were kids, and at that time, we thought he was just a mad nutter, that\rquote 
s how he was portrayed, until those years when I started reading his material.  And 
so the idea of going to Ghana was very much to go to the land of the great Kwame Nkrumah.  Whilst I was there, I was just hitch-hiking around the place, but I was treated remarkably nicely by people at the University there, at Lagos, and so I became convi
nced that it would be nice to come back here as a student.  Had I gone to Edinburgh, that\rquote s what I would have done.  So, years later, when I got this post in Dar-es-Salaam, people kindly invited me to come there, I thought, \'93
Well, the struggle for Africa is really in Southern Africa, and the centre of that struggle is Tanzania\'94
, because all the diplomatic and the political centre of these things were there, including a lot of the training for armed uprisings.  I thought it would be a wonderful experience to go there, by which time I\rquote d started reading Nyerere\rquote 
s works, and so there was no way I was going to let that go by.  So that was really the main reason for that \endash  (1) to go to Africa, but I knew that East Africa isn\rquote t so much part of her cultural baggage, 
in the way that West Africa is.  West Africa is the important place.  But by this time, the pan-Africanist notion, Nkrumah\rquote s view, that Africa is one, which is, of course, not true, but it\rquote 
s an ideological position, and so to go there was a great thing.  And I\rquote 
d met people from there who had encouraged me to come there.  And the way we got those posts was, I just met some East African academics at a party in London, who were friends of a comrade who was the leader of the Cameroonian Communist Party in exile
 in London, and we went to dinner, and we met these friends, and they asked what I was going to do, and I said, \'93Well, you know, we\rquote re looking for jobs\'94
, and the next thing we knew, we had these two contracts from Dar-es-Salaam, which was rather nice! You know, until my last two positions, I usually say that I\rquote ve not actually applied for jobs as such.  I\rquote 
ve been very fortunate that people actually ask whether you would like to have this job or that job.  And certainly the, in both those instances, I didn\rquote t 
apply.  I had to apply later on.  And then when we finished in Dar-es-Salaam, and I wanted to be in Jamaica, I\rquote d long said to people, I\rquote 
d love, if they have a job, to come.  And then on one occasional visit, they said they had a job, and if I wanted it, I could come.  And I said, \'93Well, what about people in law, would Selina have a job?\'94  And they spoke to them, and they said, \'93
Yes, there\rquote s a job\'94, so we went!  Then when I was thinking of coming back to this country, I don\rquote t know if you remember, in \rquote 83, I 
came and went around, and I met people at Warwick, and then about six months later, I was then Dean of the Faculty of Social Science at Mona, and I used to have lunch for the secretaries and the administrators, from time to time, at home, and I had this l
unch out in the garden, and I had a phone call, and it was from Warwick, saying, \'93We have this one-year Fellowship, and we know that you might be interested in it.  Would you like to come?\'94  (LAUGHS)  And so I said, \'93Fine!\'94
  And so I then went to Warwick for that year, and towards the end of it, Robin Cohen and others said, \'93There is this job.  You have to compete for it.  You have to apply.  But, you know, we think you stand a very good chance\'94
.  So I put in, and I got it!  You know, so in a sense, I\rquote ve had a charmed life, in terms of jobs.  (LAUGHS)  The job at the London Business School was for someone who was an economist, and I\rquote 
d applied, and they interviewed me, and they said, \'93Well\'94, you know, \'93quite clearly, you\rquote re not an economist, and this is not for you, but we have a job coming up soon, and if you want it, just let us know\'94
.  But then, as I said, I had this feeling, \'93I can\rquote t go (LAUGHS) through with it!\'94  So, basically, the thing about Africa, for me, it was important to live and work there at some
 point, in the same way as it was important to live and work in Jamaica, in the Caribbean, and to get to know the region.
