\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 Well, to a large extent.  I found t
hat Tanzanian Socialism was really African Nationalism, and I made a distinction clearly between those.  And, in any event, it was a kind of nationalism that excludes foreigners\'85 I\rquote 
ll illustrate it this way.  I have a Tanzanian friend whose husband is Fren
ch, and they both share similar nationalist make-up, and I encouraged both of them to take up a post which was offered to them at the University of the West Indies in Jamaica, and they went there, they went about a year before us, from East Africa.  When 
we got there, how absurd Jamaicans are!  Why?  Because elections were coming up, and she could vote.  "What sort of country is this, that allows foreigners to [vote?]" So I laughed and said, \'93
Well, you know, Nationalism in East Africa is a different thing from nationalism.  It\rquote s not that it\rquote s not there, but the fact that you\rquote re coming from another Commonwealth country, and you\rquote ve lived here, you\rquote 
re paying your tax, then it\rquote s part of the democratic make-up here that you have a right to vote, provided you regi
ster.  But they saw that as utterly absurd.  Now, for me, that seemed to me to be human!  (LAUGHS)  In East Africa, however, as long as you live there, you are still the foreigner.  It comes, of course, out of their struggle against Imperialism and Coloni
a
lism.  I realise that their struggles, and what they were involved in, were different from my struggles.  And Jamaica, in that regard, in terms of those values, is much closer.  But again, living in Jamaica, after a while, one realised, too, that without 
perhaps knowing it, you become more English than you are willing to admit.  So that in Jamaica, I was an Englishman.  In England, I might be a Jamaican \'85
