\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri113\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin113\lin1871\itap0\pararsid6571465 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid6571465\charrsid6571465 Harry:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 I was an Englishman.  In fact, (LAUGHS) I had a humorous letter, which I kept for years!  At the end of my first two years there.  I used to teach a huge class \endash  Introduction to Political Theory 
\endash  and at the end of my second year, when my two-year contract\rquote s come to an end, I had this letter just before the last lecture, and it went something like this, almost word for word.  \'93
We do not want any foreigners in our country to teach us, and we don\rquote t want any Imperialist from the Imperialist country.  In any event, we don\rquote t want an Imperialist with a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\insrsid8141884\charrsid7427796 Mhindi }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 (that meant Indian) wife\'94
.  And so it went on!  (LAUGHS)  I was completely dumbfounded, because, as a class, we had very good relationships.  And I thought, \'93How best to tackle this?\'94  So I went in and gave my lecture as usual, and then I, at the very end, said, \'93I just 
want to thank the person\'94 - or, because it was written in the plural - \'93the persons who sent me this letter, and I\rquote ll just read it to the rest of you.  And I know it\rquote 
s not the view of most of you, or, perhaps, the vast majority of you.  But I\rquote ll just read this aloud\'94
.  And I did.  And then left.  And by the time I got to my room, the whole corridor was filled with them!  (LAUGHS)  They wanted to see the letter, to see if they could find out who had written it, so they could go and \'85 (LAUGHS) \tab It\rquote 
s obviously not typical, in any sense of the stretch of the imagination.  But you learn, basical}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11762819\charrsid7427796 ly, that people see you as [for}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 eign].  And that lived experience, your lived experience, may be more what you are than what you have in your head, thinking that you are.  
So for me, the sojourn in Africa, the sojourn in the Caribbean, was of vital importance in coming to terms with who I think I am, and what I am.  It does exorcise that.  I\rquote m not worried any more.  I\rquote 
m not caught up in any kind of angst about oneself \endash  in t
hose kinds of ways.  Whereas, now, when coming back to Britain, meeting people, talking with them, I realise that they have not had those journeys, and so they, in their imagination, their heads, and their experiences, they have to struggle with this all 
the time, and so they\rquote re caught up in a real struggle as to who they are, what they are.  Are they British, or not British?  Are they this, are they that?  And so forth and so on.
