\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 So what do you say in answer to that question, then?
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri113\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin113\lin1871\itap0\pararsid16140354 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid6571465\charrsid6571465 Harry:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 Well, I think I feel that, in many respects, I am English, or British \endash  the two are not quite the same, obviously \endash 
 but I am also more than that, in that I feel that I am partly Jamaican.  I feel, given my experience, and a reflection on those experiences, that I am, perhaps, a cosmopolite, that I\rquote 
m something which I feel I can be fairly relaxed within a number of contexts, and what is important to me are a set of values, and those values, in respect of which society I live in, I wouldn\rquote t want to force them down anyone\rquote s throat, but I
\rquote ll be prepared to defend them.  And that is profoundly a sense of equality of all human beings, a sense of fairness to people, that I don\rquote t think anyone is superior to me, I don\rquote t think I\rquote 
m superior to anyone.  I would not go to war to fight for, or support anything pertaining to domination on the basis of creed or colour, and those sorts of things.  I think, as individual human beings, you have to be careful to find that you wouldn
\rquote t do that.  And yet, if there\rquote s a just cause for the rights of others, that you\rquote ll be willing to defend those.  And so those are values which I think are important, and I don\rquote 
t think they are the privilege of any one group, any one individual, in any context. I love England, and I love Jamaica!  (LAUGHS)  In different ways.  There are other places in the world which I like, but I wouldn\rquote 
t say I would particularly give my left hand for, so to speak, and I think the reason for those is because these are places where I\rquote ve lived, and where I feel I understand those societies.  I think it\rquote 
s very difficult to articulate a clear, unambiguous view about self in relation to others, because these are what you might hold, as to how many of your fellow human beings out there who hold them, you don\rquote t know.  No?  You know som
e do, to one degree or another, and they\rquote re not necessarily your countrymen or countrywomen, they cut across these boundaries, they cut across these boundaries very significantly.
