\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri113\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin113\lin1871\itap0\pararsid16140354 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid6571465\charrsid6571465 Harry:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 I probably did then.  Yes, that\rquote s right.  But I don\rquote t think of that, I don\rquote t even think that that person\rquote s going to see
 me first as black, you know?  So I just set it aside.  And I think it\rquote s deliberate, it\rquote s conscious, because I\rquote m aware, when I\rquote m in Jamaica, for example, and you\rquote 
re talking about a third party, people will describe that person in colour terms, very very much so.  In India, similarly.  And you realise that people, when they look at you, quite often, or listen to you, they\rquote re not necessarily hearing what you
\rquote re saying.  They\rquote re }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\ul\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 seeing}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 
 you.  And that is what is important.  And sometimes I test people on this, 
in a variety of ways.  Like I was travelling on the train from Euston to Coventry, and three black men, clearly from West Africa, got on board, and we started talking, and after a while they asked me where I was from \endash 
 the leader of the group.  So I said I was from London.  There is a silence.  I know what\rquote s happening.  There is a silence.  And then he asked me the question again, and I said, \'93From London\'94
.  And I ask him where is he from?  And I had a sense he was West African, but Sierra Leone.  He then came back to ask me where I was from.  When I repeated the same again, \'93London\'94, he says to his mates, \'93This black man doesn\rquote 
t know who he is\'94.  (LAUGHS)  And he didn\rquote t realise I was playing with him, in a sense!  But I\rquote m playing with his consciousness, bec
ause he assumed that, in looking first, at your colour, and he then assumed they know who and what you are.  But I\rquote 
ve had that experience so often from East Africa days.  One incident, which I might have related to you in the past, we ordered a soup, and this fellow, after about an hour it hadn\rquote t come, and I asked him why, and the other person said, \'93
Well, he\rquote s not taken your order, because you\rquote ve not given it in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid8141884\charrsid7427796 Kiswahili}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 \'94
.  So I said, \'93Look, I\rquote ve only been here a week, I don\rquote t know the language\'94.  The fellow then joined him, comes in and said, \'93How can you say you don\rquote t know }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\insrsid8141884\charrsid7427796 Kiswahili}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 ?  Every black man, every African speak }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid8141884\charrsid7427796 Kiswahili
}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796 \'94.  So we got into a discussion, a discourse about }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid8141884\charrsid7427796 Kiswahili}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4151349\charrsid7427796  and Africans.  I said, \'93You\rquote re not telling me that all Africans in Africa speak Ki Swahil\'94.  He said, \'93Yes, they do\'94, because that is his experience.  Then he said, \'93
Well, where are you from?\'94  And I said, \'93Well, I\rquote m from London\'94.  And he said, \'93Well!\'94  He laughed and laughed, and they laughed.  \'93How can a black man be from the Imperialist country?\'94  He thought only white men \'85
 (LAUGHS)  And so, I think identity is usually partly self-defined and partly externally defined, and you live on those boundaries, in a way, you know?  But I think you live with yourself more in t
erms of who you think you are, than what others think, and you can\rquote t live with what all others think about who and what you are.  And I think, if it hadn\rquote 
t been for travelling abroad, living and working abroad, and coming across a variety of situations, and being able to reconcile with these and think through them, then I think I would probably have answered the first thing, \'93I\rquote m a black man\'94
, or that I\rquote m an African.  I met a group of young black people, recently, at a dinner party, and they came out with some shiboliths, so I was a bit bored, so I decided to take on board one or two of these views.  I said, \'93
What makes you an African?\'94  And they started, shocked!  Shock, horror!  I said, \'93You\rquote re not an African at all.  You go to Africa now, and you\rquote ll find that you\rquote re not an African\'94.  And I pressed it further.  I said, \'93
Even if you go to the West Indies, where your parents are from, you\rquote ll find that you\rquote re not a West Indian either, they\rquote ll see you as something else, but certainly not a West Indian, a Jamaic
an or Barbadian.  So what are you?  Who are you?\'94 Of course, this is very painful in a way, because they\rquote ve always assumed that they\rquote re defined by \'93something out there\'94, and it\rquote 
s very painful when you observe this, when black Americans are in Africa, and they suddenly realise that, in fact, they\rquote re not Africans.  Or people from here, in the Caribbean, realise they\rquote 
re not Jamaican, etc..  And this is reality.  It doesn\rquote t mean that you lose all sense of empathy, all sense of your construction of self in relation to those places, you don\rquote 
t lose those, but you need to be realistic about that, and I think this is where, in terms of research in both spheres, has helped me profoundly.  I think I have been very fortunate to have had those experiences.  Without them,
 I think I would be still in my Black Power days of the seventies!  (LAUGHS)
