History there, and we collected quite a lot of oral history of people that settled in Coventry, which I\rquote ve never used.  I\rquote 
ve left a set with Warwick, and I have a set, and that went on for the better part of two years, and we have just never used them, and 
these are people that settled there.  So I continued that interest.  And then, of course, once I joined the Centre for Research in Ethnic Relations, they gave me freedom to make it wherever I wanted to be, to locate it in terms of my interest, but I thoug
ht, \'93Well, this is where I now live\'94, and to do some empirical work as well, \'93I want to look at what I see as post-Imperial Britain, and how ethnicity and nationalism relate to this making of this post-Imperial world\'94
.  Partly because, in the African Caribbean context, particularly in the African context, I was aware that one was living in a post-Colonial \endash  I\rquote m using \'93post-Colonial\'94
 now, in terms of politics, rather than in terms of what people in literature uses it, as post-Coloniality.  It\rquote s a world which has gone through Colonialism, and now it\rquote 
s reconstructing and rediscovering, and re-inventing itself in the social and political realms, and in so doing, a number of new questions come to the fore, including who they are, in terms of identity.  And I was a
rguing, in that piece of work, that Britain has not come to that yet.  Incidentally, I think it now is very much here, in terms of questioning, \'93What is Britain?\'94
  And if you look at the notion of empires, once an empire comes to an end, there is the thing of what happens to the empire itself?  Never mind the ex-Colonies.  And so the things that I deal with in that text is very much about those issues.  So, now, I
\rquote m very tempted to return to it because of the discussions going on, and the paper I mentioned to you, that the Heritage Lottery Fund people asked me to write for them recently, around which they had this National Conference in July.  I\rquote 
ve got a lot of data now, so I\rquote m tempted to do it, if one could only find the time.  But certainly, the interest in Britain continued, but I didn\rquote t want to come back and look at it purely in the context of what had been defined as a \'93
race relations field\'94, where you\rquote re looking at particular groups only, but looking at the society in a wider social sense, and to see ho
w the different groups relate.  So you find, although some of my stuff published since, concentrated/focused on Caribbean groups, but much of it is also about the different groups, including the autochtonous, the indigenous community itself.  I feel that 
probably springs from my training in political science, which was Comparative Politics, which is a sort of an Aristotlean view, isn\rquote 
t it, that the best way to understand any one Constitution is to compare it with another.  I think that that comparative dimension is something which is important for me.  So all the research projects I\rquote 
m currently involved with is lodged within a comparative framework with Britain as the hub, the Caribbean, South Asia, and there is one on Southern Europe, and all the researchers are working in those areas, and then what we\rquote 
re going to try to do is to pull those back together.  But the starting point is Britain.  And how it will work, I still don\rquote t know fully!  (LAUGHS)
