\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 Yeah, that\rquote s right.  It was a relativism that only Asians can write about Asians, in the way that some black Americans might say, \'93Only blacks can write about blacks\'94
, and taking that kind of perspective.  Which, in terms of the engagements that a number of us have had \endash  or I have had \endash  was an absurdity.  And I still think it\rquote s an absur
dity, that view. But in terms of methodology, you do hear this quite often, people saying that they have a particular advantage from being from the same group as they\rquote re looking at.  And I often say, \'93
Well, okay, you might have an advantage.  You also have a terrible disadvantage.  It cuts both ways.  Sometimes you have advantage in gaining access and openness, frankness, earnesty, precisely because you\rquote 
re from the outside.  Other times, it might be the opposite, but it goes both ways\'94.  And in terms of scholarship, we can\rquote 
t restrict it to the politics of empathy, to belongingness to the particular group, and that goes back to what I was saying about the comparative dimension, which does not allow for that.  And that meeting was interesting. I\rquote ve been in sim
ilar encounters, before and since.  I recall a very progressive Southern African liberator, liberation fighter in the ANC, asking me how can I want to write a book on African politics, when I\rquote 
m not an African?  He, himself, at the time, was just about to write a book on the Feminist Movement!  (LAUGHS)  And so quite often people may see the mole in the other\rquote s eye, but don\rquote t see the plank in their own! (LAUGHS)  But }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 Communities in Britain}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 , in terms of race relations in particular, became pretty fraught, on 
and off, from time to time, with the question of who should investigate particular communities.  And it can go in different directions from time to time.  I was once told \endash  I can\rquote t remember where, now \endash 
 but by a group of people of West Indian background, of Caribbean backgrounds, that since I\rquote m writing on Caribbean families, and obviously I\rquote m from a Caribbean family, isn\rquote t what I\rquote m writing, very biased?  (LAUGHS)  That
\rquote s right!  This was a group of Masters students.  Because they assumed that what I was writing is not a matter of investigation, it\rquote s a matter of, \'93Since you\rquote re a member of it, you just write what you want\'94
!  (LAUGHS)  But I think things have gone on since.  And it was a challenge and a frustration to try to understand where that cry is coming 
from, but British academic life, in these areas, as in other areas, used to be entirely dominated by white male academics, and a number of people felt that, \'93Why aren\rquote t the others there?\'94  Now, it\rquote 
s an important question, and there are a number of answers 
to that.  To a degree, that is changing, to some extent, but it is still common to go to meetings and you might just see one black academic or none, or one sole person.  Sometimes when you speak with them, they say they feel burdened because they carry th
eir burden that they\rquote re the only spokesperson in the context, and sometimes I have to reflect and think, \'93Yes, actually, I\rquote ve been in this so often that I\rquote ve stopped noticing that it is the case\'94
.  And that, I hope, hopefully will change as well.  I don\rquote t see much sign of it, but obviously we live in hope that that might come to, to an end.  It\rquote 
s partly the dearth of the amount of young people from, particularly from the Caribbean communities, who go into academic work, and also they\rquote re not always encouraged to do so.  And, after all, how do any of us \endash  I don\rquote t know \endash 
 get into, into an occupation?  It\rquote s surely the milieu in which you move, and also the accident of people taking an interest in you.  And that kind of nurturing, mentoring, is quite often not the
re. I think in terms of how we teach students nowadays, the idea of mentoring is more formalised, but its effectivity is totally absent.  It\rquote 
s very very difficult indeed. I owe, as I was saying much earlier on, such a lot to my teachers in the past, and one feels sometimes very disappointed that one\rquote 
s not been able to nurture a number of people in the same way, in terms of enabling them and helping them, if they wish to enter into academic work.  Although I have a lot of research students, most of them tend
 to be mature students, part-time students, they have an occupation elsewhere.  They\rquote re not doing it to enter academia so much, but for personal satisfaction.  So you don\rquote t get that really.
