\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 Well, for me, I\rquote 
d lived there, obviously, as a child, very much in the countryside, not knowing Jamaica at all really.  And then when I went to do research for four months, I got to know aspects of the place, in my own research fi
eld, but it was really going to work there that was important.  And they\rquote d offered me a job there much earlier on, whilst I was still doing my doctorate, but I was determined to finish, so I didn\rquote 
t take it up.  When the opportunity came for me to become the Dean of Social Sciences at Mona Campus, I grabbed it, because it struck me as one way, opportunistically, to get to know the region \endash  not just Jamaica, but the region \endash 
 because being a regional university, meetings are held across different countries, and I would use the opportunity to see more of those places.  Then, crucially it helped me, as I was saying also, earlier on, to sort out one\rquote 
s relationship with the country as such, and with the population, and with the culture, and realise that, in a sense, without any intention when I\rquote 
d moved away from that, that really, if I were Jamaican at all, it was only in terms of, well, the villages that you\rquote re from, not in terms of the broad spectrum of Jamaica. I used to describe it to Jamaican friends, because w
e have a lot of good friends there, that middle-class Jamaica is very much a prep school society.  It\rquote s who you went to school with (LAUGHS) that matters, and if you didn\rquote 
t go to school there, then you have missed out on a crucial part of the socialisation process, and it\rquote 
s very difficult to angle your way back.  I was quite successful in doing so because people are very receptive of me.  Indeed, the political party, the PNP \endash  the People\rquote s National Party \endash 
 I became very close to them.  They asked me to join, and I said I didn\rquote t particularly want to, but we agreed that, provided I never spoke in public for the other party \endash  the JLP \endash 
 that was fine. I served on a number of their - when they were in opposition in the early eighties, from \rquote 80-\rquote 84, when I was the
re, I served on two of their Commissions.  They had set up a number of Commissions to reform the Party, thresh out policies for when they came back into office.  I served on one on education, and also on the foreign policy one.  And of the group of us who
m they attracted from the University \endash  and in every generation they do this from Mona, a group of academics they attract into the political process, particularly the PNP \endash 
 one is now tipped to be leader, of the three of us.  We were three, seen as a triumvi
rate!  And the other was Ambassador, until recently, to Washington.  Because they then decided to join the Party fully, and have become fairly substantial figures.  But I said I was happy to serve behind the scenes, and so, for a number of years I did.  I
 
even participated, at one point, in the drafting of the equivalent of the response in Parliament to the Finance Minister.  They accepted me very much as part of the inner core of the Party, without being a Party member.  The present leadership I know quit
e well, because quite a number of them were also at Mona when I was there, and the Prime Minister, he came to Warwick a couple of times when they were still in opposition, whilst I was there, and I met him a number of times. 
