Canterbury Tales}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 , and I can\rquote t quote it now, in Chaucerian terms, but in paraphrase, that 
he always seemed more busy than he really was. I quoted that in my thesis!  I feel very bad about it now (LAUGHS) because when I got to understand Jamaica more, and what he was doing, I realised that he was a truly remarkable figure, and he really did wro
u
ght a revolution in Jamaica, which only outsiders have written on - some North American pieces, a couple of books by North Americans have really got to work on that very well.  The one in particular is Stephens, Stephens and Stephens, they were interested
 socialism within a democratic framework, so they\rquote ve written a book on Sweden, and then they came to Jamaica for a year, and they really did a fantastic piece of empirical work \endash  interviewing everyone, going through the records and so forth 
\endash  and it\rquote s an excellent piece of work.  That\rquote s very much from the broad political perspective. But from the social, broad social perspective, there is still a need to write a piece as to how Manley\rquote s Jamaica from \rquote 72 to 
\rquote 80, was a second phase of decolonisation, which really got to the sociological dimension, never mind the government.  Because I\rquote m told \endash  and when you live there, you realise it \endash 
 how black Jamaicans were not part of Jamaican society up to that period, and he\rquote s seen as a man who betrayed his class, because he\rquote 
s supposed to be part of that upper class.  But, in fact, his heart and his policies were very democratic and very much to open the society to all, and I think that\rquote s a remarkable achievement.  One of the great things about both Manleys \endash 
 father and junior \endash  his father, whom I am a great admirer of, Norman Manley made the point, when he retired from politics in \rquote 
69, that when he entered politics, he was a rich man, because he was a very successful barrister.  Now that he was retiring, he could pay his bi
lls, but he was a poor man.  Now, very few leaders in any part of the Third World could make a statement like that.  And I think his son, Michael Manley, was similar.  There is a disinterest in self-aggrandisement and enrichment.  They don\rquote 
t live in any gr
and way, which is something that I greatly admired in Julius Nyerere, who had a massive palace, but he simply used it administratively, and lived in a simple, simple petit-bourgeois house on the beach!  (LAUGHS)  There are certain values that they encompa
ss, and try to set a model for, for leadership, which I think is very Augustine indeed. Michael Manley, with time, I\rquote 
ve come to really appreciate profoundly, and much of what I said, summarised in that silly quotation, was quite uncalled for!  (LAUGHS)  But, no, I think Patterson is a great chap, and he\rquote 
s made history in being the longest ruling Jamaican Prime Minister, and won a number of elections.  But in retrospect, people look at Michael \endash  Manley the Younger, as I like to call him, from his daddy \endash  as b
eing the pivotal figure in so many, so many respects.  His social life was another thing, (LAUGHS) but he was a remarkable man.  And very shy.  One of the things I observed about him, if you were at a party with him, is that he\rquote 
s a very shy, was a very shy person.  You know, he would almost retreat away, and go and stand in a corner on his own, almost.  Once he\rquote s on a platform, he\rquote 
s an utterly transformed person.  The other person who I knew was like that was Walter Rodney.  If you are in a room with him, you would not know that this is the great Walter Rodney.  Very subdued, very quiet, but the moment he goes on to a platform, he
\rquote s one of the most brilliant speakers you can imagine, you know, he\rquote s unbelievable!
