Well, I used to, I found it traumatic in terms of the presumed racist perception of ordinary discourse and social behaviour.  I found it traumatic in terms of the violence. I think that I was explaining earlier, that if people are described in ra
cial terms, people are seen in colour terms, the value of the individual is closely akin to what colour they are.  So one\rquote s own social behaviour was seen, sometimes, as quite absurd.  I\rquote 
ll give you an example.  We were looking for a house, and this was bef
ore the car we were taking to the country had arrived.  Went to this estate agent, told him we were recommended, and the head of the firm put us on to one of his agents.  We walked in for an appointment, and this chap said to me, \'93
Dr. Goulbourne, you really want to buy a house?\'94  And I said, \'93Well, yes.  That\rquote s why I\rquote m here\'94.  It took me a little while to realise what was happening.  And he said, \'93And you don\rquote t have a car?\'94
  Because he had asked me, \'93Do you want to drive, or should I drive my car?\'94  And I said, \'93I don\rquote t have a car, we\rquote ll go in your car\'94
.  (LAUGHS)  And I had Hugh on my shoulder, and Selina was holding Neil, and then [he said] (LAUGHS) "Now, as a black man in Kingston, you shouldn\rquote t do that if you want people to respect you!  (LAUGHS)  You kn
ow, to want to buy a house, here you are without a car, and you\rquote re carrying your kids!"  (LAUGHS)  As an outsider, in a way, it takes time to realise what is happening.  But in general terms, that\rquote 
s an absurd example, perhaps, but in just general terms, I remember going to an office to insure that car, and the chap whom I was dealing with was what they call a \'93high brown man\'94
, who refused to deal with me.  It was soon after the elections of 1980, when the Labour Party had been returned, and people, some of these brown people were saying, \'93It\rquote s our time again\'94.  So it\rquote 
s not discussed very much in public, in the way that it is in this country, but it\rquote s very it\rquote s strong, and I used to discuss it quite a bit with people, and they would accept it, that it is, but it hadn\rquote 
t been fully tackled, and I suppose it still hasn\rquote t. So there was that aspect.  The second dimension was, of course, the question of violence, at that time, which always was on your nerves.  Because you never quite know when what would seem a perf
ectly rational situation could just break into irrationality.  You can be having a discussion with a person, and you say something which, it\rquote 
s nothing particularly offensive, but they take real offence at that.  I used to discover was a lot of schizophreni
c characteristics.  And, of course, the physical violence in terms of the guns that were available, the drugs, the sense of public disorder.  Perhaps I could live with it better now, but I felt, as a young father having young kids, I felt very vulnerable,
 
though at no point was any of this violence that close to oneself.  But, more profoundly, I used to feel that there was an absence in Third World countries, and Jamaica simply epitomised it more than most for me, at the time, a certain degree of cruelty, 
of uncaring, on the part of the well-to-do, of the rich, with regard to the not well-to-do, and that there was too much of a ostentatious display of wealth, and very little, comparatively, done to help.  There weren\rquote 
t enough charitable institutions.  And one of the things which I used to suggest \endash  and at the time it was absurd, but they have now done \endash 
 is that some of the big companies which deal in Jamaica, and big families who are very rich and have resources, why don\rquote t they give Lectureships and Professor
ships to the University?  But one of the previous Vice-Chancellors, Alasdair MacIntyre, he has really tapped into this, and I was quite impressed to see quite a number of the big families have actually responded well.  One of the things about Victorian/Ed
wardian England was a big real philanthropy, and what I\rquote 
m suggesting there is that there is a degree of absence of that.  We used to find that to be very annoying, where people are so ostentatious about their wealth.  If you travel around Kingston, or any p
art of Jamaica, but particularly the towns and Kingston, you see the sort of ostentatious living that some people display.  I think if I lived in that context and I was very poor, I would morally be justified in wanting to have some for myself!  (LAUGHS) 
I felt rather uneasy, and I didn\rquote t feel that it\rquote s a place that I would necessarily want to bring up my children fully, and yet it\rquote s a society in which I wouldn\rquote 
t want to be totally divorced from either.  And Selina, in particular, likes Jamaica more than any other country \endash  more than here, more than Kenya, more than Goa \endash  and would return there tomorrow if we were to say, \'93Let\rquote s go back
\'94.
