search on, was to look at new notions of nationalism, which was emerging in Britain.  And in that book, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 Ethnicity and Nationalism in post-Imperial Britain}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 , I sought to combine the experience of teaching politics and looking at political movements in Africa 
and the Caribbean, with looking at what was happening in a Britain which I described, then, as \'93post-Imperial\'94
.  I remember there was a book written by Alan Sked, who is one of the main voices in the UK Independence Party, and he opens his book by saying, \'93There\rquote 
s hardly enough to sustain a discussion about where Britain is going to in the post-Imperial age\'94 \endash  I\rquote m paraphrasing, but basically that was the statement.  So I thought, \'93Well, this is something worth investigating\'94
.  So my intention, then, was to 
look at what were the nationalist voices going on in Britain, beyond what Tom Nairn had written about the break-up of Britain.  But to look at that in terms of migration, in terms of the post-Imperial moment, and the idea that in the Imperial Age, there i
s a massive crisis, not only on the part of the post-Colonials.  In fact, for them, it\rquote s very optimistic, because it\rquote s a new life, it\rquote 
s regeneration, a period for creating new myths and so on.  But what happens, also, to the post-Imperial power?  And to see that this, in the case of Britain, coincided with significant migration from those post-Colonial societies, and to say, \'93
Well, how is this going to be constructed within Britain?\'94  And to demonstrate that empirically, to look at a number of communities, so to speak, and my interest, then, was to look at nationalist expressions within Britain \endash 
 the extreme Right.  But then there\rquote s quite a lot of work done on that, so I thought, \'93Well, there\rquote s not much to add to this\'94.
