\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 Yes.  Well, because you go with a body of knowledge already about what it is you want to talk about.  If you take, for example, the case of a gro
up of ethnic nationalists wanting to break up an established Union of India?  Well, I would have read, already, much of what they have published.  They would know that you have done that.  I would have had informal discussions with them.  I might even hav
e gone to some of the meetings - as I certainly have done \endash  some of their meetings beforehand, where they\rquote 
re talking to their supporters, etc., etc..  And then, settle down with one or two of them, or a group of them, to discuss the issues, and for them to explain themselves as much as possible \endash 
 and learning from that process quite considerably.  For example, one of the things I observed about ethnic nationalism, which was common both to the SNP and to the Kalistan Movement, was this.  I put the question to
 the then President of the Kalistan Council, who claimed that they were the government in exile, and his cabinet, I said, \'93Look, if you\rquote 
re saying that Sikhs in the Punjab should break away, and legitimately so, from the rest of the Indian Union, is it not logical that every other group in the country should be able to do the same?\'94  Similarly to the SNP leadership, I said, \'93
Well, wouldn\rquote t you agree, then, that in Britain, if you want to break away, if Scotland can break away, shouldn\rquote t Cornwall, the Isle of Dogs, and Wales?\'94
  In both contexts, totally separate, and seemingly very different contexts, they both agree that, \'93Yes\'94.  And in the case of India, the chaps they agree that, \'93Look, if the Indian Union\'94, which, in strict constitutional terms is a Union,
 though it\rquote s become less of a federal, in practice, system, and more of a unified one, they agreed that it would be a good thing for the Indian subcontinent to be broken up into its tiny parts.  So I said, \'93How small?\'94  And they said, \'93
Even if each village was to become its own sovereign entity, that would be fine\'94, because I then said, \'93Well, where would that lead to?\'94
