\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 And in the literature, one of the interesting things in the 19}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\super\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 th}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796  century, Lord Acton, in his famous essay on nationality, arguing against the philosophy of nationalism, argued that particularly with regard to the French Revolution, \'93
Look, given the commune system in France, if each commune was to follow the logic of the nationalist ethos and ideology, each commune would become a separate entity, and that is the illogical end game of nationalism\'94
.  But these chaps had also accepted that, in a way, without having known anything about Acton.  So in terms of the literature, in a way, there is, ther
e is a view of the illogicality, if you like, of the ideology of nationalism.  But they were converting this to saying, \'93Well, let\rquote s go there, to that logical absurd end of the road, and then something else will happen\'94
.  To an extent I think, when you loo
k at some nationalist movements today, of large entities breaking up, I think it is that same fundamental principle that is being played with.  So, so the interview is, then, as we can see, somewhat different from when you\rquote 
re interviewing, say, a family, and looking at the family history.  There\rquote s an intellectual and practical political debate which is involved.
