\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri113\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin113\lin1871\itap0\pararsid16140354 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid6571465\charrsid6571465 Harry:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 I push, but well, I never had that experience so much.  With some of the Sikhs, a couple of them \endash  not the leadership \endash 
 but I remember interviewing one Sikh person who says, within that context, that he had come from East Africa, and he said, \'93Our experience, as Asians in East Africa, is that we had nothing to learn from Africans.  They\rquote 
re so backward, etc., etc., etc.,\'94 and he went on in that way.  As an interviewer, all I could do is simply grunt and say, \'93Yes\'94.  Now, one has to make sure, of course, that one\rquote s grunting and \'93Yes\'94 is limited to saying, \'93
I can hear what you\rquote re saying.  It does not mean that I agree with you\'94
.  On the other hand, I was also interviewing a Guyanese person of African background, and he assumed, again, that because he and I are both blacks, that I would agree with his racist statements about Asians.  I simply grunted and said \'93Mmm\'94
.  And then when the interview finished, I said to him, \'93
Actually, let me go back on one of the points you raised.  This is not being recorded in any way.  But my wife is Asian, a number of my family members are from Asian backgrounds, and whites, and I don\rquote t take a rac
ist position about anybody.  I see people as individuals\'94.  And he was absolutely shocked!  (LAUGHS) But when I thought of interviewing Enoch Powell, I thought, \'93Well, one must go to that, and must do it professionally\'94
.  Set aside, so to speak, what he might say about blackness, etc., or Asians.  And one of the things about Enoch Powell, because I\rquote 
ve looked at his writings and his speeches very closely, one of the interesting things about Enoch Powell was that he made a distinction, which a lot of scholars about race and ethnicity, themselves, don\rquote t quite understand.  He made \endash 
 and I think he was right \endash  he made a distinction between race and ethnicity in conceptual and practical terms.  And whilst in his famous \rquote 68 \'93Rivers of Blood\'94 speech, he\rquote s there, lashing out against blacks and so forth \endash 
 and for him, \'93blacks\'94 mean anybody who\rquote s not white \endash  but as he went on into the seventies, particularly over the Ugandan, the Amin Crisis, with the expulsion of Asians from there to Britain, he came out with the view that it\rquote 
s not so much a matter of numbers mattered, but a question of culture.  And he, at one point, around about the same time, made a distinction between the West Indians, whom, he said, \'93didn\rquote t pose a cultural problem\'94, so they\rquote 
re not as dangerous as the Asians who were culturally different.  In his head, you can see this play between the two, and the difference, because, in a sense, it\rquote 
s almost that he can see that blacks from the Caribbean are not really a problem by the seventies.  What is really the
 problem is the Asian, for him, because they come with a different cultural baggage, which will change England.  I think he was a very thoughtful person, in a many respects.  In one of his last interviews, he made the point \endash 
 and I almost broke down to the point of tears \endash 
 saying he wished he had died as a soldier in the last War, because he would not have lived to see [what was] to become, of the United Kingdom.  Because his own practical political experience was expressed in practice, when he moved from W
olverhampton to Northern Ireland, where Britishness was very strong.  Rather like what we were saying about Gibraltar, basically!  (LAUGHS)  Whereas in Wolverhampton, it was going to the dogs!  (LAUGHS) So I feel, in social science research, sometimes you
 have to grit your teeth and absent your personality, your own inner views, your own values, somewhat aside, and listen, because you\rquote re not there to engage in exchange for understanding, necessarily, with the person you\rquote 
re interviewing.  There is that, but really you want to get as close as possible to what the person thinks, feels \endash  what they want to say.  And that does mean that you\rquote 
re engaging in a different way from when you want to impress on that person your own views.  You\rquote re there as a listener.  And
 I think, as a listener, you have to almost negate a degree of yourself as a person, as an individual, as a human being almost, so to speak, and just listen carefully.  Anything which will interrupt in that process, try and push aside.  At the end of it y
ou may feel frustrated, angry, etc., but I think it\rquote s part of that exercise.  I think Weber expresses, for me, the point very well, in terms of what he talks about are \'93demonic positions\'94
 - in other words, our own personal subjective views.  Just set those aside, and try to see the bigger picture, the other story, as clearly as you can, and to relate that and try to understand it as closely as you can in that way.  And it\rquote 
s something, not just in social sciences, but in humanities/social sciences as a whole, dealing with people, with societies, and with individuals, we have to try to do.
