\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri113\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin113\lin1871\itap0\pararsid16140354 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid6571465\charrsid6571465 Harry:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 Well, for example, with the Sikhs, I attended a number of their Gudwalahs.  I would not dress entirely appropriately, but it was required that you wear a sort of a scarlet headgear, which they\rquote 
ll give you, a kind of a scarf which you would put on the head.  You would sit in the same way, you\rquote d eat 
what they offer, etc., and just be around.  So sometimes I would sit around all day, not necessarily talking to anyone other than informally.  And what, what would I get from that?  I would get a sense of exposure to what people felt was important to them
selves.  I\rquote d get a sense of the cultural mores.  For example, the Sikhs, more than other South Asians perhaps, feel that they [believe in a] very the strong sense of equality between the sexes.  But when you\rquote 
re amongst them in the Gudwalahs and so on, you realise that they\rquote re just like others, (LAUGHS) they\rquote re not that equal!  It\rquote s, it\rquote s dominated by men.  It\rquote s dominated by men and elders, and women are around, but they
\rquote re there as helpers \endash  not that different from when you go to some Caribbean church social
 situations, where again, the men occupy the positions of control and of power, though again, there is a philosophy of total equality. Sometimes, of course, that can change.  In one of those chapters in the book, [on ???] you\rquote 
ll find that I describe how, f
rom the seventies to the eighties, how women had, indeed, come to take on leadership positions, and if anything, it was the men who were running around preparing the lunches and the teas and so on.  That sort of thing, you can\rquote 
t get that from reading scripts, you can\rquote t get that from talking to people, because what they\rquote 
re doing is expressing a view which may be very different from the practice. So I usually find it important, like in anthropology, to just sit around, and to just listen.  And sometimes, in terms of the Gudwalahs, I wouldn\rquote 
t understand the language, but, of course, you get a sense of it.  At the time when I was doing this work, I was at a conference, for example, in Chicago, which I go to from time to time, a group they call \'93Third World Conference Foundation\'94
, and on one of those occasions, I was taken to a Gudwalah in Chicago, where they\rquote re reading from the Gurigransaib, their main text, where they just read for days, one reader after another, and there\rquote s no break.  I didn\rquote 
t understand it, because I don\rquote t speak Punjabi at all, I didn\rquote 
t feel I was going to be committed to the area long enough to try to learn the language, but it was something to simply sit there and to see the process as to what is gone through.  Those are the sort of things th
at I think you get, what I got, from going to the site, from going there.  And that was similar with, with going to Caribbean Pentecostal churches.  Again, those materials I\rquote ve not really used very significantly.  I\rquote 
ve used that largely in terms of a couple of think pieces, and in terms of an application, which was unsuccessful, to Leverhulme, to look at the black-led Churches in Britain, and I\rquote ve not really gone back to that at all.  It\rquote 
s something which someone should do, and perhaps one day I might, I don\rquote t know, go back to it.  But my feeling, at the moment, is that I need time to write, rather than do any more empirical work.
