\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 Yes.  Now, the interesting thing there was long long before what we call \'93focus group discussions\'94
 these days, which with New Labour has become in academia as well, one of the main methodological techniques being used.  I came across this where I would have an appointment to speak with an individual Sikh leader, say in Derby, or in Leicester, or Birmi
ngham, and I would arrive, and find that, in fact, he was there, yes, but so was a dozen others!  (LAUGHS)  And they all wanted to talk!  And since I wasn\rquote t recording them, it was very difficult, because I\rquote 
d have to keep those points and try to remember them.  So, in a sense, one acted as a kind of Chairman, and then took some notes, and on leaving, elaborated on the notes.  So, so it\rquote s in that sense that they were there.  It wasn\rquote 
t of my choice to have the groups, it was that it was imposed.  Of course, as a researcher, you don\rquote t turn up somewhere where people are giving up their time, and if it was half a dozen of them, or a dozen of them, simply say \'93The rest should go
\'94, you take what is given!  And at that time, I found it very puzzling as to how to treat that, because you can\rquote t relate statements to individuals then, and so it\rquote 
s very difficult.  You just have to take it as a wrap-around to what was in the news this morning, about education \endash  a wrap-around statement!  But it does help you to understand thi
ngs better.  What that did, I found to be useful also, was that it brought up some contradictions, some different views about common issues amongst themselves, because they wouldn\rquote 
t all express - once they relaxed and start to talk, then you realise that it\rquote s not quite as unified, sometimes, as when you\rquote 
re speaking to one person would be.  And again, the gender thing, the sex role differentiation came through very strongly there, of the men speaking, women being kept out of the discussions.  (LAUGHS)  But a
mongst the Sikhs there is this fundamental principle of [hospitality], which is a kitchen: that any member of their own faith, or other faiths, visiting any of their communities, there\rquote s always a kitchen open, where there\rquote 
s always a meal, and you can alway
s go in, anyone.  So when I turned up at some of these places, they were very impressed that here was a black person, who is coming into their [home].  In principle, as part of their religion, it is, it is open to anyone to come.  But given the ethnicisat
i
on of British society, perhaps less so now, but in the seventies and in the eighties, and into the nineties, you would never see people who are non-Sikhs going into those.  It would be interesting to see, now, whether that principle is an open one, is one
 that\rquote s being acted on by people from other communities, in terms of entry.  After all this, speaking to some Church of England vicars, they will say how Sikhs and Muslims come to them and say, you know, \'93
The Church of England is also their place\'94, because it\rquote s seen as part of the public sphere, you know.  (LAUGHS)  So they have moved into that space, and there\rquote s no reason why it can\rquote 
t go the other way as well.  And in a multi-cultural diverse world, such as is being constructed in Britain, it would be nice to see that, wouldn\rquote t it!  (LAUGHS)
