\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 Yes.  Well, as I said earlier, I did that, but I didn\rquote 
t draw upon it.  What I wanted to capture was common responses from the different groups, and I constructed a questionnaire, I asked questions about ethnicity, about not race, because it was really ethn
icity though people, of course, can choose the two, or bring them together in terms of expressions, but it was really about ethnicity and about how they saw themselves in terms of Britain, as well as how they saw the issues to which they were relating bac
k in the Punjab or in the Caribbean.  Partly because of the pressure to produce that book quickly, and so that I would register myself on the Richter scale of production, I just didn\rquote 
t bother to analyse those, and depended on the qualitative material.  But it was a set of questions which, of course, in constructing those sorts, you tend to make them simple, tend to make them not too long, because people don\rquote 
t have time to sit down for long periods of time and do these.  I realise, also, that when you\rquote re dealing with political leaders, if you\rquote re doing political opinion, survey questionnaires are useful, and you\rquote 
re arresting a particular moment.  It doesn\rquote t mean that what the person says now is what they would have said yesterday, or what they\rquote ll say tomorrow.  So you\rquote 
re looking at a particular moment.  And since I was interested more in a longer term process, I felt the questions were useful in getting a kind of a flavour, but it didn\rquote t take me much further than that.  In terms of use of questionnaire, I
\rquote ll say that recently I did a piece of joint work on a school in Lambeth, and we used a questionnaire there, and even in using other skills in analysing the findings, we didn\rquote t find it particularly revealing, it didn\rquote 
t tell us much more than what we had gathered from the qualitative research.  It\rquote 
s this type of work which would determine which is the most appropriate methodology to use.  And certainly in terms of the questionnaire, in terms of a survey kind model, if I was doing a large-scale thing, where you\rquote re a
rresting a particular moment, it would be useful, but not when it\rquote s involving historical processes, and it involves people\rquote s deeper perceptions of things and so on.  So this is why it\rquote 
s absent from that.  I think if I was writing the book now, because meth
odology has become much more rigorous, I would want to put in appendix, and put my questionnaires to show what came from them, and I would have reflected more on it and said more about it than, than I did at the time.  I think that\rquote 
s part of the rigour of methodology which has become much stronger and much more reflexive, over the last 10, 15 years, than it was before then.
