\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 No.  No new fieldwork as such.  Both of those arose out of conferences.  The }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 Black Politics in Britain}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796  arose out of a one-day conference, one-day seminar, where, as you will
 recall, in the late eighties, it was just the beginning of the transformation of black politics, if you like, in Britain, away from protest to active participation within the mainstream of the political parties.  In \rquote 
87 was the first time, in the post-War years, that blacks and Asians are being elected to Parliament.  There were some Asians who had been elected up to the 1920s into Parliament, but there\rquote 
s this long gap, and some Caribbean folks that stood, particularly Pitt, for the Labour Party, in between that.  But before the sixties, seventies, and much of the eighties you might say, was characterised by protest, in terms of new minorities \endash 
 Asians and blacks.  But in \rquote 87 a number of candidates, there were some in the previous election as well, but \rquote 87,
 the black caucus in Labour was determined that there should be some candidate with a fair chance of winning, and of course, Boateng, Bernie Grant, Diane Abbott, were elected [in London], Keith Vaz from Leicester.  So it\rquote s change you\rquote 
re seeing.  Now, build
ing up to that, I was very aware as to some of these things going on, and so that one-day conference I organised with the idea of talking, bringing together all the [candidates], not only those in the Labour Party, but also from the Conservative Party.  A
nd so John Taylor, for example, from Solihull, at least three or four others who were from the Liberal Party, and from what later became the SDP, were invited.  As an academic, I felt, \'93Well, you should bring them all together,\'94
 but particularly the Labour Party folks didn\rquote t want this at all.  (LAUGHS)  And so a number of them didn\rquote 
t come.  But Bernie Grant, whom I have good relations with, came.  We had our quarrels and so on, but at the end of the quarrel, Bernie was a very open person.   And  some council
lors as well.  So it was very much around that, those issues, and there were some academics, to see what was happening. What I\rquote 
ve not written about was that following from that, I think in 1991, I organised two conferences, at Warwick, following from that,
 which was to mirror, somewhat, what was happening in the United States.  In Congress there is a black caucus, no?  And in Britain, up to the election of those MPs, there was what was called a \'93Parliamentary Black Caucus\'94
, which was an attempt, by members of the Lords and the Commons to come together, and to have a distinctive voice in Parliament and in the country \endash 
 similar to the Congressional black caucus in Washington.  At the time, the body who had financed my conference at Warwick, Cadburys, in Birmin
gham, they were very willing to finance more meetings, and they saw me as a sort of lynchpin to that, because they wanted an academic who could deal with politicians, deal with communities and so on.  And I was quite willing to do it.  But in those days, 
in British academia, that sort of work was secondary.  Nowadays, of course, it\rquote s central to what they want us to do!  But in those days, you didn\rquote 
t get much Brownie points for that!  But going back to my activist days, I felt that this was something which was worth doing, and a chap by the name of Joe Montgomery, he\rquote s of Caribbean background, he\rquote s now a fairly big figure, he\rquote 
s heading one of the national bodies dealing with one of the Blair Initiatives, he was one of the key figures in Birmingham, in the Cad
bury Trust, and they were willing to finance that.  At the same time, Bernie Grant and Lord Pitt and others in Parliament had approached Cadburys, or Cadbury had approached them, and they said if they wanted to develop something like the Congressional thi
n
g in Washington, they would finance it, but an academic would have to be involved.  So, all together, we converged on this, and we had a meeting at a weekend conference at Warwick, bringing together public figures from business, from NGOs, from academia, 
from politics.  But the thing with that sort of thing is that the politicians always want to lead it.  And Bernie Grant, in particular, wanted to lead this!  (LAUGHS)  And so after a while, I decided, \'93I\rquote ll just back away from it\'94
.  But it was so successful, that Conference, that one of the London councillors there, said, \'93Look, we must have a second meeting, and could you arrange it for us again, at Warwick?\'94
  So the one followed on to the other.  And from that, what was to have happened was a national body
, similar to the US body.  Indeed, Cadburys paid for the head of the US body to attend, and to be an advisor to the whole thing.  So it was quite a momentous thing, and very dramatic.  At that time, you could count, on one hand, the amount of black academ
ics there were in the universities, and they were all involved.  And until comparatively recently, they still came back to me and said, \'93Well, what happened to that initiative?  Why shouldn\rquote t we follow it through?\'94  And I said, \'93
Look, the amount of time and energy I invested in it, and at the end, given that the politicians wanted to control it entirely, and to think they could use us as academics simply as runarounds.\'94  And I thought, \'93No, we wouldn\rquote t do that\'94
.  So I moved away from that.  Now, none of that.
