\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 That\rquote s right.  I was well into it.  That came out of - when I came back here in \lquote 84/\rquote 85, I found that a lot of community bodies, perhaps because they\rquote 
d heard of me, or knew of some aspects of my interest and work, contacted me to give Public Lectures. I don\rquote t know if you know of the West Indian Standing Conference?  It is a body which emerged out of the \lquote 57/\rquote 
58 Notting Hill uprisings.  White racist attacks on Caribbean folks.  And WISC \endash  West Indian Standing Conference \endash  emerged out of that as a response by the 
liberal whites, Caribbean governments, blacks in the country generally, to have this standing body to protect, to promote blacks in Britain.  And it\rquote 
s still going.  And it was, it used to be a powerful body.  One of their main leaders is a chap called Clem
 Byfield, and he had died, and they wanted to honour him by having a series of annual public lectures, and they asked me to give the first one in Brixton, I think Brixton Town Hall, so I did.  And then Robin Cohen, was then the Director of the Centre, whe
n
 we were going through some of what we had done, and here I was, doing quite a lot of that sort of thing, dealing with communities, we came to the conclusion that since this was a properly prepared statement, that we should have it published.  So we did. 
 And that\rquote s what that is.  Soon after that, I was asked, in Birmingham, by another community group there, they\rquote 
d established an annual lecture in honour of Martin Luther King, on the anniversary of his assassination.  Again, that one I never did publish, but it was intended to.  I found that in the period up to two years ago, I think I\rquote 
ve now given about eight of such lectures, most of them have been published.  The last one I gave was not far from here, at Goldsmiths\rquote  College, the Phoenix Memorial Lecture. 
 Now, Marcia Phoenix was a daughter of Sybil Phoenix.  Sybil Phoenix is a very powerful figure in the Lewisham/South London community.  She\rquote s from Guyana, she\rquote s a social worker, but for the last 40 years, or part of that, she\rquote 
s a lay preacher in the Church of England, but she has also been a moving spirit in this part of the City, in terms of bringing young girls off the street \endash  blacks, but also whites, Asian, anybody \endash 
 and she runs a huge house, not far from me in Lewisham, where she provides an education for them, a home, have them trained and then go off into the wider world.  It\rquote s a fantastic service.  She\rquote 
s got either an OBE or an MBE for her work.  She\rquote s well recognised.  And her daughter died, accidentally, in the early seventies, and so she has esta
blished a Foundation, and her house, her Home for Girls, is named after her daughter.  And when I came to London, they wanted to establish a public lecture in her honour, and so they asked me to give the first one up at Goldsmiths\rquote 
.  The second one was giv
en recently by Trevor Philips.  It was then the Claudia Jones Memorial Lecture the year before, which was a way of honouring black journalists.  The NUJ and the black group within the NUJ, has established this annual lecture at the NUJ, in her honour, and
 again, they asked me to give the first one.  I think that was two years ago.  The second one was given, this year, by a black American radical [?? Name] who is a historian, a fairly prominent figure.  So in terms of community things, it\rquote 
s nice that they as
k me to do these.  I go back to what I was saying last time, the advice from one of my teachers from school, Fred Murphy, when I went to Lancaster as an undergraduate, and I started writing for student journals, and I remember, in a discussion with him, h
e said to me, \'93Look, whatever you write, do it to your best, so that in future, if you want to go back to them, you can always go back to them\'94.  And I found that with each of these lectures, when I\rquote 
ve been asked to give them, I treat them, I try to link it to something that I\rquote m intellectually and academically interested in, so that, if necessary, they\rquote re publishable pieces.  And that\rquote 
s one way I find, now, that the ESRC and academia say, \'93Look, how are you disseminating your research?\'94  I point to some of these and say, \'93Well, they\rquote re the same things as I do\'94.  And I don\rquote 
t know if that is simply opportunism, but I find it to be quite useful.  So I can have a dialogue and have a discussion with people.
