\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 Not, not now, not in those contexts I\rquote ve just described, because I\rquote m not doing it as a part of a work as such.  No, I don\rquote t.  That big conference with  Cadburys, with that, I
\rquote ve got all the files, I might have now destroyed them, but I usually keep all the documentation around these things, but I don\rquote t treat 
it like research as such.  Going with the NUJ and those people, and giving that talk, I just treat it as a one-off.  But, for example, what I would do is to pick up on an aspect, as I say, of my own work, and in the discussion with the people who invite m
e, I will then say, you know, \'93This is what I do.  How does it relate to what you want?\'94
  And we can pick up on a theme from that and deal with it in that way.  Like the Phoenix one, since they are dealing with girls who are being helped, I wanted to link i
t to the theme of families, so I was able to pull out a couple of things about what one does in that regard.  And so the theme of leadership, which is something which I was interested in, in terms of Caribbeans in this country, when I gave the Byfield lec
t
ure some years ago, the one in the photo there, was very much latched on to that theme.  Or at Warwick, when we established, at Warwick, a Walter Rodney Memorial Lecture, David Dabydeen and I established it, and it has gone on consistently since.  And at 
the time, I was interested in violence and the state of the Caribbean, and that\rquote 
s what that talk was about, and then we published it afterwards as that.  But I think that if one was writing an autobiography, or a memoir, would then reflect more on the sort of people you come across.
