\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 Yeah!  You\rquote ve mentioned Bernie Grant.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid11671488 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri113\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin113\lin1871\itap0\pararsid6571465 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid6571465\charrsid6571465 Harry:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 Oh yeah.  Well, Bernie and I, when we were putting together that thing - I first met Bernie soon after I returned here from the Caribbean, at a big conference in the la
st days of the GLC, before he was elected as Leader of Haringey Council.  He was a very approachable person, he\rquote s a very down-to-earth man, he\rquote 
s a very sincere, honest, earnest person, and on and off we came across each other.  And then, that Conference that I kept referring to at Warwick, he approached me first about it.  He said, \'93
Look, here is a Parliamentary caucus, we want an academic to help us with it.  You have been pointed out to us.\'94  You have to remember, in those days, I used to know all the bla
ck academics in the universities, because there were less than five of us, I think!  But now there must be a lot more.  But there were very few.  And so, he would come up to Warwick and we would talk things through, or I\rquote d come to London, we
\rquote d talk things 
through.  As a politician, obviously he has very strong views as to what should happen and what should not.  He had strong views as to who was supposed to lead the pack and who was not, and it was he was to lead the pack!  (LAUGHS) For example, Bernie wan
ted, people agreed with him more politicians should attend, but not others.  But I said, \'93Look, if there\rquote s black and Asian and minorities, surely you have to include everyone?\'94
  So with Keith Vaz, he was quite happy with that.  With Diane Abbott he was quite happy with that.  With Paul Boateng, no way!  (LAUGHS)  And I had to insist that, \'93Look here, Paul, as one of the pack \'85?\'94
  But in the process of that, the invitation - in terms of protocol, and you know how universities are, if you\rquote re inviting a public figure and Parliamentarians, it has to go through the Vice-Chancellor\rquote 
s Office - in the process of all that, obviously Paul must have known that this was happening, but his invitation went out late, because it took a bit of time to persuade Bernie that it should be done.  And I said, \'93
Look, he might come, or he might not come\'94.  It got to him, his invitation arrived, and I had a call from Paul, and he gave me such a bollocking!  Who did I think I was, sending him his invitation long after the others had rec
eived theirs?  But, because he was not to know that I had to fight to get him on the list anyway!  (LAUGHS)  But that\rquote s what it\rquote s like dealing with politicians!
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid11671488 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 
