\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 What\rquote s he like, though?
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid11671488 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri113\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin113\lin1871\itap0\pararsid16140354 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid6571465\charrsid6571465 Harry:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 I think Paul is, is quite approachable also, but again, they have a strong sense of their importance.  And what they don\rquote 
t realise is that academics also have a strong sense of their importance!  (LAUGHS)  As I tried to put Bernie on one occasion.  We were
 driving from Warwick University down to, to my home in Warwick Avenue in Coventry, we had finished our meeting, and Bernie was coming with me, and I was going to drop him off, but we were stopping at our house for a drink.  And Bernie started on me, who 
did I think I was, and so on?  So I said, \'93Look, you\rquote re a politician.  You\rquote re just a mere politician.  I\rquote m an academic, and as an academic, I\rquote m far superior to you!\'94  (LAUGHS)  So we had this big row!  (LAUGHS)  I said, 
\'93Look, I use my mind.  You use, just use your emotions\'94!  (LAUGHS)  At the end of that, there is no bitterness, he was that sort of person.  There\rquote s no bitterness, there\rquote 
s no grudge, no anything at all.  Then he and I were involved in a discussion - you know Warwick has a radio station, from 
which you can simply be interviewed there.  It was one of the first universities to do that.  And Bernie, or somebody, had made a speech about repatriation.  Bernie had come out and got questioned publicly, saying, \'93
Well, if people from the Caribbean wants to go back home, then the government should support them,\'94 in other words, a Powellite position.  \'93If people want to go home, give them the money, help them to go back\'94
.  And the BBC and the World Service had put together a programme to interview, by inte
rlinks, Bernie Grant, Keith Vaz, and myself, on the issue.  And I opposed that, firmly.  Keith opposed it.  Bernie supported it, because it was his view.  And so we had this [interview] not seeing each other.  I think Vaz was in his constituency, or somew
here in London, and Bernie was in London and I was at Warwick.  But we had this row and this argument.  But again, it\rquote s not something you\rquote 
d hold against him.  So I had a lot of time and a great deal of respect for, for, for Bernie.  At the same time, he\rquote s t
he one, I would say, who scuppered the initiative.  He started the initiative, in a way, and also destroyed it.  Keith Vaz was a person, he\rquote s a politician I had, again, a great deal of respect for.  Because if he can come to a meeting, he\rquote 
ll say \'93Yes\'94.  If he can\rquote t, he\rquote ll say \'93No\'94.  And he\rquote 
ll give full support, and so he was quite supportive and very helpful in that way. Diane Abbott, in that same invitation, her invitation turned up late, she, instead of ringing me, who was organising the thing, she rang the Vice-Chancellor\rquote 
s Office.  So I had this call from the Vice-Chancellor\rquote s Office, which hit the roof!  Because she claimed that the nitty-gritty things, like the date of things, and where, had not been sent to her.  So the Vice-Chancellor\rquote s Office rang m
e about this.  \'93What is this about?\'94  And so, to this day, she doesn\rquote t know the trouble she got me into!  (LAUGHS)  Because you don\rquote t do things that way!  Since then, nothing I\rquote m involved with, do I put her on my list!\'94
  (LAUGHS)  But there are little thin
gs like that.  This is the first generation of post-War, post-Imperial black politicians, they have a great deal of sense as to who and what they are.  And their achievement.  And in the black communities they are lionised and so forth, they\rquote 
re big public figures.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid11671488 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 
