\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 David Pitt, what about him?
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid11671488 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri113\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin113\lin1871\itap0\pararsid16140354 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid6571465\charrsid6571465 Harry:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 David was very different.  David Pitt was a great elderly statesman, so to speak.  I recall, when he stood in 1970 for Labour, in Clapham, I was one of those young hotheads who said, \'93
Who is this Uncle Tom wanting to stand for Labour?\'94
  (LAUGHS) And I remember someone pointing out to me that they went to Clapham Common to listen to one of his speeches, and to see this tall black man there, talking in support of Labour, when he should be talking about the r
evolution!  (LAUGHS)  And I agreed!  But years later, I was the Secretary for a group in Brixton, called the Jesher Francis Defence Committee, the case of a black man, in the late sixties/early seventies, when the police would attack young black youngster
s on the streets and so on, the beginning of that build-up to Brixton \rquote 81.  But then in \rquote 71, \rquote 72, this [case was about], as we saw him at the time, elderly black man \endash  he must have been in his early forties \endash 
 very much a church man, from work to home to chu
rch, that sort of figure.  It was very common in those days, the idea of going to a Social Club or to the pub, those things were not there.  [This older respectable black man], being on the street, was attacked by the police and blamed for robbing someone
.
  Now, this was a million miles from reality.  So we started this Defence Committee around him, and eventually it was successful and he came out of prison.  The doctor who had inspected him, was David, because he was a practising doctor, and one of the fe
w, if not }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\ul\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 the}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796  only black doctors around, and that\rquote 
s why this chap had gone there to him, as well.  David Pitt.  So he wrote a statement about that.  And it was then that I began to get closer, in a sense, though we had still not met him, but as Secretary I wrote to him and he responded and so on.  

