\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri113\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin113\lin1871\itap0\pararsid6571465 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid6571465\charrsid6571465 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 David Pitt.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid11671488 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri113\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin113\lin1871\itap0\pararsid16140354 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid6571465\charrsid6571465 Harry:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 Yes.  Well, as I said, he was a great fellow, and I learnt a lot, particularly doing that weekend of that Conference, from simply sitting there 
and talking with him, and he had, by then, obviously, become very much the elder statesman.  David Pitt came to Britain, I suppose in the early forties, and he must have been in his seventies when he died, so he would have been my parents\rquote 
 generation, so he was very much an older figure.  But he was very active, in CARD - Campaign Against Racial Discrimination - in the sixties.  He has been at the forefront of a lot of efforts.  He was at the forefront in the \endash 
 in terms of a black presence \endash  in the Labour P
arty, and basically the person who links, I suppose, early migration from the early forties into the eighties, with that second generation of of black and Asian politicians.  So he was a very respected figure in that regard. He became - I\rquote 
m thinking of, say, someone like Arthur Lewis?  I don\rquote t know if you\rquote re familiar with him?  Well, Arthur Lewis, he\rquote 
s the first Caribbean person to have won a Nobel Prize.  He won it for economics.  He got his knighthood for his contribution to economics, he won the Nobel Pr
ize, and he was a big, is a very big figure in Caribbean intellectual life.  [He studied] at London University, I think at the LSE, then he was Professor of Economics at Manchester, Jevons Professor, it was one of these prestigious Chairs of Economics at 
Manchester in the fifties.  He was very involved in a lot of Caribbean activities, on the active side, so to speak, and he wrote a paper called \'93Labour in the West Indies in 1938\'94, the great year of West Indian anti-Colonial uprisings, called \'93
Labour in the Caribbean\'94, which has been republished since, as a Fabian Tract, but it\rquote 
s a fat book.  He was that sort of figure who was, whilst he had this prominence in terms of international economics, one of the big figures around, but he was also closely linked int
o events in the Caribbean.  Later on he became Vice-Chancellor of the University of the West Indies, then he in the late eighties/early nineties, he was Professor of Economics at Princeton, so he spent his last years there.  A very distinguished figure in
 terms of history of economics.
