\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 Well, not as strange as it would have been for some people, in the sense that I\rquote ve always taken the view that anybody can study anybody, that racism in Britain, if it\rquote 
s cast in that way, is as much a problem to be tackled by white academics as black academics.  In a way, perhaps the burden is more for the white academic.  After all, (LAUGHS) if you want to be crude and say, \'93Well, you know, who\rquote 
s responsible for this up here?\'94  They are.  More so than blacks!  Because blacks are victims.  So I\rquote ve never, I looked at it in a broad intellectual way, the divide about black and white academics is something which I\rquote 
ve never had any patience with.  This young woman who\rquote s looking at the Black Power Movement, she\rquote 
s a white young woman.  I have no problem with that.  That will give her some strength, and it might give her some weaknesses.  In terms of the insider/outsider debate to communities, in terms of research, it cuts both ways, it\rquote 
s a two-edged sword.  When I was looking at the Sikhs, for example, the fact that I was an outsider gave me an edge with them, in the sense that I was powerless, whatever I did wasn\rquote t going to influence or affect them, whereas I can imagine t
hat a person coming from the Indian subcontinent, working amongst them, they would perhaps have closed the door, because that person, potentially, in terms of how they look at things, might have been able to influence them. So joining them as one of the f
i
rst black academics, in Britain, to have gone that way, I saw nothing contradictory or weakening, and indeed, in terms of my links with communities.  They saw it as a great strength, they saw it as a good thing that I was engaging in that way, and that I 
w
as a person, at Warwick, whom they could call upon, they could come and see, if they wished.  They drew on that.  I think it was out of that that I got those invitations to come and talk with them, and to give lectures.  The fact that, obviously, at a mor
e
 subjective personal level, it was painful, irksome, annoying, frustrating, to have some colleagues making statements where it was their prejudices which was speaking, even though they were defending these, or presenting these in terms of objective social
 science, which it wasn\rquote 
t.  A number of my colleagues, like John Rex, and some of the people who are persuaded by his type of approach to social science, was extremely annoying, and had lots of discussions with them, and sometimes just refused to have discu
ssions with them.  But at the same time, you see, as much as one had that with John, I learnt a lot from him, because, as an intellectual mind, he\rquote 
s got an incredible mind, in terms of complex ideas.  He can explain them very simply and very clearly, and some writers, whom I wasn\rquote t aware of before, in discussions with him, I\rquote 
ve gone on to follow up some of those.  I remember having a discussion with John, for example, about about culture, and how cultures change when they meet.  And he said, \'93Well, have you read Malinowsky\rquote s }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 Concept of Culture Contact and Culture Change}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 ?\'94  And I said, \'93No\'94.  So he said, \'93Well, here are some to go and read\'94
.  And I did.  And I benefited immensely from that, which I find to be much more enriching than discussions about hybridity, for example, in cultural studies.  People writing in that way haven\rquote 
t read some of the masters, I feel, in terms of culture and anthropology, which would do them a lot of good to read.  Or, thinking in terms of the position of value, what Myrdal calls \'93value\'94
, and, to an extent, Weber also, in social science, the relation between subjectivity and objectivity, and again discussing sort of an issue like that with John.  It was he who introduced me to an aspect of Weber and Myrdal, and I went back to look 
at those, and I valued those very much. But when it comes to talking about, for example, black or Asian communities in this country, he\rquote s up the wall!  (LAUGHS)  You know, he really is!  (LAUGHS)  And he\rquote s a figure who, of course, as I
\rquote ve always described him, he\rquote s an intellectual pugilist!  (LAUGHS)  We\rquote ve had relations where, um, he\rquote s more or less said to me, \'93Look, I\rquote m going to take you to court\'94.  And he ran me from his room, and said, \'93
Get out of here!\'94  And the following day when I saw him coming out of the car park, I ignored him, and that made him absolutely livid.  He said, \'93You\rquote re ill-mannered,\'94
 this and that, and he then went to see the Director of the Centre, to complain about me.  We\rquote ve had all that.  At the same time, I think we have a certain 
degree of respect for each other.  The other aspect about all this business, one of the things about race in Britain, that struck me soon after returning here, was that it wasn\rquote 
t the crudities of racism, such as discrimination in housing and employment, ed
ucation, etc., which was probably the most dangerous thing for black people in Britain.  Probably what it was, or what it still is to a degree, perhaps, is the internalisation of racism into their own lives.  I find it difficult to express this, but obvio
usly, Selina and I and others discuss this from time to time.  The racist practices of a lot of black people, they\rquote 
re unaware of it, perhaps as a result of experiencing racism in Britain.  Quite often, in their social practices, they become profoundly racist without really knowing it.  They come also to accept the racist prescription of themselves \endash 
 in terms of their abilities, in terms of their interests, in terms of who and what they are \endash  and in that internalisation is a profound dehumanising thing. I find that to be much more frightening than the discrimination, which I\rquote 
ve experienced, immensely, in terms of the employment market.  You know, if I were to tell my story in terms of how I feel I\rquote ve been discriminated against at Warwick, it would blow the min
d of a lot of people.  But that, you live with, and you can cope with.  But it\rquote 
s really the imprisonment of the person, of the mind, of the spirit, through racism.  I think the question you asked there is an aspect of that, namely, working with others, wor
king with, with Asians, working with other black Caribbean people, working with whites, in terms of this very sensitive field of intellectual endeavour.  And it\rquote s, it\rquote s there all the time, and it\rquote 
s very difficult to handle.  But the central part of that question, or part of that question as to working with whites, how does it seem?  Well, it\rquote s difficult, but it\rquote s equally difficult working in a number of other spheres.
