\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 You said John Rex was \'93up the wall\'94 about black and Asian communities?  What do you mean by that?
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid11671488 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri113\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin113\lin1871\itap0\pararsid16140354 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid6571465\charrsid6571465 Harry:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 (LAUGHS)  Oh well, I\rquote 
m exaggerating, of course!  But, okay, let me take one instance.  One of the areas of discussions we used to have was about a genre of literature that stresses that black people in Britain, Caribbean people in Br
itain, are hostile to British society.  Now, this is a central theme in one of John\rquote s books?  They\rquote 
re hostile, they wish to be distanced from.  Now, I take the opposite position.  Whereas Asians, he argue, are people who are accommodating and want to be part of the system, etc., etc..  I said, \'93Well\'94
 - and this was in the eighties, long before the Rushdie Affair, long before Al Queda and all these issues.  That was the position.  I said, \'93Look, John, if you understand Caribbean people, you will have realise
d that, fundamentally, they are, if anything, integrationists, wishing to engage and to belong.  That we pose no, no threat in terms of cultural dynamics.  Indeed, what we express in cultural terms is what becomes part of the norm.  It\rquote 
s not distanced from.  It may be it\rquote s adding to it, but it\rquote s not away from\'94.  We participate in sports, we participate in music and literature, in all those areas, and it\rquote 
s built on a foundation which is, to a large extent, largely European.  So in terms of the broad spectrum of cultural baggage that we have, is not that far removed.  I said, \'93Look, I don\rquote 
t want to make comments about Asian communities, apart from those whom I\rquote ve studied, I don\rquote t want to make a broad statement, but if you were to, you could find dimensions whe
re, in terms of the integrative process, it is not as proximate as in terms of Caribbeans\'94.  I said, \'93Well, look at marriage, at the family, you will find that whilst some Asians\'94 \endash  I\rquote m not saying this is true now, I\rquote 
m talking about then, in the eighties - whilst some Asians may be intermarried with the white majority community, it tends to be very much of the upper class, upper/middle class element, but we\rquote 
re talking now about the masses of people, at working-class, ordinary street, street level.  You don\rquote 
t find that.  What you find there with Caribbeans, they totally intermix at that level.  Of course, empirically, now you can show that to be the case.  So we had those kind of differences.  \tab As for this business of \'93withdrawal\'94, I said, \'93
Show me, where is this withdrawal?\'94  He talked about Rastafarians.  I said, \'93
Come on!  Rastafarians are not the dynamic process of the Caribbean community.  They might fascinate you and some people because of their seemingly novel expressions, but they\rquote re not }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\ul\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 the}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796  Caribbean community!\'94
  (LAUGHS)  So there were those kinds of issues, that we would get into.  I think what it really was is that, perhaps he felt that Caribbean people didn\rquote t quite appreciate, fully, that his heart, as a person, was with them.  Sometimes, of course
, John would make the point that he is black, or is partly black, because a great forbear of his was a black woman from Madagascar.  I don\rquote t know if you know the story of his family line?  So there were those sort of things.  But I think that he
\rquote s a very personalised person.  He will personalise things very much, and if you argue against an argument, you\rquote re not arguing just against an argument, you\rquote 
re arguing against a person, in his case.  So those things were, were very much so.  And I tried to show that, in terms of looking at that, that it\rquote 
s a bad thing, in an ethical way, moral way, to contrast different communities in a process of formation and try to bring out those kind of differences which are likely to highlight conflict, likely to suggest the kind
s of differences which will separate people, as opposed to those which will more unify people..
