\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 Yes, Michael Banton.  I met Michael Banton comparatively late really.  I met him, indeed, at a meeting with Bernie Grant.  Bernie came up for a morning meeting on a Saturday, I\rquote 
ve forgotten what the meeting was about now, actually.  It wasn\rquote t one about conferences, it was some years after that.  And James Jackson, he\rquote s Professor of Psychology at Ann Arbo -  I\rquote m told that Ann Arbor\rquote 
s Chair of Psychology is }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\ul\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 the}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796  premier Chair in the field in the States.  He\rquote 
s a very impressive black man who does work in Europe as well, a black American chap.  His wife is French, I think, and so he has strong links with France, and with Scandinavia and so on.  He\rquote 
s involved with the Euro Barometer work.  But Bernie came up with him, and at the meeting Michael Banton was also there.  So I was very pleased to meet him, and I introduced myself, and he said he\rquote s never heard of me.  And I said, \'93
Well, you wouldn\rquote t have done, I\rquote m comparatively new to the area\'94.  (LAUGHS)  So we laughed, and we established, in the process, a fairly good personal relationship.  And I don\rquote 
t know if you notice that, at your seminar, he gave me a collection of his papers.  I was wondering why he wanted, he had e-mailed me to say he was going to bring a collection of his papers, and then I remembered why, 
because I had a small grant with a young woman from, from the States, when I went to Cheltenham for a year, Vena Vasista (??).  Vena, when I was at Warwick, just knocked at my door one day, and she said she\rquote 
s finishing a Masters, upstairs, with David Dabydeen, and she wants to work with someone, so she can stay on in Britain for a bit longer.  But is there any work I needed doing?  You find Americans like that.  (LAUGHS)  So I said, \'93Well, not really,\'94
  but she persisted.  And she was one of these bright sparks, so I said, \'93Well, okay\'94.  Eventually, I got some money.  She went to one of these elite places, Vassar College in New York, and she\rquote 
s of Asian background, but she was born and brought up in Chicago.  And so I took her on board, and she got some money from her old College, Vassar College, and I got some from Cheltenham, to pay her way for a year.  So we said, \'93Well, what\rquote 
s the work?\'94  And at the time I was writing that book, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 Race Relations in Britain, from 1945}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 
.  I said, \'93Well, one of the things I want to look at for this is what has been the influence of research on policy, in the field?\'94
  And so we set up this little project for her to interview, I think something like 20, 25 researchers in race relations, going back in time and contemporaneously, and Banton was one of them.  So although we didn\rquote 
t meet on the thing, but we had set this up, and I had written to people, and Vena had gone and done the work, so he knows that I have that interest.  We didn\rquote t have enough money for Vena to follow things beyon
d that, and she got a good job in London and moved on.  So it\rquote 
s from that interest that I know Banton in that regard.  But he had come to that meeting at Warwick, and it was then he was telling me that he had done work in psychology, that his first Chair was in Politics at Harvard, so he\rquote 
s had a very broad background, which I had no idea about, until he was telling me.  I knew one of his students, Ken Price, who had done his doctorate with him at Bristol, Ken was a contemporary, if you like.  When I finishe
d my doctorate at Sussex, just around that time, Bob Benewick introduced me, or someone introduced me to Ken, who visited Sussex, and was giving a talk, and he said he had just submitted at Bristol, and that\rquote s what became }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 Endless Pressure}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796  the book later on
.  And Ken and I were fairly close, because he went back to the Caribbean to teach sociology at the University of the West Indies, in Trinidad, and he became Head of Department, and so when I was Dean of the Faculty at Mona, we would meet quite a lot, thr
ough that way.  But most of the people in Race Relations, I really did not know, because, as an undergraduate, as a graduate student, I didn\rquote t know them at all.  It was really coming back.  And I think a lot of people didn\rquote 
t know who I was, the people who knew me were the people in politics.  (LAUGHS)  So I then had to get to know people, and I spent a lot of energy and time going to meetings and so forth.  Nowadays, I\rquote m totally on to meetings more or less.  I don
\rquote t go to conferences.  Selina constantly attacks me for not being involved in the professional bodies.  I\rquote m not at all involved.  The BSA, I\rquote m a member of it.  The PSA I\rquote 
m a member.  I pay my fees.  I remember going to two meetings of the PSA when I came back.  I\rquote ve never been to a BSA meeting.  I\rquote ll go to the subject meetings and participate in those if they ask me to give a talk, but I don\rquote 
t particularly participate, contrary to my early years, when I was very active in, in associational grouping, meetings.  Partly I think it\rquote s [that] I have a great dissatisfaction with, as I was saying, cliquism, I find it very distasteful, so I
\rquote m not a member of any group of academic workers as such.  I relate to individual academics across a wide spectrum, and I go to one or two Caribbean Societies in this country
, for some years I went to theirs, and then once I noticed that there was a kind of a sectarianism, I just dropped out really.  I belong to a group in Chicago I\rquote ve been going to for almost 20 years, and it\rquote 
s a multi-disciplinary group.  If people ask me in
 France, here, and where have you, to participate in things, I go, but I tend not to be active in those kinds of ways.  So even today, with the Race Relations community in this country, I know quite a lot of individuals, but I don\rquote 
t relate to them as a discrete group as such at all.  Part of my failings, I\rquote m told!  (LAUGHS)
