\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 One of the central points I would hold to.  That\rquote s right
, yeah.  Very much so.  Yeah, yeah.  I think that when it came for them to consider me for a Chair at Warwick, the position was to stress what I had not done, and to ignore, entirely, what I had done, whereas there were people who had done far less.  At t
he time, the spirit was, if such a person, if anyone had had an interview elsewhere for a Chair, even though they didn\rquote 
t succeed, that was a good indication that you were worth considering.  I had had something like two or three interviews elsewhere, for a 
Chair.  And in both, in two of those situations, one was for the Chair of Politics at Bristol which I really was keen after, and my impression \endash  I might have been wrong \endash 
 but my impression was that, given my name, and people not physically knowing me, the 
moment I walked in, they shot off from the academic discussion and just looked dumbfounded.  I know that, quite often, when in the States and here, in the past, people didn\rquote t know me physically, given my name, they expected \endash 
 and people have said this to me \endash  they expect to see a Jewish person, by that they mean a white person.  And then you turn up, and you\rquote re not that, and it throws them, and I don\rquote t think they\rquote re aware of it.  They\rquote 
re expecting something else.  So much of the time is spent coping with that.  I\rquote m not saying that\rquote s so for everyone.  But that\rquote s one of the reasons, too, after a while, in the mid-nineties, I decided, \'93To hell with the Associations
\'94, I just wouldn\rquote t bother to go to, to some of these meetings.  If people invited me, quite often I would go. But for the longest while, for the better part of ten years, I don\rquote t think I\rquote ve seen a conference advertised, and I say, 
\'93Look, I have something I want to say, I\rquote ll go to it\'94.  I\rquote ve just not. It\rquote s partly that sense, I can spend my time doing so
mething else rather than go through that experience.  Certainly at Warwick, if you want me to elaborate on that, I was instrumental in helping getting two of the research programmes designed and funded, and okay, the first of those, when I competed, they 
gave the Directorship to someone who was - even if they hadn\rquote t given it to me, they ought not to have given to that person because they couldn\rquote 
t handle it at all.  And then it meant, myself as one of the two most senior persons below that person, had to run
 the show, and was never given anything for that.  I was promoted one scale up, but that was that.  But fundamentally, going back to the question of access to research communities, when I was doing work amongst the Sikhs, in particular, these were trouble
d
 times.  People were very suspicious of researchers, and one of the things I had to prove to them was that I was not working for the Home Office, and secondly that I was not coming to them from a university called Brunel, because at the time, Brunel had a
 
Police Studies Unit.  People involved in those sort of struggles and communities were very suspicious of researchers wanting to know more about them, because they assumed that whatever they tell you, or whatever you saw, would be fed back into the governm
e
ntal process.  Douglas Hurd had come out with a statement, as Home Secretary, saying that the various new religions to Britain could potentially be disruptive to British society, and, therefore, the Home Office, when he was at the Home Office, should prom
o
te research in this area.  Now, a statement like that went like a piece of wildfire in communities and potentially jeopardised the work that some researchers were doing amongst Muslims, Sikhs and so on.  Now, why am I telling this?  The Police Unit at Bru
n
el was closed, and the money that the Home Office was giving to that was then put up for tendering.  Warwick, in our Centre, we debated, for a long while, as to whether we should apply for that.  The pressure from the University was that we should.  The l
ess senior members and myself, in the Centre, decided that we would not.  Robin supported us largely on that, as Director.  But Malcolm Cross, who was then the Principal Research Fellow, the next to Robin, the most senior, decided that, \'93
No, we should go for it\'94, and the central administration, because, I think, at the time, if my memory serves me right, something like \'a33m. was involved.  Today it\rquote 
