\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 Robin and Malcolm Cross wanted me to be part of the team to go down to the Home Office for the final competition.  And it was clear as daylight to me why they wanted me to come \endash  it\rquote 
s a black face.  Years later I was relating this to some American friends and they said I\rquote d handled it badly, I should have pointed this out blatantly, and then negotiate for something!  (LAUGHS)  But I held out, and I said, \'93No, I\rquote 
m not going at all\'94.  And there was a lot of pressure.  Now, the interview for the Directorship of
 the Centre was a week after that event, and I understand that, in the discussion that ensued, the then Registrar was a very powerful figure in British higher education, Shattock, pointed out that \endash  I don\rquote t know if it\rquote 
s true, but I understand \endash  it was pointed out that I would never bring any money to the Institution.  And the people didn\rquote 
t know what he was referring to.  But I suspect, you see, in a context like that, you say that there is one black candidate, he will never bring any money, it has an immedi
ate ring, because blacks are inefficient anyway!  (LAUGHS)  A number of people on that panel, over the years, have come to me and talk and so on, but with that, I put that aside, and say, \'93Well, is one post.  Not everyone can win it\'94
.  There were some other candidates of whom, I think, like Robert Miles, he competed, I think, given his position in the field at the time, he was, perhaps, the strongest.  Malcolm Cross was another figure, he was fairly strong.  So I\rquote 
m not saying that it should have come to me,
 but there was that kind of play.  But four years down the road later on, three years down the road, when it came to getting a Chair, that was definitely something which I could have taken them to court on, not to court to fine formally, but I could have 
embarrassed the University about it.  But that is something else. What I would say, in terms of one\rquote 
s career in that regard, I found that, as a student, there was never any obstacles whatsoever, and as I mentioned earlier, and I think there was every assist
ance and help.  I think that is true, in a general sense, for most academics that I know, who have come into this way of life.  And as for black academics, I think most of those whom I have spoken with, or those whom I\rquote 
ve heard of, or read their biographies, or know something of their biographies, have been helped immensely in that way.  I mentioned earlier on perhaps the most well known Caribbean economist, Arthur Lewis.  Well, I\rquote 
m told that he went to read commerce at London University, and it was his tutors who spotted that this man, he\rquote s not for commerce, he\rquote 
s got a brilliant mind!  (LAUGHS)  And helped him.  So that with him, in no time at all, he had this incredible position.  One of his seminal essays is on, \'93Economic Development with an Unlimited Supply of Labour\'94
, which is just an essay, but is one of those classic pieces of beautiful writing.  Then there was a Jamaican chap who was Professor of Economics at Birkbeck.  I don\rquote t know if you ever came across him in the sixties and seventies?  He was an 
ordinary worker, I think the Trades Unions sent him to do a degree at the LSE, and again, his tutors there spotted him as a brilliant chap, and within a matter of years he was a full professor, and this was in the bad old days of the sixties!  He later we
n
t on to a Chair at [UWI] and an advisor to the Manley government in Jamaica, and then he returned here.  I came across a chap, recently, who is a Professor of Brewing, at Strathclyde at the moment, but he was at Aston before, and he was telling me a story
 that he came here as a boy, from Jamaica, brought up by his mother on her own.  At school he was neither here nor there, and it\rquote 
s when he left school and he had a job as a laboratory assistant, that the chap who was employing him there, sent him to university, and he end up as, now, one of the leading figures dealing with the brewery industry \endash 
 as an academic.  He was telling me, personally, that he travels all over the place - India, Germany, in this regard.  There was a big piece, a big spread on him, in the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 THES
}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 , a couple of months back.  But what I\rquote m saying is again, it\rquote s people who help in that regard.  I found that in terms of employment, it cuts both ways.  I\rquote 
ve had a lot of great opportunities, and I\rquote ve had occasions - and I suppose one of the places where I\rquote ve had occasion where I think my career was frustrated, was at Warwick.  (LAUGHS)
