\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 Well, Alastair, I suppose most people would describe him as a difficult figure, a figure difficult to fathom, to understand.  He\rquote s an old Etonian.  I think he\rquote 
s a contemporary of Douglas Hurd, one of those pupils at Eton, and he\rquote s very much from the upper sort of background, in terms of person to person, he\rquote s very much an old Etonian!  (LAUGHS)  Some of his ways a
re a bit awkward and difficult to, to fathom, he has an irksome kind of a way.  He is a broad man, a broad intellectual perspective.  His work had been on Brazil.  And it was only when I went to Warwick that I realised that, going through some of my under
graduate notes, when I did a course on Latin American History, that I\rquote d read one of his pieces on Brazil, on Brazilian history, so it was a great sweep.  He\rquote 
s of a refreshing mind, a person who is not buried into one period of history, or issue, he can look overall.  But in terms of getting your feet on the ground with him, and to see what he\rquote s on about, is often difficult to grasp, because he\rquote 
s always moving on and coming back.  I think, speaking to other colleagues like Gad Heuman, one of his colleagues, t
hey find it difficult to work with.  So the spirit of working in a collegial kind of way today, in social science, rather like the science model, is something which I suspect Alastair could never ever do, he\rquote 
s just such a strong individual, individually motivated, individually organised person, so that even when you discuss things with him and you think, \'93The next step is that\'94, when you get there, you realise that it isn\rquote t.  I\rquote 
ve never been able to \'85 to agree with him as to what it is we\rquote re going to do.  So you\rquote 
d go to meetings of the Caribbean Studies Centre, there was a year, for example, when he was away, and he asked me to act as Director for the Centre.  But he wasn\rquote 
t away.  He was always there.  (LAUGHS)  And he was always intervening in things!  And 
we would discuss things that I would go away and do, only to find that he had already done them!  (LAUGHS)  Talking with others, it has always been thus with Alastair.  The other strange social thing about him was that, being a university in the middle of
 nowhere, there\rquote s lots of dinners and parties at people\rquote 
s places and so forth, and I invited Alastair, twice, for a meal, and he always found a way out of that, and in discussing this with other colleagues in History, it has always been thus with Alastair.  They\rquote 
ve never been able to invite him to anything and, vice-versa, he\rquote s never invited them to anything.  He\rquote s always in the public sphere.  So it\rquote 
s difficult to get very close, very close to him.  his wife was a charming woman.  I understand that she\rquote s a daughter of D.H. Lawrence.  Yeah, but something very charming about her.  She\rquote 
s always very nice and polite, and very nicely spoken.  But you don\rquote t get too close to them, in terms of their lives.  You only ever see them at receptions or in a meeting Alastair, as I say, he\rquote 
s just very difficult to ground things.  He did a two-volume edited work, edited, on intellectuals in the Caribbean, in which, since I was new to the place, I helped with the organisation of a conference, brought in people, helped with the
 papers.  It didn\rquote t occur to me to insist, as I ought to have done, that it should have been jointly edited.  But after the book came out, he, himself, came to me and he said, \'93Actually, both our names should have been on it\'94
.  But I never hold it against him in any way.  I mean, there have been times where, particularly when you\rquote re leading researchers, where they can do the research or they can\rquote t write, where you had to take things and write it for them, and I
\rquote ve never claimed anything on that, because taking the team as a whole, the thing has to be done!  (LAUGHS)  I\rquote m sure you must have experienced that all the time!
