\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 That\rquote s right.  I spent a lot of time constructing a questionnaire, um, copying yours and modifying it appropriately for that, and that\rquote 
s what we used for those interviews.  Then Alastair also got, for two years running, I think it was, or perhaps might have been 
just one year, a Visiting Fellowship for a schoolteacher to come to Warwick, and what we did was to use that person to help also with that.  So there\rquote s quite a number of tapes which I think I\rquote ve left, I\rquote 
ve lodged a copy of these, with the Centre there.  They\rquote ve never been used.  And I\rquote ve kept a set.  I\rquote ll never use them.  But they\rquote 
re there.  And if anyone were to want to do a history in Coventry, or in the Midlands, I think it would prove quite worthwhile.  Of course, a number of these people have now died,
 and have gone on.  So he wanted me very much to do that, and that was very useful, indeed, to do.  Had I stayed on in the Centre for Caribbean Studies, I might have gone on and done more with that.  \tab 
But the following year, as I was saying, I moved downst
airs to the Centre for Research in Ethnic Relations, and that meant, of course, that I had different work, though I still continued to give a part-time attention to overseeing the interviews, making links with people and so forth, to enable that.  That he
l
ped, that paid off dividends later on in another way, because there was a competition to conduct a piece of policy research for Coventry City Council, and when I applied for it, I got, I won, because I knew the community fairly well!  (LAUGHS)  And then a
gain, in terms of access to the leadership in Coventry, I got that very well.  It was just six months, it lasted seven or eight months and it was \'a330,000 worth of research, which formed the basis, for some years, of the Council\rquote 
s policy towards minorities in the City.
