\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 No. No, it was for the whole Faculty.  It was for the Social Sciences and Arts.  But why they wanted someone like myself there, it was two things.  The RAE \endash 
 the Research Assessment Exercises - they wanted someone with a research background.  Se
condly, they wanted their status from a College of Higher Education to be changed to full University status, because although they did everything as a university did, they were validated \endash  for their higher degrees \endash 
 by Bristol.  And if you remember that soon after \rquote 
92, when the former polytechnics became universities, by the mid-nineties there was quite a bit of dissatisfaction with a number of them which ought not have been given the change of status.  So the HEFCE had put down a very strong line, namely t
hat any other institution which should become a university, must demonstrate, before they become one, that they have the capacity, and principally in the area of research.  So when someone like myself from Warwick applied there, they were very impressed a
nd I got this position.  But then I said, in the negotiation certain conditions, one of which was that I\rquote d get the title, a Chair, and they said, \'93Yeah, just describe what you want!\'94
  (LAUGHS)  So I was very pleased!  The Principal was very kind, and the De
an was very kind, and it was a nice place altogether.  So I went there.  And whilst being there, one of the initiatives I took was to round up a number of people in the Faculty who had an interest around policy and health, and to start a Research Centre l
ike that, with them.  And they put some money into it, and we did a number of publications.  It was a way of helping the research process along.  So after I\rquote d left, and it got its title \endash 
 because one of the conditions was that you must have at least 80 students in the research profile, you must have had something like 30 or 40 who have successfully completed and had their doctorates \endash 
 and these, I felt, were conditions that had not been set down with the former polytechnics, and therefore, after a while, Che
ltenham, even before it became a university, had a stronger research - taking research altogether, in terms of research students, research projects and so on, a stronger profile than quite a number of the former polytechnics.  But it was a deliberate thin
g
. And my time there was a very interesting and important one, important in that just before going there, you remember you introduced, re-introduced Mary [Chamberlain] and myself, and we got this project together.  I learnt, much later on, that Mary was in
terested not so much in me, but in terms of Warwick, because, because of Warwick\rquote s name, that her project should be there.  So when I announced to her that I was actually leaving, she was keen to take it to Oxford Brookes, but, of course, I said, 
\'93No, we\rquote ll just keep it as it is\'94
.  So I went to Cheltenham with that, by which time Warwick was very keen for me to stay!  (LAUGHS)  It coincided with also winning that other project that I mentioned, the one for Coventry City Council.  So I went there with these t
wo projects together, and a number of my research students from Warwick.  I said to them, \'93You can stay, or you can come.  I can understand whichever position you took\'94
.  Two of them came with me to Cheltenham.  They felt, as I would have felt, when I was 
a research student, the people are more important than the institution.  I went with a baggage, so to speak. So they were quite pleased and happy with me.  I had a wonderful time, a very good time in Cheltenham. It coincided with my kids being in the sixt
h form and leaving and so on, which I found, particularly when my first son went off to university, to my utter surprise, I found it quite traumatic.  Very traumatic.  Because I recall, we\rquote d gone to Kenya on holiday in \rquote 
95, summer, he came back for his results, and in the meantime, he had gone to Selina\rquote s family then, her brother\rquote 
s family, who have three children, one of whom was at Woburn Abbey in High Wycombe, boarding school there.  She had come home with a friend of hers from there, and that friend and H
ugh, our older son, became an item in the process.  So he had come home, waiting for his results, and they all three waiting for their results that summer, as to where they would go off to.  They all did well and so on, and then this girl, she\rquote 
s from a very very very wealthy family, she\rquote s one of these - what do they call them?  People who inherit a lot of wealth, \'93trustafarians\'94, you know?  A couple of years ago there was this talk of \'93trustafarians\'94
, kids who inherit, through a Trust, a lot of money.  She\rquote 
d gone off to Florence, to improve on her Italian, because she was going to do linguistics at Cambridge.  So she went across, which was good for [Hugh], because it struck him that although he\rquote 
d done French and he was going off to Bristol to do Classics, that he really must improve on his Modern Languages, because he met young people from all over the Continent, he said, \'93who could just switch from one language to the next\'94
, and he realised he has the capacity to.  So that was quite good for him.  But the point about that was, he came back home after that break, and I drove him, and Neil accompanied us \endash  Neil, our younger son \endash 
 and we drove him to Bristol, and on the way back, I became so depressed.  And then for about a month, I\rquote d go for extremely long walks with the dog, and I was completely broken apart.  I think I wasn\rquote 
t prepared for it at all.  So it was a good thing that I was at Cheltenham, and he was just down at Bristol, because it\rquote s no distance at all, so I could go down from time to time and see him.  (LAUGHS)  But it was, it was pretty traumatic for me.

