\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 Well, that project, as I said, we had put together whilst in my last couple of months at Warwick, with Mary.  We both \endash 
 Mary Chamberlain - we both worked quite hard at it, in terms of structuring it and so on.  I think my experience of applying for funds, particularly at CRER, was obviously much more than Mary\rquote 
s, and I knew the ESRC scene.  Her interest was largely Barbados, but I stressed, \'93Well, if you want to get money, you have to look at Britain\'94, because at that time, the ESRC was not as open as it is
 now, of looking at the wider world.  Very focused on Britain.  Indeed, in a couple of discussions with Howard Newby, who was then Director of the ESRC, because Warwick was part of his empire, Warwick had, I think, something like three of the five ESRC Ce
ntres in the country, so whenever he came to Warwick, people would say, \'93He\rquote s coming to see his empire\'94
.  So we were fortunate to have a number of meetings with him, and he was determined to change the ESRC, so I had a good sense as to what they wanted, wha
t they were looking for.  One of the points we raised with him was that the ESRC ought to be looking more outwardly, and not just exclusively Britain.  But at the same time, I realised that if you are to be successful, given the refereeing process etc., y
o
u should start with Britain and then look outwards.  So we developed this project of looking Caribbean families in Britain.  We developed the idea before.  Then towards the finalising of the thing, we learnt that the ESRC was about to put together a large
-scale research project around families in Britain.  It was entitled, \'93Household and Population Change\'94
.  But reading the description of that, realised we could put it on to that, so we did, and we were very fortunate, it was a very tightly contested thing 
