\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 I\rquote m trying to remember now.  I think the family dimension came into it partly because of what was in the media at the time, I think.  Put it this way, I\rquote 
d long been conscious of the importance of family from a number of areas.  One had been the small bit of work I\rquote d done with you, way before, as we have described, and I realised how important that was then.  But secondly, 
was that much of the literature at the time, or much of the discussion about Caribbean groups in Britain, the family was central to that, in terms of the assumption of the disfunctionality of Caribbean families therefore leads to the under-performance of 
kids at schools, housing conditions, unemployment, etc., though I\rquote d not focused on it in that way.  But then, in \rquote 93/\rquote 
94, a number of pieces appeared in the national press, really piling at the door of the Caribbean family, all the social ills of Britain, s
o to speak, and I just felt it was important to combat that.  And I felt that, in this country, since there was no-one, or well, hardly anyone at all, who knew anything about the Caribbean.  There were people talking about the Caribbean.  I\rquote 
m going back to my tirade about cultural theorists, this is one of the points about them, that they talk about those things, but actually }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\ul\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 knowing}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 , empirically, it wasn\rquote t there, and the work wasn\rquote t being done either.  And it struck me that this is an area where, if anybod
y in the country could make a contribution, I should be able to.  Then, because the other area I was interested in, a bit earlier than this, were the churches, again, from that perspective, it seemed to me that the family was not that far away.  So when w
e thought of a way of angling into that, the family seemed important.  And Mary\rquote s work, in terms of what she had done, I was particularly taken with her book on Lambeth \endash  this was one of the things which I thought was important \endash 
 where she was interviewing women.   And I said, \'93Look, if you are interested in working with me, let\rquote s do \'85\'94  - something I\rquote 
d learnt from Preston King, whom I mentioned earlier.  Preston and I, at one time, thought of doing a big project together.  I\rquote ve forgotten now what it was!  (LAUGHS)  And Preston said to me, \'93
Look, here is a set of my books.  Give me a set of what you\rquote ve written, because if we\rquote re going to work together, we should know how we have worked, and what we have done\'94.  So I did that with Mary.  I said, \'93Look, here is 
