\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 Yes.  But in terms of the fieldwork, it was divided principally between Mary and a Research Fellow \endash  Dwayne Plaza.  We had advert
ised, and there was competition, and he came on board.  He was just finishing his doctorate at Toronto, and he\rquote 
s of Trinidadian background, but brought up in Canada from very very early, but he was very keenly interested in the Caribbean.  His doctorate was on \'93Caribbean Men in Higher Education in Canada\'94
, and we thought he performed very well at the interview, so we brought him on board.  He was a very enthusiastic young man.  I\rquote m pleased, in parentheses, to say that he\rquote s gone on and is developing a rich a
cademic career for himself in North America.  So they were to do most of the interviews.  My task, principally, apart from having overall overseership, managing the budget, negotiating, gaining access, and setting up the thing in a general way, and report
ing back to the ESRC and so on, also setting the research questions, so all of those one did.  One of the things that I [did], it was quite useful in that project to have had the oral history questions that I developed from your questionnaire, and which I
\rquote d used in Coventry.  I had assumed, at the time, that Mary, having done that sort of work in oral history, that she had a similar questionnaire.  But it transpired, when I asked her, I said, \'93Look, here is mine.  Where is yours?  Let\rquote 
s meet, bring them together and sort out something new\'94.  And she said, \'93Well, actually\'85  " she doesn\rquote 
t have one, she usually start off and it develops with the individual.  And, of course, we have a Research Fellow, at the moment, from anthropology, and that\rquote s how she has worked as well, and we have had to re-train her a bit to say, \'93
No, in sociology, we want it to be a little firmer than that, and to have a questionnaire which we can look back to.\'94  Anyhow, I asked Mary, then, if she could go through mine \endash  and bearing in mind 
the sort of questions she has asked, from her work \endash  to modify it.  So we then modified it in that way, the questionnaire, but it\rquote s still the central one that I\rquote 
d used in Coventry.  And we owe you a great debt.  Particularly in terms of the categories, I\rquote d introduced new ones, because the subjects are different.  The questions, themselves, were important.  That, I\rquote 
ve always found to have been a very worthwhile exercise, because I remember, I spent a good three months working on it when I went to Warwick, ge
tting up early in the morning and really working on it.  These were the days before computers, so it was all done by hand, you know!  (LAUGHS)  I\rquote 
ve still kept it, so we have that set.  So that was worked out.  Then, in terms of getting access, I had to arrange a whole series of meetings on the sites that we wanted \endash  principally parts of London, parts of Coventry \endash 
 and since we were looking at three Caribbean groups, people of Barbadian, Jamaican, Trinidadian backgrounds, we had to look at where they were distributed.  So part of the team was also to have \endash  as I always like to have \endash 
 a statistician, a social statistician, demographer, on board.  Some people insulting say, \'93the number cruncher\'94!  (LAUGHS)  But to have a person who is familiar with the demographic profile of the communities you\rquote 
re looking at, and David Owen who had worked with us on the Coventry project, I brought him on board as well, and so he was part of that.  And he\rquote s produced a number of papers on the demography in this country, but also 
drawing on some Census data from the Caribbean, which were collected there when Mary and Dwayne were working out there, for him to look at here.  So it was really overseeing all that, coming into London, in particular, having meetings with groups of peopl
