Well, I think that she is much more - this is rather difficult, but I think that - I like to see, have a sense of a balance.  For example, when were drafting our report, I drafted the first Report for the ESRC, in a way I t
ook my statement in almost bullet point format for them, and I made the point that Caribbean families, in terms of the relationships between men and women, mothers and fathers, that a number of men are running the risk of being lost because they\rquote 
re distancing themselves from families.  Secondly, throwing too much responsibilities to women.  Now, Mary would take issue with that.  Because she would say, \'93Look, you can show that men do participate, and women are able to cope \endash  single women
\'94.  I\rquote m saying, \'93Yes, they can, but taking society as a whole, you\rquote re not looking for an ideal situation, but it is far from being ideal.  One is not saying that single mothers, lone parents, can\rquote t cope.  One\rquote 
s not saying that all men are distanced.  But it is a demographic fact that that is so, and as analysts you have to take that on board.  You can\rquote t just not take notice of it\'94.  Now, that\rquote s illustrative as, as I\rquote 
m saying, a sense of what I would see as balance, as opposed to emphasising the margin and ignoring the big main part of the page.  I\rquote m more interested in that big part of the page.  I\rquote m not saying that that margin isn\rquote 
t there, but I don\rquote t think that that is the determinant factor.  In other words, I suspect that probably I\rquote m more in control, and I might be wrong, of what Weber calls our \'93demonic positions\'94 or \'93preferred positions\'94
, than probably she might be.  That\rquote s one thing.  I think there are other factors, like style of writing, etc., and what have you.  I feel it\rquote s vitally important to pay respect to anyone who\rquote 
s made a contribution in a particular area.  I don\rquote t believe in in emphasising people you agree with, and those you don\rquote t agree with you sort of ignore.  I\rquote m not saying she does that, but I\rquote 
