\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 I\rquote m not against that, and I\rquote m not \'85 I usually feel, I\rquote ve had a discussion with Mary, where she says that her, she called them \'93informants\'94, and I call them \'93respondents
\'94.  And I think there is a difference in that.  I\rquote ve not discussed that point with her, I\rquote ve discussed 
it with a student of mine, whom I asked Mary to be the second supervisor for, because when I was at Cheltenham, you have to have a second supervisor, and I\rquote 
d asked Mary to be the second supervisor.  I had a discussion with the student, not so much with Mary, because I noticed she used the term \'93informant\'94, and I think it has a definite meaning for her in that sense.  I don\rquote t know if she\rquote 
s consciously aware of it, and it comes out of another discussion with her, where she wished to describe that the people she was interviewing, she\rquote s recording their narrative, their history, and she\rquote 
s simply the medium for it to go out, mm?  I discussed it with her, and said, \'93I don\rquote t think that that is intellectually fully honest, because that only looks at the total situation, I don\rquote t think that\rquote s what\rquote s happening\'94
.  I might be wrong, but my argument is that I prefer to call them \'93respondents\'94, because you\rquote re posing a question, and they\rquote re responding to it.  How they respond now is not how they would necessarily respond tomo
rrow, or to another person, even, because they might have reflected on it, or not, as the case may be.  So we shouldn\rquote 
t take it that what they say is simply information being transmitted, being passed on, because information, for me, indicates something like when you\rquote 
re a tourist, and you go down to the Information place, and they give you information about a, b, c, and d.  It\rquote s not contested, there\rquote s nothing argumentative about it.  It doesn\rquote t involve \endash I might even be wrong on that 
\endash  but doesn\rquote t involve in
terpretation.  Whereas when you interview a person, interpretation is involved, and that interpretation is both on the part of the respondent.  But even what they have said, in terms of transmitting to you, data, what they say, you make that into a data. 
 It\rquote s not a data before that.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\ul\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 You}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 
 make it that.  So you occupy a crucial position, you interpret that as well.  And as much as you might narrate it, as much as you might think you\rquote re narrating it, you\rquote re not.  The fundamental role of the historian, or the 
analyst, is still there \endash  of selection, exclusion, of posing of the question, of interpretation.  Those factors mean that, as much as you might want to pull ourselves \endash 
 and I think your work, for example, in terms of oral history, and bringing that as an additional methodology into the field, has strengthened the the position of making the subjects speak for themselves \endash 
 it has strengthened that, particularly for people from non-elite positions, who don\rquote t write, don\rquote t record, etc., and you\rquote re bringing them into the picture more.  But there is no way that we can say, \'93
Unless you record everything verbatim, and publish it verbatim \'85\'94  We can\rquote t do that!  So that, obviously, when you have the recording like this, and you put it somewhere, you\rquote re making sure that
, for future historians, future commentators, they can hear a fuller voice.  But once you come to write about it, you\rquote re making selection.  No?  You\rquote 
re interpreting, and, therefore, intellectually, you have to be honest with yourself and say, \'93Well, you have that responsibility\'94.  And having that responsibility means that the notion of narrative - well, I\rquote 
m a little uneasy with, in the sense that I don\rquote t think it\rquote s fully so.  But if you\rquote re using it figuratively, I can go along with it!  (LAUGHS)
