\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 Precisely.  You have to select.  And in that, there may be \endash  going back to an earlier point \endash 
 class bias, regional bias, gender bias, all kinds of biases, and those biases, you have to be up front if you are to go the full Weberian way, and say, \'93Yes, these are mine.  I have done this\'94.  Or, as Myrdal would say, \'93
Before, you should make clear to your reader, what is your own position.\'94  Which we never, we very rarely do.  So I read your narrative of the narratives, and that\rquote 
s one.  But I could look at the same data and give another narrative, and equally valid.  Or, depending on our ability as
 historians, or as analysts.  So I think there are those fundamental differences which would be difficult.  So, it could be done, we could write something together, but it would be very painful.  If you notice the book we edited, the families thing, what 
we decided to do was to write two introductory chapters, which are quite different, and we had a division of labour there.  And then something which I think we call an introduction, but it\rquote 
s really a preface in a way.  That is purely schematic, if you like.  It\rquote s not touching on any arguments.  I wrote the piece, but it\rquote s something we [can] both agree with, because we\rquote re not touching on those factors.  And then I said, 
\'93Look, you go and write another chapter, and I\rquote ll write another one.\'94  We just have a division in that way.  So I think there are those differences.  But a curious point I would say here, in terms of doing collaborative work, and Mary\rquote 
s an instance of that, is that we come from different, I think, intellectual trainings.  And the paradox with M
ary is this, that I was trained as a historian, and I still like to think of myself as that.  She was trained as an anthropologist, as her undergraduate work, and because those are our formative years, they still have an abiding impact, whether we\rquote 
ve moved sideways or whatever directions.  And although she\rquote s a Professor of History, and I\rquote m of Sociology, I\rquote m much more of a historian in methodology than she is!  (LAUGHS) \'85 
