\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 Well, it\rquote s related to the family [research project] in the sense that the chapter, for example, on \'93Transnational Characteristics of Families\'94
 is reproduced slightly differently there.  I did some work, I wanted, at one time, to write a book on the black presence in Britain in the post-War years.  That\rquote 
s why I was very pleased to see that student who came to see me a couple of days ago from Sheffield, because what she\rquote s doing, I was saying, I have a lot of material I could let her have, because I don\rquote t think I\rquote 
m ever going to do it.  But in the meantime, what I\rquote ve done is this, touching on aspects, most of which should have been a separate book at one time.  For example, I wanted to write, to do some research on the black-led Churches.  There isn\rquote 
t anything here particularly on that.  I wanted to do something on black publishing, and there is a chapter on that, though it doesn\rquote t explore the full field.  There is an interesting chapter [on how] common popula
r notions which are shared between African Americans and blacks in Britain, as a way of showing how the construction of blackness in Britain is very much part of something imported from North America, rather than the Caribbean.  That came out of a piece o
f work which I was asked [to do on] these two boxers - I don\rquote t know if I\rquote ve told you this story?  Have I told you?  Frank Bruno and Lennox Lewis.  Well, in the nineties, one had called the other an \'93Uncle Tom.\'94  \'85
 I think it was Lewis who called Bruno an \'93Uncle Tom\'94
, because in one of their bouts, Bruno had gone into the ring, covered over with the Union Jack, and Lewis had gone in singing Bob Marley, so as to contrast them in terms of their different perspectives on post-Imperial or contemporary Britain, an
d how they fit, as black folks, into this situation.  Anyhow, Lewis had called Bruno an \'93Uncle Tom\'94.  I think it was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 The Guardian}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796  and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 The Observer}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796  had published this \endash 
 as news \endash  and Bruno, of course, was very upset, naturally, and took them to court.  So when I was at Cheltenham, I had this call from London, from a firm of solicitors, whether I could write a piece explaining the term \'93Uncle Tom\'94
.  So I said, \'93Well, yes, I suppose I could.\'94  So I did, and that young woman was working with me at the time, I mentioned, Vena Versista, she had gone home to Chicago to visit her family, so I rung Vena, who\rquote 
s a brilliant researcher, and said, \'93Look, dig me up everything you can about Uncle Tom\'94, and she came back with piles of stuff!  So between ourselves, well, I d
id the reading, she just guided me through it, and I wrote a long piece.  The agreement was - when they said how much would I charge, I said, \'93Well, now that I\rquote 
m a big man and a professor, I should charge you what a QC should charge you.  How much is that?\'94  So we agreed at \'a3100, I think, per day, which wasn\rquote t much, but said, \'93Okay\'94.  Anyhow, I got into the piece much more than perhaps they
\rquote d intended, and I\rquote d intended, and it ended up with me charging them something like \'a314,000!  But they said they\rquote d use the piece, and it helped to settle the case out of court, but they said they really hadn\rquote 
t thought it would be so much!  (LAUGHS)  So we, we arrived at a compromise, and I said, \'93Okay, take half of that\'94, and I\rquote d have the right, the copyright, I\rquote d have the
 right to publish, to republish it.  So it was just lying there, and it was a long piece, a long piece of work, something like 15 or 20,000 words.  And so when I was doing this, I thought, \'93
Well, this is an important part of the whole thing, of that picture of the construction of black Britain and America, that I\rquote d used part of this, part of the vocabulary.  So that chapter\rquote s quite a different piece.  So that\rquote 
s how that came about.  (LAUGHS)  It\rquote s one of those pieces of academic work where you get paid for doing it!  (LAUGHS) Then there\rquote 
s a piece on the Black Unity and Freedom Party, and Black Activism in Britain, which, again, I had collected enough material in interviews of some leaders, and publications and so on, to write a whole book on, and, um, I\rquote ve n
ot had the time to get around to it, but I was able to dig enough from that for a chapter.  So most of those chapters, each of them, came out of a situation, were different from the idea of sitting down and planning a book as such.  So when I had discussi
ons with Pluto, for years they\rquote ve been saying, \'93When are you going to publish something with us?\'94  I know the publishers well from Africa days, and I took this to them and said, \'93Well, would you be interested in this?\'94
- I think, at the time, I said, \'93as a collection of essays\'94 - and in the discussion as we came along, this is their title.  I don\rquote t think any of my books are in my own title.  I don\rquote 
t know about yours?  But somehow, in the discussion with publishers, they arrive at something, and that\rquote s how it emerged.
