Yes.  Because what happened with that Chair, it was interesting, I applied for it, and I think they short-listed four people, and then they had an afternoon meeting beforehand, and only two of us turned up \endash  John 
Solomos (??), who was a colleague from Warwick days, who had moved to Birkbeck and to Southampton, he had a Chair in Social Policy in Southampton at the time, and the other two didn\rquote t turn up.  And when we asked Jeffrey Weeks, the Dean, why 
\endash  he said, \'93Well, they were given - where they were coming from didn\rquote t want them to leave, so they were given Chairs where they were, so they stayed.\'94 They, themselves, obviously didn\rquote 
t want to leave.  So it was just the two of us, and I thought, \'93Well, we\rquote re here, might as well play at the game\'94
.  My interview was first, John was second, the following day.  I went back home and when I got there, there was a phone call.  Apparently the Vice-Chancellor was trying to get through to me, because he was going on holiday the following day, to say, he
\rquote s offering the post, and I have five minutes to say yes or no.  (LAUGHS)  And I said, \'93Yes, of course!\'94 at once!  But he said, \'93It\rquote s good news, nonetheless.  You\rquote ll be pleased to hear that John is also here.\'94
  Because what they did, although it was one Chair going, there was a vacant Chair in Education, and they decided to appoint both of us.  So when we got there, one of the things I\rquote 
d said in my interview was that, given our location in London, and given, if there\rquote s enough interest
 with the other people working in that field, it would be good to start a cluster of research around those issues.  And John must have said much the same.  But John, and Heidi Mirza who was there, the three of us had lunch one day, and we said, \'93
Look, we should start something like this\'94.  So we sat there and drew it up over lunch.  Then I said, \'93Well, who should lead this?\'94  They said, \'93Well, since you have more experience, you lead it\'94.  I said, \'93Okay, I\rquote 
ll take it on for two years, and then one of you take it on later on, let it be rotational.  Maximum of three years.  I\rquote ll set it up and then, you know, we move it around\'94
.  Within the year, Heidi left and got a Chair at Middlesex, and then the following year John left, to City University.  So I was left with the baby!  (LAUGHS)  So that\rquote s how that came about.  \tab 
But what it did mean is that at that time, we had sufficient, we had enough people working in that area, but as people came and left, we\rquote ve had fewer and fewer people working in that field.  And wha
t we have done now, with the Families and Social Capital Group, we have three, four Research Fellows working in those areas, as one of the three strands within that Group.  But we felt, under the last RAE, they said that our subject area was strong in eth
nicity, families, and I think something else - what is it?  So in building for the next, we thought, \'93Well, the thing to do is to bring everything together under the families strand\'94, so that\rquote s what we\rquote 
ve been doing.  So it has ethnicity and education intermeshing strands.  So it\rquote s very much under that.  Formally, we haven\rquote t disbanded the Group, and a number of people feel we shouldn\rquote 
t.  But the activities we used to do there, like seminars and so forth, we\rquote ve been able to do under the families.  It\rquote s still 
a discussion as to whether - what that did help to do is to bring in people from the communities more, whereas under the family, it\rquote 
s much more academics, and so there is that of tension.  And unless we were to get some more folks who are involved, not sim
ply as researchers, but on the teaching side, with an academic interest in that area, then we might just, for the next RAE, just let it slide away, no?
