 as well as the returnees paper, those two papers, the germination of the ideas for that strand come from those two papers.  When we were thinking, six of us, as professors at South Bank, to bring together an initiative, to bring a big research project to
 our Faculty, and the ESRC had put out tender, we thought, \'93Well, this is something which would link a number of interests\'94 \endash 
 John and myself in terms of ethnicity, families also in terms of myself.  Jeffrey Weeks in terms of intimacy and families.  Ros Edw
ards and Janet Holland in terms of young people, and Claire Callendar in terms of education and the labour market on.  So we knocked heads together, and we said, \'93Okay, we\rquote 
ll have a Research Group, three strands.  Two professors to each.  And then we will want three Research Fellows for each.  So go away and plan it out\'94.  So I planned out, and I thought, \'93
Well, I would like to see something done on provision and care, in terms of Britain, but outwards to the Caribbean, to Southern India and Southern Europe\'94
.  So I constructed one of the Research Fellowships, for three years, around that problematic.  In my paper on Caribbean returnees, that\rquote 
s a very big theme about care and provision.  So secondly, youth identities, that it would be important to have someth
ing as to how youth, in minority communities in Britain, how do they see the places from which their parents are from?  What are the links that are still there?  Again, that springs from part of that paper.  So I constructed another one on that.  And a th
ird one was, I\rquote d been to a seminar, I\rquote 
d been invited as a result of those two papers, to a seminar at Sussex, by some anthropologists - about a year before our application - which focused largely around rituals and ceremonies in communities, and I found it very enriching, and so I thought, 
\'93Well, it would be good to see to what extent do we have the continuities of rituals, and how are they changing?  And such social practices\'94.  And so I constructed a third one around that.  But in each project, those quest
ions will be taken across empirically, then, starting in Britain to the Caribbean, to the Indian subcontinent, and to Southern Europe.  And so we advertised these. The first one\rquote 
s the Caribbean.  I had a Research Fellow at South Bank already, and she was written into that.  Tracey Reynolds.  So she was written into that, yeah?  Because I\rquote 
d made an application to the ESRC, that initiative they have for post-doctoral Fellows, and so I changed it around and wrote her in, so we didn\rquote t have to advertise for her.
  But for the other two, we advertised it nationally.  Of course, nowadays, national means international \endash  people apply from everywhere \endash  it\rquote 
s a very strong field.  For the subcontinent, obviously India is somewhere I know, I thought [the research] might b
e there, but it was open to anywhere in Bangladesh, Pakistan, India, Sri Lanka.  And the competition from there, for that post, was fairly strong.  A couple of Germans and Continentals who have done work on parts of that were in contention.  Eventually we
 appointed someone for that, and she\rquote s just about, now, to go off for a second visit to India, and she\rquote 
s done quite a bit of work here.  And I wanted the person appointed, to focus on two subcontinental communities.  She decided to focus on the Punjabis, be
cause she did her doctorate on Punjabis, and so she can build from that.  The second group we thought that she might look at, and she was interested in, were the Gujuratis.  But both communities in this country, quite a lot of work are done on them anyway
.  But when she was going to India for an orientation visit, I said, \'93Well, if you want to go to Goa\'94 - it\rquote s somewhere she\rquote s never been, and she fell in love with the place, so she now wants to make it that, and there\rquote 
s nothing written on Goans at all.  And since I know something about the place, I can assist better.  So that\rquote 
s one.  For Southern Europe, I had, in mind, when I was constructing this, very much someone like from Turkey, or preferably Cyprus, because I have an interest in Cypriots in this country \endash  a minor sort of interest \endash 
 but the field is extremely powerful.  We offered the post to a Turkish scholar, a woman in this country, who works on Turkey and she is from Turkey.  But she turned us down.  So because the field was so strong, we had listed
 1, 2, 3 sort of thing.  So we then offered it to Rona, who is Italian, she\rquote s just finished her doctorate at Sussex, and was working in Barcelona on a project there.  And so she\rquote 
s picked it up.  And her interest is very much Italy, so we have chosen three sites in Italy \endash  one where she\rquote s from, the Northern part, and Rome and Sicily \endash  and she\rquote s the one who\rquote 
s gone off and has her first baby!  But in fact, today, tomorrow, they\rquote re off to Vienna to the International Conference of Anthropologists, to lead the pa
nel, and to present a paper from this work.  In the process of all that, the ESRC came back to us about a year and a half ago, and said, \'93Look, there is some extra money\'94.  If we could put in a bid like yesterday, we might get some.  They\rquote 
re coming up to and end of a financial year, and there\rquote s something there which they have to disburse quickly, so we put in.  And my idea was to have a fourth project, where the person would would build a critical bibliography for six months, on 
\'85 the United States, and the
 presence of Caribbean minorities and South Asian minorities there, which would help us in terms of the overall conquering of the critique of the literature, and to build, also, a research project out of that.  So when we were interviewing, we thought 
