1,500, but the Chelsea had had this thing that they would help young people to buy their first premises, a flat or something, so we had a mortgage from them at a very low interest rate, or something like that.  So we borrowed \'a3
9,000 from them, and we had a thousand saved, and we bought a flat for \'a39,000, in North London,
 in the Crouch End area, and spent a thousand pounds modernising it, and had a home.  That was a Godsend, in a way. Because the following year we then had, as I finished my doctorate, as I was just finishing, both of us were offered jobs in Tanzania and i
n Guyana, in the universities \endash 
 Politics and Law.  But we decided, well, Selina wanted to go to Guyana, and Walter Rodney, who had just returned from Tanzania, who had been offered the Chair of History in Guyana, but Burnham, the President, refused to let h
im take it up, and it was a big cause celebre at the time.  But Walter said, \'93Look, you should come to Guyana, he\rquote s going to launch a new political party, he\rquote s going to [fight] against the racism of the place and so forth and so on\'94
, and as a historian and a person whom I admired, I thought, \'93Fine, but I think I\rquote d rather go to Tanzania\'94
.  But Selina wanted to go there, so I won that, and we went to Tanzania for that period.  So in terms of family life, as soon as we were there, after about a year and a half
 or so, Hugh was born, and then very soon after Neil.  The separation between them 19 months, so we had, we end up with two sons, which was a great disappointment for me \endash  in terms of having two sons \endash 
 I expected the second to have been a girl!  I\rquote ve told him so, that his first child had better be recompense!  (LAUGHS)  But in my family, both of my brothers have sons and sons and sons, so we thought, \'93Well, there\rquote 
s no point in trying for any more, it\rquote ll just be more sons!\'94 Then we went off to Jamaica, and, of course, you\rquote 
re familiar with how we tried to get back here.  Got back here, and I felt, once we settled back in Britain, that basically we had travelled far and wide enough.  When we went to Tanzania, we thought we understood the world.  We were married
 when we were 24, and we went to Tanzania when I was 26, and when I came back here from Jamaica, I was 35/36, I felt I\rquote 
d had a full life!  (LAUGHS)  I remember having a discussion in Mexico, at a conference in Mexico, and one of the key speakers there was a man called Ali Mazuri. He\rquote s regarded as one of Africa\rquote 
s most prominent intellectuals.  He was the first black person to have given the Reith Lectures, way back in the early eighties/late seventies, and he\rquote s just a wonderful person to talk with.  He\rquote s ver
y buoyant and full of life and humour, and he\rquote s a big intellectual, he\rquote s just one of those wonderful figures, and him saying to me, \'93Well, 35/36 is a good age\'94.  (LAUGHS)  He was reflecting on his own life.  He said, \'93It\rquote 
s a great age\'94.  But when I came ba
ck, I felt that we were pretty old.  But by then, I think, in British academic life, things were changing, people were doing their doctorates later, people were not in the rush, I think, as people in our generations were.  Did you get that impression of y
our generation?  If you were going to do a doctorate, or write something, by the time you\rquote re in mid-twenties, you feel fairly old, whereas nowadays, you come across young people who, at 34, 35, they still feel that they\rquote 
re young.  You know, by the age of 29, I\rquote 
d had both kids, and felt too old to want to have any more!  (LAUGHS)  But sometimes we regret that.  Sometimes we feel we ought to have had a third.  We certainly felt that we should not just have one, rather, because observing \endash  I might be wrong 
\endash  but looking at families in which there\rquote s just one, is the feel that the child must be a bit lonely, or too much attention, and that it\rquote s just good to have two or more.
