\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 You were saying, when we broke earlier, that coming back from Jamaica was quite difficult, from the point of view of the children.  Do you remember saying that?
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid11671488 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri113\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin113\lin1871\itap0\pararsid6571465 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid6571465\charrsid6571465 Harry:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 Yes.  It was difficult in that, in terms of education, because one of the reasons \endash  not the sole reason \endash  but one of the reasons was to ensure that we put them in a schoo
l which was a regular ordinary, non-elitist sort of school.  Selina had gone to a boarding school in Kenya, and she didn\rquote t like it, and I\rquote 
ve always thought a boarding school is not quite the thing anyway.  But, nonetheless, we wanted them to have a good education, because that\rquote s the only thing, what we would call, today, \'93social capital\'94, that\rquote 
s the only thing they would have.  And as black kids, if they\rquote re going to live in Britain, if you don\rquote t have an education, where are you going to get to?  You won\rquote t h
ave a second chance.  That seemed to us, irrespective of our politics, to be paramount.  So after a year in the state sector, we decided that we should find a school for them outside.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid11671488 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri113\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin113\lin1871\itap0\pararsid6571465 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid6571465\charrsid6571465 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 What was the problem? 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid11671488 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri113\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin113\lin1871\itap0\pararsid6571465 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid6571465\charrsid6571465 Harry:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 Well, the problem - we spent a lot
 of time talking with the teachers, but they were obsessed and concerned about happiness of children, which is legitimate and fine, but I think I have an old Caribbean notion about schooling, which is that schooling is not about happiness, schooling is ab
out the three R\rquote s, principally, and the other things that come with that.  It\rquote 
s about acquiring an education.  They were concerned that they should be there to do paintings.  I remember going to one primary school in Coventry, and we were looking around, and the Headmistress spent all her time convincing us that they\rquote 
re aware of cultural differences, and they showed us a lot of painting of black kids, of Asian kids, of instruments from India, and from Africa and the Caribbean and so on, and that they spent a lot of time on these issues.  And we\rquote 
re sitting there absolutely bewildered!  We weren\rquote t sending our children to school for these things!  We wanted to know that if they go there, they\rquote ll be doing maths, they\rquote ll be doing English, they\rquote ll be doing other th
ings related to those subjects.  As I say, it\rquote s an old-fashioned Caribbean sort of attitude, and, I suspect, it\rquote s also an attitude of most middle-class families in this country, that your kids go to school for those things which you can
\rquote t do for them at home you haven\rquote 
t got the time, and the home is not the right place for them, they need to do it in that socialised space of the school.  As for happiness and so on, we can take care of those factors!  (LAUGHS)  We were very disillusioned with that.  They, th
emselves, came home from school and ask us to set us some of the work they used to do in school in Jamaica.  So my younger brother, who was, at that time, was an infant\rquote 
s school teacher, he would come and set them some arithmetic and some English tests, and they were quite happy with that.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid11671488 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri113\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin113\lin1871\itap0\pararsid6571465 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid6571465\charrsid6571465 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 Where was he, then, your brother?
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid11671488 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri113\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin113\lin1871\itap0\pararsid6571465 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid6571465\charrsid6571465 Harry:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 In London.  Yes, yes.  I feel very strongly about this, that people feel that children don\rquote t learn automatically, and I believe that children learn like sponges, like sponges soak up water, that
\rquote s how children learn.  They learn from the things they\rquote re exposed to around them, and it\rquote s not a great effort at all.  Learning is not a great effort if it\rquote s something you\rquote re enjoying and it\rquote 
s there around you.  And certainly our kid
s were like that, and the thing was, then, to have that environment for them.  As for things that they could do at home, they would do.  I felt it was our responsibility to teach them things, introducing them, for example, to music, to cycling was my task
.
  Learning to play football and other things, and those can be done within the context of a family.  But formal learning, they need to learn that at school.  So those were the factors we were very worried about, and why we wanted them to go into an enviro
nment that they would be happy with.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid11671488 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri113\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin113\lin1871\itap0\pararsid6571465 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid6571465\charrsid6571465 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 And where did you send them to school?
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid11671488 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri113\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin113\lin1871\itap0\pararsid9575211 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid6571465\charrsid6571465 Harry:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 Well, as I was saying earlier on, they won places at St. George\rquote s, and we felt that it wouldn\rquote 
t be right for them, as two black kids, the only black kids, I suspect, at the time.  I spoke to a friend and a former teacher at St. George\rquote 
s at Windsor.  His name is Ian Hall, Ian was Head of Music in the school opposite to my school in Peckham, and he w
as one of the few black teachers we knew in those days.  Because my younger sister went to that school, we got to know each other when I was in the sixth form, and he was teaching there.  And since then, he\rquote s a good musician, he\rquote 
s invited me to a number of
 his concerts. Ian went to Bishop Tennyson Grammar School at the Oval.  His parents are from Guyana.  He went to one of the Oxford Colleges, where he claims to be the first black man to have done music there, and so on.  And Ian speaks in a very upper cla
ss voice!  (LAUGHS)  And (LAUGHS) he\rquote s great fun!  But I rung Ian, as a musician, and said, \'93Look, give me your advice about this\'94.  And he said, well, his son had won a place there earlier, and they decided not to send him.  \'93
I should think about it carefully\'94.  And we thought about it carefully, and we thought, \'93Well, the thing to do is just to go back to Coventry\'94
, since I was working at Warwick.  I just found that, it seemed to us that most of the kids, their parents were from the military and from the navy, and that we\rquote re not upper class people, we\rquote 
re ordinary folks.  They would be in a position where, socially, it\rquote s not the right place.  We felt that we would have lost them as people, as individuals, and therefore, what would be better, since we wanted 
them to have a good, sound, formal, grammar-type education, but to have their feet firmly on the ground in a community somewhere, that the thing to do is to sell up our flat in Richmond, buy a decent house in Coventry, and try to get them into what used t
o be the grammar school there.  When the grammar schools were abolished, they went totally into the private sector.  But it\rquote 
s a school started for - I say to Neil, who wants to be a politician, and is determined to get to Parliament, that he can always sell
 himself as the boy who went to the inner city school, which was started under a Charter from Henry VIIIth, and named after him.  For a merchant in Coventry wrote to the King, saying, \'93
There are lots of boys terrorising the streets of Coventry and the good citizens.  Would you give some land?\'94
  This chap would put the money, but could the King give some [land]?  And so some of the land he had confiscated, he gave to this chap to start the school \endash  named after himself, Henry VIIIth.  But it\rquote s fairly much in 
the inner part of the City.  So, as a politician, you know what politicians are today, he can always claim that he went to an inner city school.  It\rquote 
s not very distinguished, but it is a good grammar school.  Just before the boys went there, the year before, I think, Enoch Powell went there and gave a talk, and said, \'93It\rquote 
s still one of the few schools in the country where you could do the Classics\'94.  Up to then, it seemed, you could still do Hebrew as well as Latin and Greek.  So they both went there, and t
hey had a fairly good time.  I think Hugh perhaps less of a good time, in that when he was at school, he was very much a socialite, and wanted to mix with the popular boys, and, of course, we wanted him to do intellectually well.  Which he did well enough
 on, but he\rquote 
s quite a keen sportsman as well, he wanted to be in the cricket team, and he never did make it in, because it seems he was not a friend of the master who was running it.  So he did the right thing, he just took up on his own interest, and he wa
s the only one who took that up, which was to, to do golf, and they provided for him to learn golf.  They were both involved with not only the Cathedral Choir, but with the Music Society.  Neil ended up, they established a Scholarship to celebrate the 400
}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\super\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 th}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 
 anniversary of the School, and they established it in music, and in the sixth form, Neil won that, which paid for half his fees, so he was a music scholar for the School.  He was the only boy who became Head Boy who was not a great sportsman, and I think
 it was his performance intellectually and in music, that he was appointed.  And it was then that he became interested in politics.  Up to then he was keen to be a vet, and he must know every farm in the Midlands and the South West, and in the West, becau
se he had to have lots of experience.  Because in those times \endash  I don\rquote t know if it still is \endash 
 but the most difficult to thing to get into universities for was veterinary medicine, because there are so few places, and only six places that offered it, and he 
only wanted to go to one place, to Cambridge, from he was very small, he wanted to go to Cambridge.  The joke about it, he had to apply to the rest, it was a matter of school rules, and they turned him down at Liverpool, which he thought the weakest, and 
which he wouldn\rquote t even go to at all!  (LAUGHS)  But by then, he had already been accepted at Cambridge anyway.  So he got a place, one of the two places at St. John\rquote s.  I\rquote d always teased him, and said, \'93
Why do you want to waste a good brain, and sing to rich people\rquote s cats and dogs?  And, moreover, if you want to be a politician, do you think cats and dogs are going to vote for you?\'94
  And, literally, on the last day, going to take up this place, in the car, he said, \'93You know, I think you\rquote re right.  I think you\rquote re right\'94.  (LAUGHS)  So, you know, within the year \endash  because they all do a Common First Year 
\endash  he was able to persuade them - they were very angry with him.  But I think because he has something like six A\rquote s at \lquote A\rquote  Level, and he got a Merit, not a Distinction \endash  he was disappointed with that \endash 
 in the College Entry Exam, they were quite willing for him to change.  Intellectually, it wasn\rquote t a challenge in any way, because veterinary medicine seems to be a bit more - I don\rquote t understand these things - it tak
es up more time, more cramming.  Seems to be a cramming discipline!  Hugh went off, he didn\rquote 
t get into Oxford, where he wanted to go to, and if he had waited a year after, when we made some enquiries, they would have been happy at Cambridge.  He didn\rquote t get into Oxford.  But he didn\rquote 
t want to go to the same institution as his younger brother, and he knew that Neil only wanted to go to Cambridge, so he had Durham and Bristol, he went to Bristol, which I was quite pleased about.  But he discovered, there, that
 you could spend a year on the Continent, so he went to Bologna for a year and learnt Italian, which he hadn\rquote 
t done before, and I think that has opened his eyes to the Continent in a very significant way.  So that later on he did a stage at the European Co
mmission, with an intention that, later on, he might go there.  And then he went into the law.  From early years, he thought he would do the law, but because he enjoyed the Classics, we was encouraging him, saying, \'93If that\rquote 
s what you want to do, do that\'94, and he agreed that it\rquote s something you would never do later on, unless you do it at that stage of your school years.  I\rquote 
m quite pleased and proud that I have two fellows who are okay, except for one thing that they now disappoint me in, and that is they won\rquote t have some children!
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid11671488 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 
