\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 Now, tell me, how much of a part do you think moving to the \'93Homestead\'94 played in that, then?
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid11671488 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri113\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin113\lin1871\itap0\pararsid9575211 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid6571465\charrsid6571465 Harry:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 
I think it played a very important part.  And, in fact, it was very deliberately so, because we felt that Hugh, who used to be, at school, a great socialite, as we saw him, that if he stayed in the town, he would end up like some of our neighbours\rquote 
 kids, of wanting to go out and so on and so on.  We felt, well, one of the things in being on the land, a bit out of town - it\rquote s five miles from Coventry City Centre - he\rquote 
ll have to make an effort to come in.  Of course, we wanted to bring them up the way our parents brought us up, namely that you don\rquote t go out!  (LAUGHS)  Well, you do, but you know where you\rquote 
re going to, and you know your bounds.  And in those days, black boys in in British cities always had a rough time with the police, and I wasn\rquote t going to 
be prepared for this.  So when we moved there, they became very proud of the idea of living on a piece of land, and during the vacation times, what Hugh, in particular, would do, he would invite five, six friends, to the homestead.  We had a mini lake, a 
large pond, um, which was big enough to take a small boat.  They\rquote 
d pitch two tents there and stay for a week, and it became a tradition until his second year at university, the Easter break was always the period for pitching the tents.  I think things like 
those meant that there was never any great urge to be part of the big city.  In fact, whenever we came to London for, for anything at all, they hated it!  So it was quite interesting to see, once they were undergraduates, by the third year, they were dete
rmined that they must come to London!  (LAUGHS)  Things had changed!  But I didn\rquote t worry about that, because, by then, they were balanced young people who knew how to cope.  But I would have been worried to have brought them up in a city context.  

\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid11671488 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri113\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin113\lin1871\itap0\pararsid6571465 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid6571465\charrsid6571465 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 And for you, did that take you back to your roots?
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid11671488 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri113\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin113\lin1871\itap0\pararsid9575211 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid6571465\charrsid6571465 Harry:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 It did, yeah.  It was very much part of it.  I\rquote ve always wondered on the miracle, almost, of the transition of pe
ople from India, but particularly the Punjab, but particularly from the Caribbean, like my parents, coming from rural backgrounds, where all their lives, well into adulthood, have lived on the land, and then they come to Britain and they live an industria
l life, an urban life.  So I\rquote ve long had the urge to live on the land.  When we went to Jamaica, we came close to buying a farm outside Kingston, and it was just a matter of accident that we didn\rquote 
t, because we were determined to go and live on the land.  So when we had the opportunity, when we came here, the first farm we looked at, 110 acres, and a really old farmhouse, and we thought, \'93Gosh!  How can we manage this?\'94  Well, we couldn
\rquote t, because we couldn\rquote t raise enough capital for it!  (LAUGHS)  And so that fell through.  Then we forgot about the idea.  And then a couple of years later, we redoubled the effort, and I think I redoubled the effort when I didn\rquote 
t get the Directorship of the Centre, because I felt, \'93Well, if I can\rquote t put my energy there,\'94 - I think I had a lot of energy at the time, and creativity - \'93Let me put it into something else\'94.  So we got this place, and I thought, \'93
Okay, what we want to do is become the biggest goat producers in Britain\'94.  So I had this great plan that there is a big market for, among Southern Europeans, South Asians and Caribbeans, for goat meat, and that we could produce this.  I think it
\rquote s still the case.  Anyone who were to pick up on that, they could find a huge market there.  But you can\rquote t do those sort of things and take it up fully whilst being an academic, and having kids at school and all the rest of it!  And  I
\rquote d taught the boys the basics of horse-riding, but and one of the ideas of having the place, that we would get a couple of horses, but given the amount of 
money and time we were spending (1) on their education, and on their music, because we had to pay quite a bit for each instrument and so on, and for lessons.  One, we didn\rquote t have the money, secondly we didn\rquote 
t have the time.  So the goats was quite a useful thing.  But we got to a point where we were producing milk for quite a lot of people who need goat\rquote s milk for a particular stomach ailment and so on, and after a while, we just couldn\rquote 
t keep it up.  But again, there\rquote s a big market there, I thought, for so
meone to take up.  So it, it did all of us a lot of good.  The only reason, I felt, after what, 14 years or so, that we had done enough.  Selina would still regret it, and would still prefer to be there, because she, too, was brought up in Nairobi, which 
was not as urban as it is now, and they lived on the outskirts, so they\rquote 
re used to having land.  In Goa, the family home there, they have similar to ourselves, land holdings there, not as big, but they have a couple of acres, and people are close to the lan
d, and rural life.  I think it did a lot of good for these fellows.  I suspect, when they come to having families, and hopefully they will, they will want to return to a rural setting, because I think that\rquote 
s a wonderful time for children.  I keep saying that was wonderful when we were young, to have been in London, to live in London, and it\rquote 
s wonderful to be back now, but in between I am very very very pleased that we had that kind of a life.  So in the same way as there was a great urge and a spiritual yearning, if you like, to live in Africa, and to live in Jamaica, I\rquote 
ve released myself from those.  There\rquote s no great urge to.  I can understand, when I meet a number of people like myself, who have never had the opportunity to, and they still have a burning urge to do so.  And I can say, \'93Look, you know, I
\rquote ve done it.  I don\rquote t need to any more\'94.  (LAUGHS)
