\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 So how about your friends?
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid11671488 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri113\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin113\lin1871\itap0\pararsid6571465 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid6571465\charrsid6571465 Harry:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 Friends?  We don\rquote t have a lot of friends, actually, I don\rquote t think, and not geographically based friends either.  I think they\rquote 
re spread out.  In a wide range of countries, whenever Hugh and Neil go travelling, we can give them names of good friends, of people to go and stay with, and a wide range of countries, or parts of the United States, I stay w
ith friends.  I think the best and longest friends seem to have been those we made in Tanzania days, and must have been a very formative period of our lives.  In ki-Swahili there is a saying, \'93You\rquote re as old as your oldest child\'94
, because when you have a child, in the ki-Swahili language is expressed that you - I\rquote m known, for example, as \'93Baba Hugh\'94 \endash  father of Hugh.  Your oldest child, they refer to \'93father of\'94, or \'93mother of\'94
, and the idea is basically, and it\rquote s true, in a sense that you get to know people with the same experience of life.  Whereas now, when I walk down the road, and I see a lot of young families around here, we\rquote 
ve quite a lot of them, we have nothing in common, so we talk, but you don\rquote t establish a relationship, whereas you can see they, t
hemselves, are establishing relationships because they have children of the same age.  So, for example, here, our friends, a lot of them are still up at Warwick.  We have a lot of friends in the United States, in the Caribbean.  Our African friends, they 
don\rquote t write, so we\rquote re more or less cut off, in a sense.  In Continental Europe \endash  in France, and Italy, a couple.  But they\rquote re distributed.  So around here, I can\rquote t get up now and walk to a friend\rquote 
s house.  And friends in London are quite a long way - I think you\rquote re the closest, actually!  (LAUGHS)  Yes, of all the friends, I think you are the nearest!
