\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 Quite a lot.  More with Selina\rquote s family.  In the early phase of our, of our family life, the 
first half, I suppose, it was much more my family, both here in London and when we went, when we worked in Jamaica.  In the last 15, 10/15 years, it\rquote s much more her side of the family.  It\rquote 
s partly because our kids are, in terms of age group, are approximate in age to her siblings\rquote  children, whereas my siblings\rquote  children are much much older.  There\rquote 
s one, my youngest brother, his kids are very very much younger.  But, and I think might perhaps have something to do with it, though they themselves don\rquote t keep so much in touch now.  But we feel that it\rquote 
s our sort of responsibility to go to India from time to time, and we don\rquote t just go and come back, we like to stay a couple of weeks.  We don\rquote t stay there all the time either, we travel around, and so we get a hol
iday in, but basically to see people.  Then to Jamaica, my brother who returned there about 15 years ago, he wanted to return whilst he was young enough to establish a friendship, because he wasn\rquote 
t returning to where we were from, but to stay in Kingston, and he\rquote s done that, he\rquote s been very successful in that.  And we\rquote ve been promising, for some time, to go now.  But, fortunately, they\rquote 
ve been coming this side.  My family in this country, we keep in touch in a very formal kind of a way.  Whereas when the boys were younger, we had far more events to which people turned up at.  But it\rquote 
s over a year now, since we had a big family doo-dah in Ipswich, and it was because my brother from Kingston was visiting, and he has sons who live in Ipswich, so it was organised.  We thought of it here, but then they said, \'93
Look, you know how noisy we are!  The place is big enough, but you need open space!\'94  And there is a place where one of his sons, has two houses, and then a car port which comes in for both houses, and a huge 
garden, so they just take over the space, which was fine.  But I would say that, in our generation, the way our families were close when, when our parents were around, is not as close.  One of my worries, well, it\rquote 
s not a worry any more, but one of my suspicions, is that in the next generation, our children\rquote s generation, they\rquote 
ll be completely cut off, I think.  This is something I remember discussing with Mary, at a personal level, in terms of her children and her wider family, and she was making the same point that, in a sense, they\rquote 
re cut off.  I think it will be so, our children will be cut of from their Indian side, and also from our side, and I think friendship - they seem to be much closer to their friends.  And in family studies, this interest now in 
friendships, which is something I had observed with Caribbean families, that it is probably a much wider phenomenon that I\rquote 
m describing, but it is, it is becoming very important. I used to ask Hugh and Neil, who used to talk so much about their school friends, how many of their school friends they\rquote 
re still in touch with?  And not very many.  Hugh is in touch with one - we had bought a flat for Hugh when, about four years back, in Leytonstone, which we later on got into his name, got him to take charge of it
.  And he shared that with one of his friends from schooldays, he\rquote s rather like your son, Stephen, he didn\rquote 
t do Chinese, he did Japanese, a five year course at Oxford, in Japanese, and now works in the City.  So he lived there with Hugh for a couple of yea
rs, and then another person joined him.  But now Hugh is living on his own.  But the point about that is that most of their friends are friends since university days, particularly with Neil.  It seems to be a Cambridge disease where they just stick togeth
er.  I remember when Neil was sharing my flat with me, and he said he had some friends around for his girlfriend\rquote s birthday, and apart from one kid, all of them were from the same year in Cambridge.  Something must be wrong with that!  It\rquote 
s just crazy!  And they\rquote re nearly all medics!   (LAUGHS)  That\rquote s true!  All medics!  There was one banker amongst them!  (LAUGHS)  \tab But yeah, I think friendships, and certainly our cousins in the United States, whom I\rquote 
m in touch with, their kids are not.  They\rquote ve met, a cou
ple of times, our children, but they have no link with them.  So I think, in terms of families- I think I made this remark to you some time back, or perhaps I think it was at your seminar at the Institute \endash 
 that the remarkable thing about families, the mor
e usual thing roundabout families is that there is a tendency of breakage, of outward movement, mm?  So after a while, the remarkable thing is, some families, obviously, special circumstances, keep in touch, and over a long period of time.  But outside of
 Royal Families, and stinkingly rich families, they\rquote re always breaking outwards and moving away.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11671488 
