\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11671488\charrsid7427796 That\rquote s right, yes.  And that\rquote s true, isn\rquote t it!  It\rquote s the way of things.  I\rquote 
m beginning to meet people in Britain, I had a phone call from a woman who is a student at Middlesex, she said she\rquote s writing a paper on something to do with race relations in Britain, a student, and she saw my name, and she doesn\rquote 
t know me, but the fact that the name is spelt the same way, I must be related, because it\rquote s the same name!  (LAUGHS)  Which is true, but I don\rquote t know who she is, and she didn\rquote t know who I am.  It\rquote 
s a kind of a name where, if it\rquote s spelt the same way, you know you must be related, because it\rquote 
s an unusual name. I remember, it was funny, when we went to Jamaica, and we went to pick up our car, going, going through the process of the paperwork and so on, at the counter, the clerk called for \'93Goulbourne\'94, and two of us walked fo
rward.  And then we looked at each other (LAUGHS) quite taken aback!  (LAUGHS)  We said nothing to each other!  (LAUGHS)  What came to my mind was what my father had said, "These brown-cum-whites Jamaicans, we don\rquote 
t have anything to do with them", and he was one of that type, you know!  (LAUGHS) Then, in India, where we were staying at Selina\rquote s family home, Selina\rquote 
s sister-in-law had a visitor from schooldays, staying for a couple of weeks, and she was telling me, she showed me a piece in one of the Indian 
journals, that the person who had done the longest jump this year, was a woman name of Goulbourne, from Kingston.  So she said, \'93Is she, is she a relative?\'94  And I said, \'93I\rquote ve no idea!\'94
  (LAUGHS)  But I suspect that that will most certainly happen.  And if it\rquote s happening in this country, then it happened a long time ago in, in Jamaica.
